\begin_body

\begin_layout Part
Quantum Physics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Optics systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cavities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Detuned Fabry-Perot
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Deuned Fabry-Perot Hamiltonian approach
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the optomechanical limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(also called 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
strawman system
\end_layout

\end_inset

strawman system)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Problem setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the setup shown in the figure: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cavity problem.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cavity setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We will treat the outside environment as a continuum field, This is reasonable
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k=2\pi/L$
\end_inset

 and when 
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inside the cavity, say we have only 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 mode.
 Although other modes do indeed exist, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k=2\pi/d$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the length of the cavity, which is small - on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m to meters.
 Hence, we expect that the energy separation between different modes to
 be large.
 Indeed, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=ck$
\end_inset

 and the minimum energy in each is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have been Tayloring expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\Omega\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 This will turn out to give the accurate result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 be the frequency of the mechanical system that we will be investigating.
 Optomechanical people consider the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 In their case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}\sim hz-Mhz$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the intrinsic frequency of the mechanical system that we are probing
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\sim d/c\sim10^{-8}-10^{-10}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the length of the cavity, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, one can use the `
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hamiltonian approach
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (which is tailored to one Hamiltonian) to derive the input-output relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hamiltonian is (note that we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 because it turns out to give easier equations of motion than 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

; indeed, remember that the HO can also be described with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}^{\dagger}\hat{b}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}=\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\omega_{c}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have picked the negative sign because the positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x-$
\end_inset

axis is to the right*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We picked the negative sign (positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis is to the right) because as we stretch the cavity it loses energy
 (say 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 photons in the system, and you stretch the cavity length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 adiabatically the number of photons is conserved and energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\hbar\omega n$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\propto1/L$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\propto k$
\end_inset

) decreases with increasing length; note: if this is done adiabatically,
 then the number of photons not necessarily conserved and we might have
 photon creation: see 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename sudden change potential.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A sudden-non-adiabatic change in the potential can lead to the creation
 of new quanta
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\equiv\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 gives us the number of photons in the cavity, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}=\omega_{c}/d=k/\left(d/c\right)$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $c=\omega/k$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=kc$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{0}=\frac{\omega}{d}=\frac{kc}{d}=\frac{k}{\left(d/c\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the length of the cavity and where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the coupling constant 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}=\omega_{c}/d$
\end_inset

 (the value of the coupling constant will be motivated later on with two
 approaches).
 The Hamiltonian can also be written in the following form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{H} & = & \frac{P^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\omega_{c}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hat{x}.\frac{\hat{N}\hbar\vec{k}}{\tau}\label{eq:eqTemp}\\
 & = & \frac{P^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\omega_{c}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}=k/\left(d/c\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=d/c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\equiv d/c$
\end_inset

 is the photon travel time from one end of the mirror to the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Interpretation of the radiation pressure force term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\hbar\vec{k}/\tau$
\end_inset

 is like 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\hat{P}/\tau\sim\Delta P/\Delta T=\mbox{Force}\equiv\hat{F}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar k$
\end_inset

 is the momentum carried by one photon
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We also have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\hbar\vec{k}/\tau$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\hbar G_{0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 (unit vector along 
\begin_inset Formula $+x$
\end_inset

 direction) is aligned with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{k}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If they are aligned then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}.\vec{k}=\hat{x}k$
\end_inset

.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\omega_{c}/c$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\hat{N}\hbar\vec{k}}{\tau}=\hat{N}\hbar\frac{\omega_{c}}{c}\frac{c}{d}=\hat{N}\hbar\frac{\omega_{c}}{d}=\hat{N}\hbar G_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}.\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted to be the work done to move the oscillator (We only
 could have gotten this result if 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}=\omega_{c}/d$
\end_inset

).
 This way of viewing the interaction Hamiltonian can be intuitively explained
 with the statement: When the mirror changes its position, the energy in
 the field changes, and this change in the energy can give us the work,
 and so the force applied on the mirror.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also take a different viewpoint by rewriting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{c}\hat{N}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{N}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hbar\omega_{c}\hat{N}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{N}=\hbar\omega_{c}\left(1-\frac{\hat{x}}{d}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we view the motion of the mirror as disturbing the cavity field: it
 detunes it.
 This is like parametric coupling.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}/d$
\end_inset

 is small then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hbar\omega_{c}\left(1-\frac{\hat{x}}{d}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}\approx\hbar\omega_{c}\frac{d}{d+\hat{x}}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\equiv d$
\end_inset

.
 We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{L}{L+\hat{x}} & = & \frac{L}{L\left(1+\hat{x}/L\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+\hat{x}/L}\\
 & \approx & 1-\frac{\hat{x}}{L}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this interaction term could have also been derived differently:
 Write the Hamiltonian as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega\left(\hat{x}\right)a^{\dagger}a$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(\hat{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 defines the resonance condition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is some set of quantum operators that define your cavity.
 Specifically, say we have a cavity of length 
\begin_inset Formula $L=d+\hat{x}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}=2\pi n/d$
\end_inset

, then the resonance condition is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\omega\left(x\right) & = & \frac{2\pi n}{L=\left(d+\hat{x}\right)}c\\
 & = & \frac{2\pi n}{d\left(1+\hat{x}/d\right)}c\\
 & = & \frac{2\pi n}{d}c\frac{1}{\left(1+\hat{x}/d\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{\omega_{c}}{\left(1+\hat{x}/d\right)}\\
 & \approx & \omega_{c}\left(1-\frac{\hat{x}}{d}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

as expected.
 Moreover, notice that this derivation gives us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{G_{0}=\omega_{c}/d}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Adding the input and output fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now add the input and output fields: if the mirror has finite transmittance
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, then it couples with the external environment.
 Add to the Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{2}=i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we are in the interaction picture for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}$
\end_inset

 (so we do not add 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{in}\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{in}$
\end_inset

 to the total Hamiltonian).
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the laser frequency and so 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\omega_{0}t}$
\end_inset

 factors out the fast time dependence (other frequencies still exist in
 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{iH_{0,in}t}$
\end_inset

,where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0,in}=\int dk\omega_{k}a_{k}^{\dagger}a_{k}$
\end_inset

, but they do not play a big role if the input field is a laser; because
 of this 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}$
\end_inset

 will have some time dependence in it).
 In addition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{T}{4\left(d/c\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is of dimension of frequency and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 has units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Hz}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}$
\end_inset

 must have dimensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Hz}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is dimensionless.
 This can be explained by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]=\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(this commutation relation comes from the two photon formalism) 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(t\right)\sim1/\Delta t$
\end_inset

 which has units of 
\begin_inset Formula $Hz$
\end_inset

.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right] & = & 1\\
\left[x,p\right] & = & i\hbar\\
\left[x,a\right] & = & \left[p,a\right]=0.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Rigorously, we must have the interaction term is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\int dka_{in}^{\dagger}\left(k\right)a & = & \int dke^{ik\left(x=0\right)}a_{in}^{\dagger}\left(k\right)a\\
 & = & a_{in}^{\dagger}\left(x=0\right)a\label{eq:ainRigorous}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

more rigorous details about this can be found in Quantum optics by Milburn
 (the section on input-output formalism) , which itself cites a long rigorous
 paper by Gardiner; there is also a rigorous treatment in single photon
 optomechanics paper by ting and huan: 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://arxiv.org/abs/1110.3348
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have to add a heat bath.
 This is not usually done explicitly, as interactions with a thermal bath
 is a very well understood problem.
 When dealing with Heisenberg equations of motion, a noise term is introduced
 (like the quantum Langevin equations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Moving into the interaction picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next is to move into another 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interaction picture
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=H_{0}+H_{I},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
H_{0} & = & \hbar\omega_{0}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}\\
H_{I} & = & \frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+\\
 &  & i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

We obtain that, in this new picture, the total Hamiltonian is given by*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:interactionHI"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
H_{I,SI} & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)H_{SI}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{SI}$
\end_inset

 most the terms will be unaffected because they live in a different Hilbert
 space than 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The terms that will be affected will be the following, with 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}=\exp\left(i\omega_{0}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}t\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\xi & \equiv & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\left\{ \hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right)\right\} U_{0}\left(t\right)\\
 & = & \hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega_{0}t}U_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}U_{0}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega_{0}t}U_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}^{\dagger}U_{0}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We have that, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}U_{0} & = & \hat{a}e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\\
U_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}^{\dagger}U_{0} & = & \hat{a}^{\dagger}e^{i\omega_{0}t}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:usefulExpN"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-i\omega_{0}t$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi=\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{H_{I,int}=\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
H_{I,int} & = & \frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).\label{eq:totalHamiltonianAfterInteractionPicture}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Simple Equations of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Heisenberg equations of motion are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}A=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H,A\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 EOM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{x}=\frac{\hat{P}}{m},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (remember that we are working in the interaction picture)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{I,int}=\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
-i\frac{d}{dt}\hat{x} & = & \frac{1}{\hbar}\left[H_{I,int},\hat{x}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\hbar}\left[\frac{P^{2}}{2m},\hat{x}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2m\hbar}2\hat{P}\left[\hat{P},\hat{x}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{-i\hbar}{m\hbar}\hat{P}=\frac{-i}{m}\hat{P}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where in the third equality, we used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:generalCommutatorFunction"

\end_inset

 and we used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{P},\hat{x}\right]=-i\hbar\hat{I}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:commutationPX"

\end_inset

).
 We hence obtain that
\end_layout

\end_inset

as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 EOM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{p}=\hbar G_{0}\hat{N}-m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (remember that we are working in the interaction picture)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{I,int}=\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
-i\frac{d}{dt}\hat{p} & = & \frac{1}{\hbar}\left[H_{I,int},\hat{p}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\hbar}m\omega_{m}^{2}\left[\hat{x}^{2},\hat{p}\right]-G_{0}\left[\hat{x},\hat{p}\right]\hat{N}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\hbar}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}\left[\hat{x},\hat{p}\right]-i\hbar G_{0}\hat{N}\\
 & = & im\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}-i\hbar G_{0}\hat{N},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where in the third equality, we used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:generalCommutatorFunction"

\end_inset

 and we used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{x},\hat{P}\right]=i\hbar\hat{I}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:commutationXP"

\end_inset

).
 We hence obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{p}=\hbar G_{0}\hat{N}-m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

which is what we would expect: 
\begin_inset Formula $-m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spring
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force term*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a SHO, we have that the resonance frequency is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{m}^{2}=\sqrt{K/m},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $m\omega_{m}^{2}=K$
\end_inset

, as wanted.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar G_{0}\hat{N}$
\end_inset

 is the radiation force term (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eqTemp"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 EOM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{a}=i\left(-\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}+G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}\right)+\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}_{in},.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (remember that we are working in the interaction picture)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{I,int}=\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{m}^{2}\hat{x}^{2}+\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\hat{a}+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{a} & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H_{I,int},\hat{a}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left(\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\left[\hat{N},\hat{a}\right]-\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}\left[\hat{N},\hat{a}\right]+i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left[\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger},\hat{a}\right]\right)\\
 & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left(-\hbar\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)a+\hbar G_{0}\hat{x}a-i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}_{in}\right)\\
 & = & i\left(-\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}\right)\hat{a}+G_{0}\hat{x}\hat{a}\right)+\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}_{in},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[N=a^{\dagger}a,a\right]=-a$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:Na_commutation_relation"

\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,a^{\dagger}a\right]=a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{out}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output field is not independent of the input field.
 Indeed, it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)\equiv-\limit{\Delta t}0\hat{a}_{in}\left(t+\Delta t\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the minus sign is the phase change due to the interaction with the
 mirror.
 In out model, at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the input field interacts with the cavity field and with the mirror.
 Hence, at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{+}$
\end_inset

, which would denote the time right after that the input field interacts
 with the cavity field and with the mirror (again this happens at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

), the output field emerges.
 (more explanation: *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider the simple model of a perfectly reflecting mirror (so that the
 input field does not interact with the cavity field), then the output field
 time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, will simply be the reflected field at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}\left(t,x=0\right)$
\end_inset

 (remember that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}$
\end_inset

 that appears in the Hamiltonian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{in}\left(x=0\right)$
\end_inset

; see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ainRigorous"

\end_inset

).
 Right after being reflected, the field travels slightly to give us 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{out}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 This can also be understood with the following diagram: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename spacetime diagram of reflection from mirror.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Space-time diagram of the output field, in the simple setup of a perfectly
 reflecting mirror.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another possible way of visualizing what has been said is to draw the output
 field as exiting to the right: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename representation2OutputField.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this picture, we take the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 So the output field is simply related to the input field in that it is
 the input field at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Hence, we can write that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)=-e^{iH\delta t/\hbar}\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-iH\delta t/\hbar},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=e^{iH\delta t}$
\end_inset

 is the time evolution operator that will evolve a Heisenberg operator in
 time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equation of motion for
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{out}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)=-\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)+\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}\left(t\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{out}\left(t+\delta t\right)=\limit{\Delta t}0\hat{a}_{in}\left(t+\delta t-\Delta t\right)=\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

) using the interaction picture Hamiltonian (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:totalHamiltonianAfterInteractionPicture"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & -\frac{d}{dt}\hat{a}_{out}\left(t-\delta t\right)\\
 & = & -\lim_{\Delta t\rightarrow0}\frac{\hat{a}_{out}\left(t-\delta t+\Delta t\right)-\hat{a}_{out}\left(t-\delta t\right)}{\Delta t}=-\lim_{\Delta t\rightarrow0}\frac{\hat{a}_{out}\left(t-\delta t+\Delta t\right)+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)}{\Delta t}\\
 & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H_{I}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H_{I}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\\
 & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\left[\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\hat{a}+\left[\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right)\\
 & \approx- & \sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\left[\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\hat{a}+\left[\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right)\\
 & = & -\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}\delta\left(0\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\delta\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fishyDeltaZero"

\end_inset

), we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
-\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)-\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & -\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}\\
\implies\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & +\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ANOTHER BETTER APPROACH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The better approach is to use 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)=-\lim_{\delta t\rightarrow0}e^{iH\delta t/\hbar}\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-iH\delta t/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 because the differential equation approach only works if the Hamiltonian
 is time-independent (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:InteractionPicture"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (for brevity letting 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{I}\left(t\right)\equiv H$
\end_inset

) (the minus sign is due to the phase factor picked up due to the interaction
 with the mirror) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
-\hat{a}_{out}\left(t\right)=\hat{a}_{in}\left(t+\delta t\right) & = & e^{iH\delta t/\hbar}\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)e^{-iH\delta t/\hbar}\\
 & \approx & \left(1+i\frac{H\delta t}{\hbar}\right)\hat{a}_{in}\left(1-i\frac{H\delta t}{\hbar}\right)+O\left(\delta t^{2}\right)\\
 & = & \hat{a}_{in}+i\frac{\delta t}{\hbar}H\hat{a}_{in}-i\frac{\delta t}{\hbar}\hat{a}_{in}H+O\left(\delta t^{2}\right)\\
 & \approx & \hat{a}_{in}+i\frac{\delta t}{\hbar}\left[H,\hat{a}_{in}\right]\\
 & = & \hat{a}_{in}+i\frac{\delta t}{\hbar}\left[i\hbar\sqrt{\gamma}\left(-\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a}+\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right),\hat{a}_{in}\right]\\
 & = & \hat{a}_{in}+\delta t\sqrt{\gamma}\left[\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{a},\hat{a}_{in}\right]=1+\delta t\sqrt{\gamma}\left[\hat{a}_{in}^{\dagger}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{in}\left(t\right)\right]\hat{a}\\
 & = & \hat{a}_{in}-\delta t\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a}\delta\left(0\right)=\hat{a}_{in}-\sqrt{\gamma}\hat{a},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(0\right)\delta t=1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:aadaggerCommutationrelation"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]=I.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

