Optics Devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Beamsplitter"

\end_inset

Beam splitter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Beam Splitter Input-output relations"
target "http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~howell/mysite2/Tutorials/Beamsplitter2.pdf"

\end_inset

: More geared towards quantum optics of a single photon + matrix approach
 to classical optics beam splitter 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Beam Splitter Input-output relations"
target "C:\\Users\\Bass\\Documents\\Research\\Learning Material\\Optics\\Beamsplitter.pdf"
type "file:"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum mechanics of beam splitters: see section 6.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gerryQO"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mandel treatment of the beam-splitter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename quantumBeamSplitter.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:qunatum beamsplitter"

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Work with the layout presented in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:qunatum beamsplitter"

\end_inset

.
 The input fields satisfy the normal bosonic operators' commutation relations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{a}_{i},\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\right] & = & 1\; i=1,2.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Use the scattering matrix of a beam splitter (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Classical-Beam-splitter"

\end_inset

) to relate the output fields to the input fields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{2} & = & t^{'}\hat{a}_{0}+r\hat{a}_{1}\\
\hat{a}_{3} & = & r^{'}\hat{a}_{0}+t\hat{a}_{1}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{0}$
\end_inset

 are independent fields (and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{a}_{0},\hat{a}_{1}^{\dagger}\right]=0$
\end_inset

) and the above relations, we can obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[a_{2},a_{2}^{\dagger}\right] & = & \left[a_{3},a_{3}^{\dagger}\right]=0\\
\left[a_{2},a_{3}^{\dagger}\right] & = & 0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We can also calculate the photon number operators to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{n}_{2} & = & \left|t\right|^{2}\hat{n}_{0}+\left|r\right|^{2}\hat{n}_{1}+t^{'*}r\hat{a}_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{1}+r^{*}t^{'}\hat{a}_{1}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{0}\label{eq:QuantumBSphotonconservation}\\
\hat{n}_{3} & = & \left|r\right|^{2}\hat{n}_{0}+\left|t\right|^{2}\hat{n}_{1}+r^{'*}t\hat{a}_{0}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{1}+t^{*}r^{'}\hat{a}_{1}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{0}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and by use of the reciprocity relations (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:StokesReciprocityRelations"

\end_inset

), we can obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{n}_{2}+\hat{n}_{3} & = & \hat{n}_{0}+\hat{n}_{1},\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is a statement of the conservation of photons between the inputs and
 the outputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Exhaustive quantum-mechanical treatment of a beam-splitter including its
 use in a michelson interferometer is given in section 12.12.0-4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Photon correlations with a vacuum field in one of the ports of the beam-splitter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the field in mode 0 is the vacuum and denote the total state
 of the input field by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{a}_{0}\hat{\rho}_{0} & = & \hat{\rho}\hat{a}_{0}^{\dagger}=0\label{eq:consequenceVaccumField}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 and with the help of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumBSphotonconservation"

\end_inset

, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \hat{n}_{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left|r\right|^{2}\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}\right\rangle \quad\left\langle \hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle =\left|t\right|^{2}\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}\right\rangle ,\label{eq:outputNumbersQBS}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which is consistent with the classical input-output relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A non-classical result can be obtained by looking at the correlations between
 the output beams 2 and 3: Suppose that there are photodetectors placed
 at the 2 exit ports 2 and 3 then the probability that both of them will
 detect a photon is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{23} & = & \left\langle :\hat{n}_{2}\hat{n}_{3}:\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle \hat{n}_{2}\hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The first equality follows from the relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:probNphotodetectors"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 and plane waves and setting the quantum efficiency to unity.
 the second equality follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 commute as was stated earlier .
\end_layout

\end_inset

This can be calculated to be, with the help of Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumBSphotonconservation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:consequenceVaccumField"

\end_inset

 and the fact that the fields 0 and 1 are independent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{23} & = & \left|r\right|^{2}\left|t\right|^{2}\left[\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}\right\rangle \right]\label{eq:ouputProbDetected}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{n}_{2}\hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 IFF 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the field consists 1 photon*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \sum p_{i}\ket{1_{i}}\bra{1_{i}}\\
\implies Tr\left(\rho n\right) & = & \sum p_{i}=1\\
\mbox{and }Tr\left(\rho n^{2}\right) & = & \sum p_{i}=1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which would entail that it is impossible to detect a photon in both the
 reflected and transmitted beam (because 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{23}=0$
\end_inset

) if we have a 1 photon state - a non-classical behavior*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Classically we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle I_{transmitted}I_{reflected}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 IFF both fields vanish
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another non-classical behavior can be obtained by looking at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \Delta\hat{n}_{2}\Delta\hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \hat{n}_{2}\hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle -\left\langle \hat{n}_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left|r\right|^{2}\left|t\right|^{2}\left[\left\langle \left(\Delta\hat{n}_{1}\right)^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \hat{n}_{1}\right\rangle \right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The first equality follows from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \Delta\hat{n}_{2}\Delta\hat{n}_{3}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \left(n_{2}-\left\langle n_{2}\right\rangle \right)\left(n_{3}-\left\langle n_{3}\right\rangle \right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle n_{2}n_{3}\right\rangle -\left\langle n_{2}\left\langle n_{3}\right\rangle \right\rangle -\left\langle \left\langle n_{2}\right\rangle n_{3}\right\rangle +\left\langle n_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle n_{3}\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The second equality follows directly from Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputNumbersQBS"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ouputProbDetected"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Hence, for subpoissonian statistics, we have negative correlations between
 the fluctuations of the transmitted (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{3}$
\end_inset

) and reflected beams (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 For a coherent state, the correlations are equal to zero (use Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:photonStatisticsCoherentState"

\end_inset

).
 When the correlation between output 2 and 3 is positive, the phenomenon
 is then known as the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hanbury Brown-Twiss effect
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\emph on
Hanbury Brown-Twiss 
\emph default
effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 12.12.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
2 Photon interference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume now that the input field is given by the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1_{0},1_{1}}$
\end_inset

 then using Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumBSphotonconservation"

\end_inset

, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{23} & = & \left(\left|t\right|^{2}-\left|r\right|^{2}\right)^{2},\label{eq:blah}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which vanishes for a 50%:50% beam-splitter.
 
\emph on
This is also called the Hong–Ou–Mandel effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

This can be understood as follows.
 There are 2 different ways in which the situation with one photon exiting
 at port 2 and one photon exiting at port 3 can arise:either both incident
 photons are transmitted through the BS or both are reflected from the BS.
 As the detectors observing the output cannot distinguish between these
 possibilities, the corresponding two-photon probability amplitudes must
 be added before squaring to determine the probability.
 But because of the phase shifts on reflection and transmission, the two
 probability amplitudes are exactly 180 degrees out of phase*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
such a beam splitter has a scattering matrix of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 (From wikipedia http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hong%E2%80%93Ou%E2%80%93Mandel_effec
t), so that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and the final state looks like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\ket{rr}-\ket{tt}\right) & = & \ket{final}\\
\implies probability & = & \left|\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)^{2}\braket{tt|final}+\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)^{2}\braket{rr|final}\right|^{2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the probability amplitude that both photons are either reflected or
 transmitted, then for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{tt|final}$
\end_inset

 is the probability amplitude that both photons are measured when they are
 both transmitted.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 12.12.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Effect of a polarizer on a quantum field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section 12.13 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Single Mode laser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The light emitted by a single mode laser can be modeled by a by a mixture
 of coherent states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{v=r_{0}e^{i\theta}}$
\end_inset

 having the same value 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 but with the phases 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 uniformly distributed over the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,2\pi\right]$
\end_inset

.
 (From section 11.8.6 - (b): 
\emph on
The randomly phased laser model 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Simple-analysis-of single mode laser"

\end_inset

Simple analysis of the light emitted by a Single Mode laser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this simple treatment of the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
single mode laser
\end_layout

\end_inset

single mode laser, we will assume that it emits light described by the coherent
 state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\xi}$
\end_inset

 with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is real.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write down the electric field in the following fashion: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & = & \mathcal{C}_{0}\left(\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right)\\
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\\
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}=\sqrt{\left(4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}\right)/\mathcal{A}c}$
\end_inset

 being a constant (see Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eqeQuadratures2photonformalism"

\end_inset

).
 Apply the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}\rightarrow\hat{D}^{\dagger}\left(\alpha\right)\hat{O}\hat{D}\left(\alpha\right)$
\end_inset

 which leaves the physics invariant (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:The-displacement-transformation"

\end_inset

).
 Under this transformation, (using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{\omega},a_{\omega^{'}}^{\dagger}\right]=2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{D}^{\dagger}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\hat{a}_{\Omega}\hat{D}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right) & = & \hat{a}_{\Omega}+\alpha\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{D}^{\dagger}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\hat{a}_{\Omega}^{\dagger}\hat{D}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right) & = & \hat{a}_{\Omega}^{\dagger}+\alpha^{*}\left(\Omega\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general displacement transformation"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=1/2\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\omega\right)=c_{1}\bar{a}\delta\left(\omega-\omega_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a constant*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Turns out that this form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 results in the desired form of the electric field
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Applying this transformation to the electric field operator, we obtain
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right) & \rightarrow & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}+\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}\label{eq:transformed electric fields}\\
 & \equiv & \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)+\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}\\
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right) & \rightarrow & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\nonumber \\
 & \equiv & \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{+}+\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{\sqrt{2}}\approx\frac{\hat{a}_{+}+\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{\sqrt{2}}\\
 & \rightarrow & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}+\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{\dagger}+\alpha_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}+\alpha_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{*}\right)=\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+\sqrt{2}c_{1}\bar{a}\delta\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used the fact that the laser has no sidebands (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}\approx1$
\end_inset

- see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defLambda2photonFormalism"

\end_inset

) and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 is real.
 And so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\\
 & \rightarrow & \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)+\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Similarly, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{+}-\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}\approx\frac{\hat{a}_{+}-\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}\\
 & \rightarrow & \frac{1}{i\sqrt{2}}\left(\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}-\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}+\alpha_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}-\alpha_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{*}\right)=\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{s}$
\end_inset

 remains invariant under the transformation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

where it is convenient to pick 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & \rightarrow & \mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\left(\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right].\label{eq:singleModeLaserElectricField}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & 0\label{eq:expectations quadratures 1mode laser}\\
\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & 0.\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Note that the new (denoting the state of light by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\alpha\right\rangle $
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\right\rangle  & = & \bar{a}=\left\langle \psi\left|\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\right|\psi\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle \psi|D\left(D^{\dagger}\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,transformed}D\right)D^{\dagger}|\psi\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle \psi_{transformed}\left|\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,transformed}\right|\psi_{transformed}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle \psi_{transformed}|\left(\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,afterTransformation}\right)|\psi_{transformed}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \bar{a}+\left\langle \psi_{transformed}|\left(\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,afterTransformation}\right)|\psi_{transformed}\right\rangle =\bar{a}+\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,afterTransformation}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \bar{a}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,afterTransformation}\right\rangle  & = & 0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Moreover, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\left|\xi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\xi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is a coherent state and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is real, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\right\rangle  & \approx & \left\langle \frac{\hat{a}_{+}-\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}\right\rangle =\frac{\delta\left(\Omega\right)}{i\sqrt{2}}\left(\xi-\xi^{*}\right)=0\\
\implies\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,beforeTransformation}}\right\rangle  & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,beforeTransformation}}\right\rangle =\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,afterTransformation}}\right\rangle =\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
What are 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}$
\end_inset

? We can show that we must have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{a} & = & \sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\\
\xi & = & \bar{a}\pi\sqrt{2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the time averaged optical power*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We will be able to write down the electric field in the following form:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}\left(t\right)/\mathcal{C}_{0}\rightarrow\left(\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t$
\end_inset

 (cf.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:singleModeLaserElectricField"

\end_inset

), so (in CGS the intensity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\langle E^{2}\right\rangle _{time-average}/4\pi\times\mathcal{A}c\right)=\left|E^{2}\right|c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (equation preceding B16 on top of page 28 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kimble2001"

\end_inset

 ..also see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poynting in cgs"

\end_inset

) the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is to normalize over the beam cross-sectional area.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c_{2}^{-1}\hat{I}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2} & = & \left|E\right|^{2}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}=\left|\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\cos^{2}\omega_{0}t+\left|\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}\sin^{2}\omega_{0}t+2\sin\omega_{0}t\cos\omega_{0}tRe\left(\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\left(\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\right)\right)\\
c_{2}^{-1}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}\left\langle I\right\rangle _{time-average\mbox{ over one period }T=2\pi/\omega_{0}} & = & \frac{\left|\frac{c_{1}\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}}{2}+\frac{\left|\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\right|^{2}}{2}\equiv c_{2}^{-1}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}\times\hat{I}_{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as can be determined using Mathematica with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle O\right\rangle _{time-average}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}Odt$
\end_inset

 (note that we have not included 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{cs}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 in the time average because the time dependence should be all included
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos$
\end_inset

 term ?? I think it is for a monochromatic beam).
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c_{2}^{-1}\braket{\xi|\hat{I}_{0}}{\xi}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}=1/c_{2}/\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}\left\langle \hat{I}_{0}\right\rangle  & \equiv & \frac{4\pi}{\mathcal{A}c}I_{0}=\left(\frac{c_{1}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\right)^{2}\frac{\bar{a}}{2}^{2}+\bar{a}\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\right\rangle +\frac{\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}^{2}\right\rangle }{2}+\frac{\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}^{2}\right\rangle }{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c,beforeTransformation}\right\rangle =?\\
\mbox{and }\left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\right\rangle  & \approx & \left\langle \frac{\hat{a}_{+}+\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{\sqrt{2}}\right\rangle =\frac{\delta\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\xi+\xi^{*}\right)=\sqrt{2}\delta\left(\Omega\right)\xi
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 because we are working in the limit that the sidebands are very small and
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}\approx1$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defLambda2photonFormalism"

\end_inset

) and we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is real.
 Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\implies\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c,beforeTransformation}}\right\rangle =\left\langle \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\xi}{\sqrt{2}\pi}\\
 & = & \bar{a}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

by definition.
 If we pick
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & = & \pi\sqrt{2}\bar{a}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 then it works out.
 Furthermore, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\right\rangle  & \approx & \left\langle \frac{\hat{a}_{+}-\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}\right\rangle =\frac{\delta\left(\Omega\right)}{i\sqrt{2}}\left(\xi-\xi^{*}\right)=0\\
\implies\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,beforeTransformation}}\right\rangle  & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,beforeTransformation}}\right\rangle =\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{s,afterTransformation}}\right\rangle =\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and hence we must have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{0} & = & c_{2}\left(\frac{c_{1}\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\pi\sqrt{2}}\right)^{2}\frac{\bar{a}}{2}^{2}+O\left(\left\langle \hat{\mathcal{E}_{sc}}^{2}\right\rangle \right)\\
\implies\bar{a} & = & \frac{1}{\mathcal{C}_{0}\sqrt{c_{2}}}\sqrt{2I_{0}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}=\sqrt{4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}/\mathcal{A}c},$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{a} & = & \sqrt{\frac{\mathcal{A}c}{4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}\sqrt{c_{2}}}}\sqrt{2I_{0}}\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\left(\sqrt{\frac{\mathcal{A}c}{4\pi c_{2}}}\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the electric field to be in the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & = & \mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\left(\bar{a}+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right].\label{eq:final simple single mode laser}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

(Basis: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset

 equation 2.15)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electric Field Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Propagation in free space
\end_layout

\end_inset

Propagation in free space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a coherent optical field traveling for time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-field-propagating"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename QuantumPropagationFreeSpace.svg
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:A-field-propagating"

\end_inset

A field propagating for time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we get the same result had the field moved from left to right
 or right to left.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 How are the field's quadratures related to the input field's quadratures?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the input optical field is a single mode coherent state and
 so we can write all electric fields in the following (unnormalized) form
 (this is Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:final simple single mode laser"

\end_inset

 without the normalization constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}$
\end_inset

 )
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{u}_{1}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{u}_{2}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the amplitude and phase quadratures, respectively.
 Denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{a}_{1}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{2}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\\
\hat{E}_{fsp}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-\tau\right)\\
 & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{b}_{1}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{b}_{2}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{E}_{fsp}\left(t\right)=\hat{E}_{in}\left(t-\tau\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simplePropagationFreeSpace"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{b}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{b}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)=e^{i\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}\tau & -\sin\omega_{0}\tau\\
\sin\omega_{0}\tau & \cos\omega_{0}\tau
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{a}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{a}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:quadraturesFreeSpacePropagation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{fsp}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-\tau\right)\\
 & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-\tau\right)+\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\sin\omega_{0}\left(t-\tau\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then use that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sin\omega_{0}\left(t-\tau\right) & \approx & \sin\omega_{0}t\cos\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)-\cos\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\\
\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-\tau\right) & \approx & \cos\omega_{0}t\cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right)+\sin\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

to obtain that (letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\equiv\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}_{fsp}\left(t\right) & = & \left[\xi+\hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]\left(\cos\omega_{0}t\cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right)+\sin\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right)+\\
 &  & \hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\left\{ \sin\omega_{0}t\cos\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)-\cos\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right\} \\
 & = & \cos\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\left\{ \left[\xi+\hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]\cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right)-\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right\} \\
 &  & +\sin\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\left\{ \left[\xi+\hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)+\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\cos\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right\} \\
 & = & \cos\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\left\{ \hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right)-\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right\} \\
 &  & +\sin\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\left\{ \hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)+\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)\cos\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\right\} \\
 &  & +\xi\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-\tau\right)\\
 & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{b}_{1}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{b}_{2}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Hence, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{b}_{1}\left(t\right)\\
\hat{b}_{2}\left(t\right)
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right) & -\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right)\\
\sin\left(\tau\omega_{0}\right) & \cos\left(\omega_{0}\tau\right)
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{a}_{1}\left(t-\tau\right)\\
\hat{a}_{2}\left(t-\tau\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now let us apply the Fourier transform.
 All we need to use is that, using the shift property of Fourier transforms
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shiftPropertyFourierTransforms"

\end_inset

 with the Fourier transform defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[g\right]\propto\int e^{ixk}g\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{a}_{1,2}\left(t-\tau\right)\right] & = & e^{i\Omega\tau}a_{1,2}\left(\Omega\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{b}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{b}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)=e^{i\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}\tau & -\sin\omega_{0}\tau\\
\sin\omega_{0}\tau & \cos\omega_{0}\tau
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{a}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{a}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Fundamentals of Quantum Optics/Quantum Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Light pictures in QO (for single mode fields)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point is to write down the expression for a single mode of
 the electric field in the Heisenberg picture*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quantizedEfieldAPH190"

\end_inset

 restricted to one mode
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{E}\left(\vec{x},t\right) & = & \sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2\epsilon_{0}}}\left(a\left(t\right)+a^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\right)\vec{u}\left(\vec{x}\right)\\
 & \equiv & \mathcal{C}_{0}\frac{\mathcal{E}\left(\vec{x},t\right)e^{i\vec{k}.\vec{x}-i\omega t}+\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)e^{-i\vec{k}.\vec{x}+i\omega t}}{\sqrt{2}}\\
 & \equiv & \mathcal{C}_{0}\left(\mathcal{E}_{c}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\cos\left(\omega t-\vec{k}.\vec{x}\right)+\mathcal{E}_{s}\left(\vec{x},t\right)\sin\left(\omega t-\vec{k}.\vec{x}\right)\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 Then in analogy to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:classicalLightPictures"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 are the complex amplitude quadratures
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
complex amplitude quadratures
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{s}$
\end_inset

 are the cosine/amplitude and sine/phase quadratures
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cosine/amplitude and sine/phase quadratures
\end_layout

\end_inset

, respectively.
 We can see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{E}_{c}\left(\vec{x},t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{E}\left(\vec{x},t\right)+\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)}{\sqrt{2}}\\
\mathcal{E}_{s}\left(\vec{x},t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{E}\left(\vec{x},t\right)-\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(\vec{x},t\right)}{i\sqrt{2}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
i\im{\frac{\mathcal{E}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega t}+\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega t}}{\sqrt{2}}} & = & -\frac{\im{\mathcal{E}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega t}}+\im{\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega t}}}{i\sqrt{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{\mathcal{E}\left(t\right)-\mathcal{E}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)}{i\sqrt{2}}\sin\omega t\\
 & = & \mathcal{E}_{s}\sin\omega t
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results for two photon formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the analysis done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:2photon-formalism"

\end_inset

, we have in the limit that the sidebands 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\ll\omega$
\end_inset

 that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:complexAmplitude2PhotonFormalism"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathcal{E}}\left(t\right)\equiv\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\hat{a}\left(t\right)=\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\lambda_{+}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{+}e^{-i\Omega t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}\equiv\sqrt{\left(4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}\right)/\mathcal{A}c}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why did we choose this normalization constant? From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Qemrelations"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right)=\frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k}}\sum_{s}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2\epsilon_{0}}}\left[i\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can define
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{3/2}\equiv\sqrt{\mathcal{A}L}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, going to gaussian cgs units, mean we pick up a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 So now we obtain something like
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right)=\sum_{\vec{k}}\sum_{s}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\hbar\omega}{\mathcal{A}L}}\left[i\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

How does 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1/L}$
\end_inset

 become 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1/c}$
\end_inset

 ?? where does a time constant come into play ???
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}\left(\Omega\right)\equiv\sqrt{\frac{\omega_{0}\pm\Omega}{\omega_{0}}}$
\end_inset

.
 We would then obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}+\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{\dagger}}{2},\\
\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}-\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and in the small bandwidth limit (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\ggg\Omega$
\end_inset

), we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}\approx1$
\end_inset

 and so in this limit
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}+\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{\dagger}}{2},\\
\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}-\hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Different pictures in Quantum physics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Heisenberg-picture"

\end_inset

Heisenberg picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, then the Heisenberg picture is defined in the following way: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{U}^{\dagger}\left(t,t_{0}\right)\hat{A}\hat{U}\left(t,t_{0}\right)\\
\left|\psi_{H}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left|\psi\left(t_{0}\right)\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is an operator, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 a ket, in the Schrodinger picture, the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 refers to the Heisenberg picture of the associated quantity (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{H}$
\end_inset

 is an operator in the Heisenberg picture) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\left(t,t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the time evolution operator associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Heisenberg picture, expectation values are conserved:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{\psi_{1}\left(t\right)|\hat{A}|\psi_{2}\left(t\right)}=\braket{\psi_{1,H}|\hat{A}_{H}|\psi_{2,H}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\braket{\psi_{1H}|\hat{A}_{H}|\psi_{2H}} & = & \braket{\psi_{1}\left(t_{0}\right)|U^{\dagger}\hat{A}U|\psi_{2}\left(t_{0}\right)}\\
 & = & \braket{\psi_{1}\left(t\right)|\hat{A}|\psi_{2}\left(t\right)}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time evolution of an operator is given by (assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is time-independent) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right)=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\hat{H},\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right)\right]+e^{iHt/\hbar}\left(\partial_{t}\hat{A}\left(t\right)\right)e^{-iHt/\hbar}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "shrodinger proof"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $U=e^{-iHt},$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{U}^{\dagger}\left(t,t_{0}\right)\hat{A}\hat{U}\left(t,t_{0}\right)\\
 & = & e^{iHt}\hat{A}\left(t\right)e^{-iHt}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{A}_{H} & = & iH\hat{A}_{H}-i\hat{A}_{H}H+e^{iHt}\left(\partial_{t}\hat{A}\left(t\right)\right)e^{-iHt}\\
 & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H,\hat{A}_{H}\right]+e^{iHt}\left(\partial_{t}\hat{A}\left(t\right)\right)e^{-iHt}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:InteractionPicture"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interaction picture
\end_layout

\end_inset

Interaction picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Hamiltonian of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{0}+H_{int}$
\end_inset

, where I will refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{int}$
\end_inset

 as the interaction Hamiltonian (in the Schrodinger picture).
 Then, in reference to the Schrodinger picture (whose elements will be denoted
 with the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

), the interaction picture elements, which will be denoted with subscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, are defined in the following way
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\left|\psi_{S}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
A_{I}\left(t\right) & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)A_{S}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)\\
\hat{\rho}_{I}\left(t\right) & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{\rho}_{S}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)\\
H_{0,I} & = & H_{0}\\
H_{I,int} & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)H_{int}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)\label{eq:interactionHI}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the time evolution operators for 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is time-independent, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\left(t\right)=e^{-iH_{0}t/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 The interaction picture is equivalent to any other picture because expectation
 values are conserved, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{tr}\left(\hat{\rho}_{I}\hat{A}_{I}\right)=\mbox{tr}\left(\hat{\rho}_{S}\hat{A}_{S}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{tr}\left(\hat{\rho}_{I}\hat{A}_{I}\right) & = & \mbox{tr}\left(U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{\rho}_{S}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)A_{S}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)\right)\\
 & = & \mbox{tr}\left(U_{0}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\hat{\rho}_{S}\left(t\right)A_{S}\left(t\right)U_{0}\left(t\right)\right)\\
 & = & \mbox{tr}\left(\hat{\rho}_{S}\hat{A}_{S}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

because the trace is invariant under unitary transformations.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Time evolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is time-independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time evolution of states, operators and density operators is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & H_{I,int}\left(t\right)\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
\frac{d}{dt}A_{I}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H_{0},A_{I}\right]\\
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\hat{\rho}_{I}\left(t\right) & = & \left[H_{I,int}\left(t\right),\hat{\rho}_{I}\left(t\right)\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(for the operator equations of motion, look at 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "shrodinger proof"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{0}$
\end_inset

),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to see why, notice that originally, we had that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{S}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & H\left(t\right)\left|\psi_{S}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
\implies i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\left(U\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \right) & = & i\hbar U\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle +\left(i\hbar-i\frac{H_{0}}{\hbar}\right)U\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =i\hbar U\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle +H_{0}U\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & i\hbar U\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle +\underbrace{UH_{0}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle }\\
 & = & UU^{\dagger}H\left(t\right)\left|\psi_{S}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & U\left(U^{\dagger}H\left(t\right)U\right)\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & U\left(\underbrace{H_{0}}+H_{I,SI}\right)\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle .
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Canceling the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 from both sides, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\hbar U\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =UH_{I,SI}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Left multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, we obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =H_{I,SI}\left|\psi_{I}\left(t\right)\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantized E&M
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Free fields in free space (SI)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the EM field is contained in a big cube of side 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (and we impose periodic boundary conditions) then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{A}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k}}\sum_{s}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega\epsilon_{0}}}\left[\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right]\label{eq:Qemrelations}\\
\hat{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k}}\sum_{s}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2\epsilon_{0}}}\left[i\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right]\nonumber \\
\hat{B}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k}}\sum_{s=1,2}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega\epsilon_{0}}}\left[i\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\left(\vec{k}\times\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}\right)e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right].\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

(from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 equ.
 10.4-38-40) 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 indexes the polarization base vectors: 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\vec{k}1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\vec{k}2}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{k}.\epsilon_{\vec{k}s} & = & 0\\
\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}^{*}.\epsilon_{\vec{k}s^{'}} & = & \delta_{ss^{'}}\\
\epsilon_{\vec{k}1}\times\epsilon_{\vec{k}2} & = & \vec{k}/k\\
\sum_{S}\left(\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}\right)_{i}\left(\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}\right)_{j} & = & \delta_{ij}-\frac{k_{i}k_{j}}{k^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The last relation comes from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 equ.
 10.2-19c
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 limit we obtain something like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3/2}}\intop_{\left(\infty\right)}\sum_{s}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega\epsilon_{0}}}\left[\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\left(t=0\right)\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right]d^{3}k.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\vec{k}}\rightarrow\left(L/2\pi\right)^{3}\intop\left(\right)d^{3}k$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(L/2\pi\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the density of modes --- but then how to get rid of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{3/2}$
\end_inset

 ??
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
