\begin_layout Subsection
Momentum of the quantized field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From classical E&M, the total linear momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of the field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto$
\end_inset

 to the volume integral of the Poynting vector (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ClassicalEMmomentum"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\boldsymbol{P} & = & \epsilon_{0}\intop_{L^{3}}\boldsymbol{E}\left(r,t\right)\times\boldsymbol{B}\left(r,t\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Howeover, this classical expression is not Hermitian (
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 do not commute).
 So we adopt the following symmetric expression for the momentum of the
 quantized field:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{P} & = & \frac{1}{2}\epsilon_{0}\intop_{L^{3}}\left[\hat{E}\times\hat{B}-\hat{B}\times\hat{E}\right]d^{3}r
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Use the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Qemrelations"

\end_inset

) to obtain after some tedious algebra that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{P} & = & \sum_{\boldsymbol{k}s}\hbar\boldsymbol{k}\hat{n}_{\boldsymbol{k}s}\label{eq:momentumQMfield}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

 commute for a free field*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a free field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}=\sum_{ks}\hbar\omega\hat{n}_{ks}$
\end_inset

 which also a sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{ks}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 would be a constant of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 10.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A phase operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write the creation operator as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{ks} & = & \hat{g}_{ks}e^{i\hat{\phi}_{ks}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(this is in analogy with classical EM where the complex amplitude of a field
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{ks}=\left|\mathcal{E}_{ks}\right|e^{i\phi_{ks}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
From now on, assume we are working with one mode.
 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
The issue is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is not Hermitian and (equivalently 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{\phi}}$
\end_inset

 is not unitary)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
To see why let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X & = & e^{i\hat{\phi}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a & = & gX\\
 & = & \sqrt{n+1}X\\
\implies X & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}a
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
XX^{\dagger} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}aa^{\dagger}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}\left(n+1\right)\frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}=1\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X^{\dagger}X & = & a^{\dagger}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n+1}}a\\
 & = & a^{\dagger}\frac{1}{n+1}a
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

But 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\dagger}X$
\end_inset

 is different than unity as can be seen in the fact that when it is operator
 on the vacuum it gives 0 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is not unitary.
 But for fock states different than 0
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X^{\dagger}X\ket{n} & = & \sqrt{n}a^{\dagger}\frac{1}{n+1}\ket{n-1}\\
 & = & \frac{\sqrt{n}}{n}\sqrt{n}\ket{n}\\
 & = & \left(1\right)\ket{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X^{\dagger}X & = & I-\ket{0}\bra{0}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Howeover, if we make those assumptions we obtain the following relations:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{n} & = & e^{-i\hat{\phi}}\left(\hat{n}+1\right)e^{i\hat{\phi}}=e^{-i\hat{\phi}}\hat{n}e^{i\hat{\phi}}+1\label{eq:tempPhaseOperator}\\
\implies\left[\hat{n},e^{i\hat{\phi}}\right] & = & -e^{i\hat{\phi}},\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
From the definiton 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}_{ks}e^{i\hat{\phi}_{ks}}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\dagger}=e^{-i\phi}g$
\end_inset

 and so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
aa^{\dagger} & = & n+1=g^{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\sqrt{n+1}$
\end_inset

 which directly entails that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{n} & = & e^{-i\phi}g^{2}e^{i\phi}=e^{-i\hat{\phi}}\left(\hat{n}+1\right)e^{i\hat{\phi}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

which turns out to be correct (see section 10.7.2.
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

) and we obtain that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{n},\hat{\phi}\right] & = & i\quad\mbox{(incorrect)}\nonumber \\
\implies\sqrt{\left\langle \left(\Delta\hat{n}\right)^{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \left(\Delta\hat{\phi}\right)^{2}\right\rangle } & \geq & \frac{1}{2}\quad\mbox{(incorrect)}.\label{eq:uncertainty phase operator}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Use the operator expansion theorem (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:operatorExpansionTheorem"

\end_inset

) on eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tempPhaseOperator"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{n}-1 & = & \hat{n}-i\left[\hat{\phi},n\right]+\frac{\left(-i\right)^{2}}{2!}\left[\phi,\left[\phi,n\right]\right]+...,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[n,\phi\right]\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 then the second higher order and higher order terms dissapear and we are
 left with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{n}-1 & = & \hat{n}-i\left[\hat{\phi},n\right]\\
\implies1 & = & i\left[\hat{\phi},n\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

These relations lead to the contradiction 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m-n\right)\braket{m|\hat{\phi}|n}=i\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 10.7.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Two-photon formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
One photon formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A one photon device is that its output consists of independently excited
 modes with time stationary (TS) noise.
 Indeed, the photons of a beam produced by a one-photon device are created
 one at a time means that the fluctuations in the electric field are due
 to random emission of single photons which have various frequencies and
 phases.
 As a result, the fluctuations at different frequencies are independent,
 and the fluctuations at each frequency are distributed randomly in phase.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be formalized by saying that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \Delta E\left(\omega\right)\Delta E\left(\omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle  & = & 0\quad\mbox{(fluctuations at different frequencies are independent)}\\
\left\langle \Delta E\left(\omega\right)\Delta E^{*}\left(\omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle  & \propto & \mathcal{D}\left(\omega\right)2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \right\rangle $
\end_inset

 denotes a classical statistical average, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E\left(\omega\right)\equiv E\left(\omega\right)-\left\langle E\left(\omega\right)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is the flux spectral density of the e-field fluctuations (in dimensions
 of energy per area).
 Or equivalently, we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \Delta E\left(x,t\right)^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \intop\frac{d\omega}{2\pi}\mathcal{D}\left(\omega\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

i.e.
 the variance of the electric field is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formalism of one-photon optics is founded firmly on the annihilation
 operator as the fundamental operator and on the coherent states as the
 fundamental quantum states.
 Quasiprobability distributions (QPD) such as the Glauber p-representation
 (see sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:p representation"

\end_inset

) is a convenient tool to describe one-photon devices but not necessarily
 2-photon devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Introduction of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "caves1985"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:2photon-formalism"

\end_inset

Two photon formalism; introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The polarization of light has been ignored*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Insofar as the light beams in the interferometer can be well approximated
 as paraxial beams, and the polarization of the light wave does not matter
 in most of the considered interferometers, we will omit the vector nature
 of the electric field and treat it as a scalar field with strength defined
 by a scalar operator-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}\left(x,y,z,t\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a light wave traveling along the + direction of the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis, then in the Heisenberg picture:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}\left(x,y,z;t\right) & = & u\left(x,y,z\right)\left\{ \hat{E}^{\left(+\right)}\left(t\right)+\hat{E}^{\left(-\right)}\left(t\right)\right\} \label{eq:eField2photonFormalism}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the spatial mode shape (assume that it is slowly changing on a wavelength
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 scale) and in CGS units 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}^{\left(+\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\hbar\omega}{\mathcal{A}c}}\hat{a}_{\omega}e^{-i\omega t}\\
\hat{E}^{\left(-\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{E}^{\left(+\right)\dagger}\left(t\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is the effective cross-section area of the light beam*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These results are a special case of the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cavityEM"

\end_inset

 with a spatial profile given by 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\omega/c$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2\pi\hbar ck_{n}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cavityEM"

\end_inset

 becomes 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2\pi\hbar\omega_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{a}_{\omega},\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}^{\dagger}\right] & = & 2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)\label{eq:commutationFrequencyDomain}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is a consequence of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:continuumCommutation"

\end_inset

 and defining something like 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\omega}=\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{c}}a_{k}$
\end_inset

 so that the commutation relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:continuumCommutation"

\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

 or something like that.
 Note that this is made easy by the fact that we have a one-dimensional
 plane wave so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{k}=\left(0,0,k_{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{k}\right|=k_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Details: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{k},a_{k^{'}}\right]=\delta\left(k-k^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

s are 1D (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 eq.
 10.10-4).
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\omega/c$
\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{\omega},a_{\omega^{'}}\right]=\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)/c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Also this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{t},a_{s}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta\left(t-s\right)$
\end_inset

: We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{a}_{\omega},\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}^{\dagger}\right] & = & \left[\int a_{t}e^{-i\omega t}dt,\int a_{s}^{\dagger}e^{i\omega^{'}s}ds\right]\\
 & = & \int\int dsdte^{i\omega^{'}s}e^{-i\omega t}\left[a_{t},a_{s}^{\dagger}\right]\\
 & = & \int ds\int dte^{i\omega^{'}s}e^{-i\omega t}\delta\left(t-s\right)\\
 & = & \int dt\exp\left(-i\left[\omega-\omega^{'}\right]t\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Assume that the light consists mostly a monochramatic wave (with frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

) with two sidebands defined by the amplitudes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{+} & = & \hat{a}_{\omega_{0}+\Omega}\\
\hat{a}_{-} & = & \hat{a}_{\omega_{0}-\Omega}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The different parts of the electric field can be rewritten (in the approximation
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 is very large compared to the sidebands of the light signal*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and so if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 appears as one of the limits in an integral then we can replace it with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because of this narrowband approximation, the 2 photon formalism arises
 naturally when dealing with monochramatic or nearly monochramatic beams
 (Opinion)
\end_layout

\end_inset

) to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}^{\left(+\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{\mathcal{E}}\left(t\right)e^{-i\omega_{0}t},\\
\hat{E}^{\left(-\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{\mathcal{E}}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)e^{i\omega_{0}t},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{\mathcal{E}}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\lambda_{+}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{+}e^{-i\Omega t}=\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\hat{a}\left(t\right)\label{eq:complexAmplitude2PhotonFormalism}\\
\hat{\mathcal{E}}^{\dagger}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\lambda_{-}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}e^{-i\Omega t}=\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}^{\left(+\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi\hbar\omega}{\mathcal{A}c}}\hat{a}_{\omega}e^{-i\omega t}\\
 & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}e^{-i\omega_{0}t}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\omega_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\frac{\sqrt{\Omega+\omega_{0}}}{\sqrt{\omega_{0}}}\hat{a}_{\Omega+\omega_{0}}e^{-i\Omega t}\\
\implies\hat{E}^{\left(-\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{E}^{\left(+\right)\dagger}\left(t\right)=\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}e^{i\omega_{0}t}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\omega_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\frac{\sqrt{\Omega+\omega_{0}}}{\sqrt{\omega_{0}}}\hat{a}_{\Omega+\omega_{0}}^{\dagger}e^{i\Omega t}\\
 & = & -\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}e^{i\omega_{0}t}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{\omega_{0}}^{-\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\frac{\sqrt{-\Omega+\omega_{0}}}{\sqrt{\omega_{0}}}\hat{a}_{-\Omega+\omega_{0}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\Omega t}\\
 & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}e^{i\omega_{0}t}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\omega_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\frac{\sqrt{-\Omega+\omega_{0}}}{\sqrt{\omega_{0}}}\hat{a}_{-\Omega+\omega_{0}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\Omega t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We integrate from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 for the following reason: by definition we split the electric field into
 positive and negative frequency components:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\omega\right)=\begin{cases}
E^{+}, & \omega>0\\
E^{-}, & \omega<0.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 plays the role of a complex quadrature*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
because now the electric field has the form of Re
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\right)$
\end_inset

-see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:classicalLightPictures"

\end_inset

 for more details Note that here
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & \mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

without the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, which implies that when we make the transformation to phase and amplitude
 quadratures using the standard formulas Eqs 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transformationElectricFieldPictures"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{E}{\sqrt{2}} & \rightarrow & E_{c}\cos+E_{s}\sin
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because of the definition of E as
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and so to maintain the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}\cos+E_{s}\sin$
\end_inset

 we multiply the standard transformation rules by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{C}_{0} & \equiv & \sqrt{\left(4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}\right)/\mathcal{A}c}\label{eq:definition of C0 in QuantumEfield}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{\pm}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \sqrt{\frac{\omega_{0}\pm\Omega}{\omega_{0}}}\label{eq:defLambda2photonFormalism}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
After a simple variable substitution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\omega-\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}^{\left(+\right)}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}e^{-i\omega_{0}t}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\lambda_{+}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{+}e^{-i\Omega t}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then take the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 is very large.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 With the interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 as a complex amplitude in mind, we can obtain the amplitude and phase quadratur
es : 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & \equiv & \hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\nonumber \\
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right) & = & \mathcal{C}_{0}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}=\mathcal{C}_{0}\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\\
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right) & = & \mathcal{C}_{0}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}=\mathcal{C}_{0}\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right),\label{eqeQuadratures2photonformalism}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that here the complex amplitude picture of the electric field is of
 the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & \mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

without the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, which implies that when we make the transformation to phase and amplitude
 quadratures using the standard formulas Eqs 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transformationElectricFieldPictures"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{E}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.\right) & \rightarrow & E_{c}\cos+E_{s}\sin\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because of the definition of E as
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and so to maintain the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}\cos+E_{s}\sin$
\end_inset

 we multiply the standard transformation rules by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are called the phase and amplitude quadratures, respectively, because in
 the classical limit they correspond to amplitude and phase modulations*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, the electric field is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left(t\right) & = & \hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0t}+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Assume that the electric field has a large amplitude then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left(t\right) & \approx & \left(A+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\\
 & = & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\\
 & \approx & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+A\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}-\frac{1}{3!}\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)^{3}+\frac{1}{5!}\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)^{5}+...\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\\
 & = & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+A\sin\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\approx A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}}{A}\right)\sin\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\\
 & = & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\left[\cos\omega_{0}t+\sin\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]\\
 & \approx & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\left[\cos\omega_{0}t\left(1+\frac{1}{2!}\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}}{A}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{4!}\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}}{A}\right)^{4}+...\right)+\sin\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]\\
 & = & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\left[\cos\omega_{0}t\cos\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}}{A}\right)+\sin\left(\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]\\
 & \approx & A\left(1+\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)}{A}\right)\cos\left(\omega_{0}t-\frac{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}}{A}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(inspired from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset

 section 2.4.1 footnote 1) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Furthermore, we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{c}^{\dagger}a_{c},a_{s}\right]=a_{c}^{\dagger}\left[a_{c},a_{s}\right]+\left[a_{c}^{\dagger},a_{s}\right]a_{c}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{+}+\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{2}\\
\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\lambda_{+}\hat{a}_{+}-\lambda_{-}\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}}{i\sqrt{2}},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These expressions can be found by using equs 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transformationElectricFieldPictures"

\end_inset

 to transform from complex amplitude picture to quadratures picture and
 then doing some simple algebra.
\end_layout

\end_inset

and so we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{a}_{sc}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \hat{a}_{sc}\left(-\Omega\right)\quad\implies\hat{a}_{sc}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)=\hat{a}_{sc}\left(t\right)\label{eq:phasequadraturesarehermitian}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)e^{i\Omega t}\\
 & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(-\Omega\right)e^{i\Omega t}\\
 & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}=a_{c}\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The Fourier operators satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]=2\pi\frac{\Omega}{\omega_{0}}\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\nonumber \\
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]=2\pi i\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\label{eq:commutation2photonformalism}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Use equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:commutationFrequency"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{a}_{cs}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{cs}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]\neq0$
\end_inset

 which will contribute noise to the final measurement result.
 However if the photodetectors measure the photon number flux:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t\right) & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega d\omega^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)t\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why this represents the photon number flux look at section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Photoelectric"

\end_inset

.
 Basically, 
\begin_inset Formula $N=F^{-}\left(r,t\right)F^{+}\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(k\right)=1$
\end_inset

 Just note that in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Photoelectric"

\end_inset

 we work with discrete 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t\right),\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]=0$
\end_inset

 and there is no new noise*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t\right),\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega d\omega^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{dsds^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)t\right]\exp\left[i\left(s-s^{'}\right)t^{'}\right]\left[\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}},\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\right]\\
 & = & \int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega d\omega^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{dsds^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)t\right]\exp\left[i\left(s-s^{'}\right)t^{'}\right]\left(\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\left[\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}},\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\right]\hat{a}_{s^{'}}+\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left[\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}},\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\right]+\left[\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\right]\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}+\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left[\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\right]\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega d\omega^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{dsds^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)t\right]\exp\left[i\left(s-s^{'}\right)t^{'}\right]\left(\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\delta\left(\omega^{'}-s\right)-\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}\delta\left(\omega-s^{'}\right)\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{dsds^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-s\right)t\right]\exp\left[i\left(s-s^{'}\right)t^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}-\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega d\omega^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{ds}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[i\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)t\right]\exp\left[i\left(s-\omega\right)t^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{dsds^{'}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\Theta\left(s\right)e^{-is\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\exp\left[i\omega t\right]\exp\left[-is^{'}t^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}-\intop_{0}^{\infty}\int\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega^{'}d\omega}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{ds}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}e^{i\omega\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\exp\left[-i\omega^{'}t\right]\exp\left[ist^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}\right)\\
 & = & \intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{ds^{'}}{\pi}\exp\left[i\omega t\right]\exp\left[-is^{'}t^{'}\right]\left[\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right)-\frac{i}{\pi\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\right]\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}-\\
 &  & \intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega^{'}}{\pi}\frac{ds}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\exp\left[-i\omega^{'}t\right]\exp\left[ist^{'}\right]\left[\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right)+\frac{i}{\pi\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\right]\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\omega^{'}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the following fourier transform identity was used 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{F}\left[\Theta\left(s\right)\right] & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right)-\frac{i}{\pi\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\right].\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In the second integral of the last equality, rename 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{'}=s^{'}$
\end_inset

 which eliminates the delta function (???) I get equality if the integration
 is from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

..
 We'd be left with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t\right),\hat{\mathcal{N}}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & -\frac{i}{\pi\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\frac{ds^{'}}{\pi}\left(\exp\left[i\omega t\right]\exp\left[-is^{'}t^{'}\right]+\exp\left[i\omega t'\right]\exp\left[-is^{'}t\right]\right)\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{s^{'}}\\
 & = & -\frac{i}{2\pi^{4}\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\left[\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}d\omega\exp\left[i\omega t\right]\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}ds\exp\left[-ist^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{s}\right)+\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}d\omega\exp\left[i\omega t^{'}\right]\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\intop_{0}^{\infty}ds\exp\left[-ist\right]\hat{a}_{s}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \left(???\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

THERE IS A TYPO LIMITS OF INTEGRATION SHOULD BE FROM 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 (note also that the above treatment can be made correct by use of the bandwith
 approximation with a change of variables from 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\omega-\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and then taking 
\begin_inset Formula $-\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

