\begin_layout Subsection
Spectral densities (double-sided) for 2 photon formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They are defined in the following way
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{j}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left\langle \hat{a}_{i}\hat{a}_{j}+\hat{a}_{j}\hat{a}_{i}\right\rangle \\
 & \equiv & 2\pi S_{ij}\left(\Omega\right)\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the delta function makes sense because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{i}\hat{a}_{j}+\hat{a}_{j}\hat{a}_{i}\right\rangle  & = & 2\left\langle \hat{a}_{i}\hat{a}_{j}\right\rangle +C\times\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a constant
\end_layout

\end_inset

We can introduce the quadrature amplitudes matrix of spectral densities
 in the following fashion
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & \left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
\left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & \left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}
\end{array}\right] & = & 2\pi\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\left[\begin{array}{cc}
S_{cc}\left(\Omega\right) & S_{cs}\left(\Omega\right)\\
S_{sc}\left(\Omega\right) & S_{ss}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right]\nonumber \\
 & \equiv & 2\pi\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\mathbb{S}\label{eq:defSpectral2photon}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Example for the vacuum state (in the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 - see commutations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:commutation2photonformalism"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathbb{S}_{vac} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1/2 & 0\\
0 & 1/2
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:spectralVacuum}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
use the commutation relations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:commutation2photonformalism"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First we calculate the diagonal terms: in the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{c}$
\end_inset

 commutes with itself for all frequencies.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & \braket{vac|\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)|vac}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\braket{vac|\left(a_{+}+a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\left(a_{+}+a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega\right)|vac}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\braket{vac|\left(a_{+}\right)\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\left(a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega\right)|vac}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\braket{\omega_{0}+\Omega^{'}|\omega_{0}-\Omega}=\frac{1}{2}\left(2\pi\right)\delta\left(\omega_{0}+\Omega^{'}-\left(\omega_{0}-\Omega\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(2\pi\right)\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second, for the off-diagonal terms we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle +\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{-i}{2}\braket{vac|\left(a_{+}-a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\left(a_{+}+a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega\right)|vac}+\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{-i}{2}\braket{vac|\left(a_{+}\right)\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\left(a_{-}^{\dagger}\right)\left(\Omega\right)|vac}+\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\\
 & = & -\frac{i}{2}\left(2\pi\right)\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)+\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)=0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the first line we used that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & 2\pi i\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\\
\implies\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & 2\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

FOR the same reason the states are normalized differently.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 eq.
 10.10-4 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{k},a_{k}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta^{3}\left(\vec{k}-\vec{k}^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

 without the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 3.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Covariance matrix of photon states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to spectral densities but defined in the time domain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{V}_{ij}\left(t\right)\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right) & = & \left\langle \hat{a}_{i}\left(t\right)\hat{a}_{j}\left(t^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The delta function tells us that the noise levels at different times are
 statistically independent, i.e.
 the noise is Markovian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example for a vacuum state: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{V}_{vac} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1/2 & 0\\
0 & 1/2
\end{array}\right].\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{E}\left(x,y,z,t\right)^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left(u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\right)^{2}\times\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)\mathbb{V}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)^{T},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}\left(x,y,z,t\right)=u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(x,y,z,t\right) & = & u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]\\
\left\langle E\right\rangle  & = & u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\left\langle \hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \cos\omega_{0}t+\left\langle \hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \sin\omega_{0}t\right]\\
\hat{E}^{2}\left(x,y,z,t\right) & = & \left(u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\right)^{2}\left[\hat{a}_{c}^{2}\left(t\right)\cos^{2}\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}^{2}\left(t\right)\sin^{2}\omega_{0}t+a_{c}a_{s}\cos\sin+a_{s}a_{c}\cos\sin\right]\\
\implies\hat{E}^{2}\left(x,y,z,t\right) & = & \left(u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\right)^{2}\left[\mathbb{V}_{cc}\cos^{2}\omega_{0}t+\mathbb{V}_{ss}\sin^{2}\omega_{0}t+\mathbb{V}_{cs}\cos\sin+\mathbb{V}_{sc}\cos\sin\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)\mathbb{V}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)^{T} & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)\begin{array}{cc}
v_{cc} & v_{cs}\\
v_{sc} & v_{ss}
\end{array}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)^{T}\\
 & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
v_{cc}\cos+v_{sc}\sin & v_{cs}\cos+v_{ss}\sin\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\omega_{0}t & \sin\omega_{0}t\end{array}\right)^{T}\\
 & = & v_{cc}\cos^{2}+v_{sc}\sin\cos+v_{cs}\cos\sin+v_{ss}\sin^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 3.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Small sidebands approximation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defLambda2photonFormalism"

\end_inset

 is approximately equal to 1 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\hat{a}_{+}\left(\Omega\right)+\hat{a}_{-}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{2}}\nonumber \\
\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\hat{a}_{+}\left(\Omega\right)-\hat{a}_{-}\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{2}}.\label{eq:sidesbands2photonAcAs}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Moreover, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:commutation2photonformalism"

\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]\approx0\nonumber \\
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]=2\pi i\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\label{eq:2photonCommutationNarrowband}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and the electric field can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(x,y;t\right) & = & u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have from eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eqeQuadratures2photonformalism"

\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{2\pi}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)e^{-i\Omega t}\\
 &  & =\frac{\mathcal{C}_{0}}{\sqrt{2}}\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EfieldDefinitions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
?? I guess 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0,new}=\mathcal{C}_{0}/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 NO there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 because the complex amplitude picture is defined to be here 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & \mathcal{E}e^{-i\omega t}+h.c.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since the carrier field is classical, it will be advantageous to write
 the electric field in the following form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(x,y;t\right) & = & u\left(x,y,z\right)\mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\left(A_{c}+\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\left(A_{s}+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{cs}^{old}\rightarrow A_{c,s}+\hat{a}_{cs}^{new}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{cs}\equiv\left\langle \hat{a}_{cs}^{old}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, introduce the following notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{A} & \equiv & \left[\begin{array}{c}
A_{c}\\
A_{s}
\end{array}\right]\nonumber \\
\vec{a} & \equiv & \left[\begin{array}{c}
\hat{a}_{c}\\
\hat{a}_{s}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:defA2photon}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

: overview)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
In the small sidebands approximation, the amplitude and phase-quadratures,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{s}$
\end_inset

, are uncorrelated in time: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a_{c}\left(t\right)a_{s}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle -\left\langle a_{c}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \left\langle a_{s}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Note1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Commutation relations in the time domain and the small sidebands approximation
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 limit)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]\approx0\nonumber \\
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]=i\delta\left(t-t'\right).\label{eq:commutationRelationsTime2Photon}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2photonCommutationNarrowband"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]\approx0\\
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right]=2\pi i\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now take the Fourier transform to obtain that (the form of the Fourier transform
 used follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eqeQuadratures2photonformalism"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{s}^{\dagger}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\hat{a}_{c}^{\dagger}\left(t\right),\hat{a}_{s}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]=2\pi i\int\int d\Omega d\Omega^{'}e^{i\Omega t}e^{i\Omega^{'}t^{'}}\delta\left(\Omega+\Omega^{'}\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi i\int d\Omega e^{i\Omega\left(t-t^{'}\right)}\\
 & = & i\delta\left(t-t^{'}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:field operators"

\end_inset

Positive-frequency and negative frequency field operators 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the mode expansion of the EM field (Equs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:Qemrelations}\right)$
\end_inset

) are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F\left(r,t\right) & \equiv & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}\left[l\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+\mbox{h.c.}\right]\nonumber \\
 & \equiv & F^{+}\left(r,t\right)+F^{-}\left(r,t\right)\nonumber \\
F^{+} & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}l\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}\qquad\mbox{(positive frequency field operator).}\label{eq:Field Operators}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The case when 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(\omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-}$
\end_inset

 being a creation operator of a photon at the location
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 (see section 1.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PeskinQFT"

\end_inset

 or section 12.11 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

; latter is much more oriented towards the subject of localizing photons).
 So this operator is very important because most detection of photons happens
 by absorption via the photoelectric effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the positive and negative field operators satisfy the wave equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.12)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Commutation relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[F_{i}^{+}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right),F_{j}^{-}\left(r_{2},t_{2}\right)\right] & = & \frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}\intop\left|l\left(\omega\right)\right|^{2}\left(\delta_{ij}-\frac{k_{i}k_{j}}{k^{2}}\right)\exp\left(i\left(\vec{k}.\left(r_{1}-r_{2}\right)-\omega\left(t_{1}-t_{2}\right)\right)\right)d^{3}k\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Other relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{ks} & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\frac{1}{l\left(k\right)}\intop\epsilon_{ks}^{*}.F^{+}\left(r,t\right)e^{-i\left(k.r-\omega t\right)}d^{3}r.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.12.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Wave packets as fundamental modes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A wave packet is a linear combination of plane-wave modes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{u}_{m}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\lambda=\vec{k},s}\alpha_{m\lambda}l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\vec{\epsilon}_{\lambda}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}_{\lambda}.\vec{r}-\omega_{\lambda}t\right)\right],\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{m\lambda}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
are chosen so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}_{m}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for the representation of field vectors and they; i dont think
 this is necessary but is rather a nice feature to have,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using the fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are othogonal, i.e.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\epsilon_{1}+\epsilon_{2}\right)\left(\epsilon_{1}+\epsilon_{2}\right)=\left|\epsilon_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|\epsilon_{2}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
u_{m}.u_{n}^{*} & = & \frac{1}{L^{3}}\sum_{\lambda}\alpha_{m\lambda}\alpha_{n\lambda^{'}}^{*}\left|l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\right|^{2}\left|\epsilon_{\lambda}\right|^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{L^{3}}\sum_{\lambda}\alpha_{m\lambda}\alpha_{n\lambda^{'}}^{*}\left|l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\right|^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

are chosen to be the elements of a unitary matrix so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{m}\alpha_{m\lambda}^{*}\alpha_{m\lambda^{'}} & = & \delta_{\lambda\lambda^{'}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\boldsymbol{F}}^{\left(+\right)}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \sum_{m}\hat{c}_{m}\vec{u}_{m}\left(\vec{r},t\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{m}\equiv\sum_{\lambda}\alpha_{m\lambda}^{*}\hat{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\boldsymbol{F}}^{\left(+\right)}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\lambda}\hat{a}_{\lambda}l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\vec{\epsilon}_{\lambda}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}_{\lambda}.\vec{r}-\omega_{\lambda}t\right)\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\lambda}\left(\sum_{\lambda^{'}}\sum_{m}\alpha_{m\lambda^{'}}^{*}\alpha_{m\lambda}\hat{a}_{\lambda^{'}}\right)l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\vec{\epsilon}_{\lambda}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}_{\lambda}.\vec{r}-\omega_{\lambda}t\right)\right]\\
 & = & \sum_{m}\left(\sum_{\lambda^{'}}\alpha_{m\lambda^{'}}^{*}\hat{a}_{\lambda^{'}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\lambda}\alpha_{m\lambda}l\left(k_{\lambda}\right)\vec{\epsilon}_{\lambda}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}_{\lambda}.\vec{r}-\omega_{\lambda}t\right)\right]\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{\lambda^{'}}\sum_{m}\alpha_{m\lambda^{'}}^{*}\alpha_{m\lambda}\hat{a}_{\lambda^{'}} & = & \hat{a}_{\lambda}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and they act as boson annihilation and creation operators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{c}_{m},\hat{c}_{n}\right] & = & 0=\left[\hat{c}_{m}^{\dagger},\hat{c}_{n}^{\dagger}\right]\\
\left[\hat{c}_{m},\hat{c}_{n}^{\dagger}\right] & = & \delta_{mn}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The first equality directly follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{\lambda},a_{\lambda^{'}}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 while the second equality is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{c}_{m},\hat{c}_{n}^{\dagger}\right] & = & \sum_{\lambda}\sum_{\lambda^{'}}\alpha_{m\lambda}^{*}\alpha_{n\lambda^{'}}\left[a_{\lambda},a_{\lambda^{'}}\right]\\
 & = & \sum_{\lambda}\alpha_{m\lambda}^{*}\alpha_{n\lambda}=\delta_{mn}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Because of these relations, excitations of the field corresponding to different
 mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be produced independently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.7.4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Detection of photons and associated correlation functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Photoelectric"

\end_inset

Photoelectric measurement of the optical field; simple treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a photodetector*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that these have a low frequency threshold as well as an upper bound
 connected with the finite size of the potential well binding the photoelectron;
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 page 613 footnote.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 located 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

.
 We ask what is the probability of the detection of a photon (i.e.
 absorption, by emission of a photoelectron, of a photon).
 Field operators (section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:field operators}$
\end_inset

) are well suited for answering this question because they can be interpreted
 as the operators that absorb/create a photon in the vicinity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

[[TODO: Add reference/Explain]].
 The operator corresponding to the detection of a photon of polarization
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{F^{+}\left(s,\vec{r},t\right)=\frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k}}l\left(k\right)\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

is kept general (e.g.
 if the detector interacts with the field through 
\begin_inset Formula $-p.A$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{+}$
\end_inset

 would the positive frequency part of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: such an example, which would consist of a simple treatment of photoelectric
 effect in hydrogen, can be found in section 18.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shankarQM"

\end_inset

 or 15.3.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bellacQM"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us follow a simple argument: the interaction is described by 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{+}$
\end_inset

 and so the probability amplitude for the process of absorption at time
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and location 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is given by the matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{\psi_{final}|F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{initial}}{}$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "glauber photodector theory"
target "http://www.quantum.physik.uni-potsdam.de/teaching/ws2006/henkel.ws2006.qo.s23.pdf"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "glauber photodector theory"
target "C:\\Users\\Bass\\Documents\\Research\\Learning Material\\QO"
type "file:"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 for a simple detector model showing this) 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
looks very much like fermi's golden rule but without an extra proportionality
 factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto1/\hbar$
\end_inset

 ; origins at http://prola.aps.org/abstract/PR/v130/i6/p2529_1
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the case that we don't postselect for the final state, then we sum over
 a complete set of final states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{final}}$
\end_inset

.
 In the general case that the initial state is a mixture: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{\psi_{initial}}p\left(\psi_{initial}\right)\ket{\psi_{iniitial}}\bra{\psi_{initial}}$
\end_inset

 we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{Probability of photodection for polarization \ensuremath{s}}\nonumber \\
\mbox{at \ensuremath{r}, \ensuremath{t}within \ensuremath{\Delta t}} & \equiv & P_{1}\left(s,r,t\right)\Delta t\nonumber \\
 & = & C_{1}\Delta t\left\langle F^{-}\left(s,r,t\right)F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & = & C_{1}\Delta t\left\langle I\left(s,r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi},\label{eq:c1detector}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a constant characteristic of the detector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is a short interval over which the rate of detection does not vary appreciably
 and where the last equality comes from the definition of a 
\emph on
generalized intensity
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I\left(s,r,t\right) & \equiv & F^{-}F^{+}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is normally ordered so we can use the optical equivalence theorem (see
 sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:opticaEquivalence"

\end_inset

).
 Note if all polarization are included then we replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\pm}\left(s,r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\pm}\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 (and not add the probabilities)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The probability of a single transition is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{1,transition} & = & C_{1}\left|\braket{\psi_{final}|F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{initial}}\right|^{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so for all final states we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{all} & = & \sum_{final}P_{1,transition}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

When we have a mixed initial state then each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{all}$
\end_inset

 is weighted with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\psi_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 resulting in a rate of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{Rate of photodetection} & = & C_{1}\sum_{\psi_{initial}}p\left(\psi_{initial}\right)\sum_{\psi_{final}}\left|\braket{\psi_{final}|F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{initial}}\right|^{2}\\
 & = & C_{1}\sum_{\psi_{initial}}p\left(\psi_{initial}\right)\sum_{\psi_{final}}\braket{\psi_{initial}|F^{-}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{final}}\braket{\psi_{final}|F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{initial}}\\
 & = & C_{1}\sum_{\psi_{initial}}p\left(\psi_{initial}\right)\braket{\psi_{initial}|F^{-}\left(s,r,t\right)F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)|\psi_{initial}}\\
 & = & C_{1}Tr\left[\rho F^{-}\left(s,r,t\right)F^{+}\left(s,r,t\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiple photodetections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the more general situation in which a number of photoelectric detection
s are observed.
 What is the joint probability of all events?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume a number of photo-detectors located at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2},...$
\end_inset

 with polarizers in front of them as shown below.
 Assume there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections orderred so that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}<t_{2}<...<t_{N}$
\end_inset

 and so the probability amplitude for the transition from the initial state
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 to the final state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{probability amplitude} & = & \braket{\psi_{2}|F^{+}\left(s_{N},r_{N},t_{N}\right)...F^{+}\left(s_{2},r_{2},t_{2}\right)F^{+}\left(s_{1},r_{1},t_{1}\right)|\psi_{1}}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We then proceed as in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Photoelectric"

\end_inset

 to obtain that the joint 
\begin_inset Formula $N-fold$
\end_inset

 probability of photodetection for polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 within 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 ...
 and for polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{N}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{N}$
\end_inset

 within 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{N}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{N} & = & C_{N}\Delta t_{1}...\Delta t_{N}\left\langle F^{-}\left(s_{1},r_{1},t_{1}\right)...F^{-}\left(s_{N},r_{N},t_{N}\right)F^{+}\left(s_{N},r_{N},t_{N}\right)...F^{+}\left(s_{1},r_{1},t_{1}\right)\right\rangle ,\label{eq:probNphotodetectors}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which again is a 
\emph on
normally orderred correlation function
\emph default
.
 Again this arises because the fundamental measuring process is a photon
 absorption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename multiple photodetectors.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From 12.2.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.2.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Photon density operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field operators 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(k\right)=1$
\end_inset

 have a special significance and are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V & = & \frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)},\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the positive frequency operator.
 Consider the corresponding intensity operator 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(r,t\right)\equiv V^{\dagger}\left(r,t\right)V\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

, which is called the 
\emph on
photon density operator
\emph default
 because
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop_{L^{3}}I\left(r,t\right)d^{3}r & = & \sum_{\vec{k}s}a_{\vec{k}s}^{\dagger}a_{\vec{k}s}\equiv n\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop_{L^{3}}I\left(r,t\right)d^{3}r & = & \frac{1}{L^{3}}\intop_{L^{3}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}\sum_{\vec{k}^{'},s^{'}}\hat{a}_{\vec{k^{'}}s^{'}}^{\dagger}\epsilon_{\vec{k}^{'}s^{'}}e^{-i\left(\vec{k}^{'}.\vec{r}-\omega^{'}t\right)}\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\epsilon_{\vec{k}s}e^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}d^{3}r\\
 & = & \frac{1}{L^{3}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}\sum_{\vec{k}^{'},s^{'}}\hat{a}_{\vec{k^{'}}s^{'}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}\intop_{L^{3}}e^{i\left(r.\left(k-k^{'}\right)-t\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)\right)}d^{3}r\\
 & = & \frac{1}{L^{3}}\sum_{\vec{k},s}\sum_{\vec{k}^{'},s^{'}}\hat{a}_{\vec{k^{'}}s^{'}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\vec{k}s}e^{-it\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)}\left(L^{3}\delta_{\vec{k^{'}}\vec{k}}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

represents the photon number in the entire volume.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(V,t\right)=\intop_{V}I\left(r,t\right)d^{3}r$
\end_inset

 is to some extent the 
\emph on
local photon number operator
\emph default
 (as long as the dimensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are much larger than an optical wavelength: in the situation that we have
 a collection of points 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},...,r_{N}$
\end_inset

 that lie clearly (i.e.
 not defined to an accuracy better than a few wavelengths) then 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(V,t\right)$
\end_inset

 has eigenstates of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i_{1}}^{\dagger}\left(r_{1},t\right)...V_{i_{n}}^{\dagger}\left(r_{N},t\right)$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U\left(r_{1},V\right)+...+U\left(r_{N},V\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(r,V\right)$
\end_inset

 is equal to 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise; see section 12.11-
\begin_inset Formula $0\rightarrow4$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 for a detailed analysis*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
well written with some cool math
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quasi Monochromatic light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In such light (where the frequency spread is small compared with the midfrequenc
y) then 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 in the definition of the field operators 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Field Operators"

\end_inset

 is approximately a constant of the range of occupied modes
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Think of a sharp gaussian for 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(k\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In such a case, all possible intensities 
\begin_inset Formula $I=F^{+}F^{-}$
\end_inset

 are the same up to a constant and in this case the mean photon density
 is a measure of the mean field intensity up to a constant which we will
 determine below (for an example of a one photon polychromatic photon and
 how the above breaks down see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.11.5*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where the probability amplitude of energies and of photo detection is shown
 to be a convolution of the position space wave function
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Resultant simple interpertation of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:c1detector"

\end_inset


\series default
: We can now ask what 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equal to for a detector which is given by the model illustrated in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simpleDetector"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename simpledetectorModel.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:simpleDetector"

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 The measurement surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of the detector is chosen to be very small so that the field looks like
 a plane wave*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we have a spread of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{k}$
\end_inset

s for instance then we won't have a plane wave
\end_layout

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 which directly entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

 in equ.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:c1detector"

\end_inset

 may be taken to be any point on the exposed surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to interpert 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 to be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{1} & = & \alpha cS,\\
\implies P_{1}\Delta t & = & \alpha\left(S\times c\Delta t\right)\left\langle I\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the speed of light.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $S\times c\Delta t$
\end_inset

 represents the volume in which the photons can reside for them to be able
 to reach the detector in time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 (so photons outside this detector will not be detected).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is then the probability that any of those photons will be detected and
 is called the 
\emph on
quantum efficiency
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Second order correlation functions (Interference experiments)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a simple interference experiment shown below 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename simpleInterference.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:simpleInterference"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 figure 12.3
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:PrepInterference"

\end_inset

P-representation of interfering fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simpleInterference"

\end_inset

, suppose that one laser sends a coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{v_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and the other another coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{v_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 When both excitations are present, the total excitation is characterized
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\psi} & = & D\left(v_{2}\right)D\left(v_{1}\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & = & e^{\left(v_{2}v_{1}^{*}-v_{1}^{*}v_{2}\right)/2}D\left(v_{2}+v_{1}\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & = & e^{\left(v_{2}v_{1}^{*}-v_{1}^{*}v_{2}\right)/2}\ket{v_{2}+v_{1}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

A general representation can then be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)\ket{v_{1}+v_{2}}\bra{v_{1}+v_{2}}d^{2}v_{1}d^{2}v_{2}\\
 & = & \intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v-v_{1}\right)\ket v\bra vd^{2}v_{1}d^{2}v\\
 & \equiv & \intop\phi\left(v\right)\ket v\bra vd^{2}v,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)\equiv\intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v-v_{1}\right)d^{2}v_{1}=\intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)d^{2}v_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the second equality is obtained by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $v=v_{1}+v_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an actual experiment, one or the other of the light beams can be blocked
 in turn (like in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simpleInterference"

\end_inset

) so it must be possible for the two excitations to exist separately:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho_{1} & = & \intop\phi_{1}\left(v_{1}\right)\ket{v_{1}}\bra{v_{1}}d^{2}v_{1}\\
\mbox{and }\rho_{1} & = & \intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)\ket{v_{1}}\bra{v_{1}}d^{2}v_{1}d^{2}v_{2}\\
\implies\phi_{1}\left(v_{1}\right) & = & \intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)d^{2}v_{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If the two sources are independent then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)=\phi_{1}\left(v_{1}\right)\phi_{2}\left(v_{2}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.8.6 - (f) with example of a superimposed laser).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the light intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{I}\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simpleInterference"

\end_inset

)? We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle F_{1}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}}+\left\langle F_{2}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{2}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}}+\left\langle F_{1}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{2}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}}+\left\langle F_{2}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}},\label{eq:intensities}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the total field is described by the joint space functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}\left(\left\{ v_{1}\right\} ,\left\{ v_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle  & = & Tr\left(\rho\hat{F}^{-}.\hat{F}^{+}\right)\\
 & = & \int\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)Tr\left(\ket{v}\bra{v}\hat{F}^{-}.\hat{F}^{+}\right)d\left\{ v\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then use the first relation of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:QMequs"

\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \int\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)\braket{v|\hat{I}|v}d\left\{ v\right\} \\
 & = & \int\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)I\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)d\left\{ v\right\} \\
 & = & \int\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)\left[F_{1}^{-}+F_{2}^{-}\right].\left[F_{1}^{+}+F_{2}^{+}\right]dv_{1}dv_{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)=\intop\phi_{12}\left(v_{1},v_{2}\right)d^{2}v_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}^{-}=\hat{F}_{1}^{-}+\hat{F}_{2}^{-}$
\end_inset

.
 Then just expand to obtain the desired result.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For approximately quasi-monchromatic and plane-wave fields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{F}_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right) & \approx & K_{1}\vec{F}^{+}\left(r_{1},t-\tau_{1}\right)\\
\vec{F}_{2}^{+}\left(r,t\right) & \approx & K_{2}\vec{F}^{+}\left(r_{2},t-\tau_{2}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}=\left|r-r_{1}\right|/c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}=\left|r-r_{2}\right|/c$
\end_inset

 are the propagation times from the pinholes to the interference point and
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1},K_{2}\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
?? Not sure why; have to make an analogy to classical optics; although is
 somewhat plausible as if we have plane waves that are monochromatic (then
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

s are no longer vectors) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right) & = & v_{1}\chi\left(r,t,\vec{k}_{1}\right)\\
F^{+}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & v_{1}\chi\left(r_{1},t_{1},k_{1}\right)+v_{2}\chi\left(r_{2},t_{2},k_{2}\right)=v_{1}\left(\chi\left(r_{1},t_{1},k_{1}\right)+\frac{v_{2}}{v_{1}}\chi\left(r_{2},t_{2},k_{2}\right)\right)\\
\implies F_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right) & = & K_{1}F^{+}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is some phase factor.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 And so the cross-correlation terms appearing in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intensities"

\end_inset

 (3rd and 4th terms) can be written as the following 
\emph on
cross-correlation function
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma & \equiv & \left\langle \vec{F}^{-}\left(r_{1},t-\tau_{1}\right).\vec{F}^{+}\left(r_{2},t-\tau_{2}\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle F_{1}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{2}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}}+\left\langle F_{2}^{-}\left(r,t\right).F_{1}^{+}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle _{\phi_{12}} & \approx & K_{1}^{*}K_{2}\left\langle F^{-}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right).F^{+}\left(r_{2},t_{2}\right)\right\rangle +K_{1}K_{2}^{*}\left\langle F^{-}\left(r_{2},t_{2}\right).F^{+}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & 2Re....
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Now we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r,t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left|K_{1}\right|^{2}\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r_{1},t-\tau_{1}\right)\right\rangle +\left|K_{2}\right|^{2}\left\langle \hat{I}\left(r_{2},t-\tau_{2}\right)\right\rangle +2Re\left[K_{1}^{*}K_{2}\left\langle \hat{\vec{F}}^{-}\left(r_{1},t-\tau_{1}\right).\hat{\vec{F}}^{+}\left(r_{2},t-\tau_{2}\right)\right\rangle \right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The generalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 to multiple photodetectors will be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma^{\left(N,N\right)} & = & \left\langle F_{i_{1}}^{-}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right)...F_{i_{1N}}^{-}\left(r_{N},t_{N}\right)F_{i_{N}}^{+}\left(r_{N},t_{N}\right)...F_{i_{1}}^{+}\left(r_{1},t_{1}\right)\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
this generalization is based on form of the probability/intensity of photodetect
ion for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 photodetectors (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:probNphotodetectors"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $P\propto\left\langle F^{-}\left(s_{1},r_{1},t_{1}\right)...F^{-}\left(s_{N},r_{N},t_{N}\right)F^{+}\left(s_{N},r_{N},t_{N}\right)...F^{+}\left(s_{1},r_{1},t_{1}\right)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If we include non-linearities then we might have more positive frequency
 field operators than negative frequency operators or vice versa (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.5).
 The general form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma^{\left(M,N\right)}\left(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{M};y_{1},y_{2},...,y_{N}\right) & = & \left\langle F^{-}\left(x_{1}\right)...F^{-}\left(x_{M}\right)F^{+}\left(y_{m}\right)...F^{+}\left(y_{1}\right)\right\rangle ,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where a symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 stand for a space coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{l}$
\end_inset

, time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{l}$
\end_inset

 and cartesian component 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{l}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.4) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cross spectral density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Theta^{\left(N,M\right)}\left(k_{1},s_{1},...,k_{N},s_{N};k_{M}^{'},s_{M}^{'},...,k_{1}^{'},s_{1}^{'}\right) & = & \left\langle a_{k_{1}s_{1}}^{\dagger}...a_{k_{N}s_{N}}^{\dagger}a_{k_{M}^{'}s_{M}^{'}}...a_{k_{1}^{'}s_{1}^{'}}\right\rangle \\
\implies\Theta^{\left(N,M\right)}\left(k_{1},s_{1},...,k_{N},s_{N};k_{M}^{'},s_{M}^{'},...,k_{1}^{'},s_{1}^{'}\right) & = & \left(\frac{1}{L^{3/2}}\right)^{N+M}\int\Gamma^{\left(N,M\right)}\left(r_{1},t_{1},i_{1},...,r_{N},t_{N},i_{N};r_{M}^{'},t_{M}^{'},j_{M}^{'},...,r_{1}^{'},t_{1}^{'},j_{1}^{'}\right)\\
 &  & \quad\times\prod_{n=1}^{M}\prod_{m=1}^{M}\left[\frac{1}{l^{*}\left(k_{n}\right)}\frac{1}{l\left(k_{m}^{'}\right)}\times\left(\epsilon_{k_{n}s_{n}}\right)_{i_{n}}\left(\epsilon_{k_{m}^{'}s_{m}^{'}}^{*}\right)_{j_{m}}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}_{n}.\vec{r}_{n}-k_{m}^{'}.r_{m}^{'}-\omega_{n}t_{n}+\omega_{m}^{'}t_{m}^{'}\right)\right]d^{3}r_{n}d^{3}r_{m}^{'}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Useful fact: the spectral densities without repeated indices (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq M$
\end_inset

) all vanish when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 is a functional only of the set of moduli 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|v\right|\right\} $
\end_inset

 and vice -versa.
 The same holds for the correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\left(N,M\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.5.2-3) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coherence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma^{\left(1,1\right)}\left(x,y\right) & \equiv & \frac{\Gamma^{\left(1,1\right)}\left(x,y\right)}{\sqrt{\Gamma^{\left(1,1\right)}\left(x,x\right)\Gamma^{\left(1,1\right)}\left(y,y\right)}}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is simply related to the visibility of the intereference fringes that
 are formed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Coherence of up to an arbitary order is difficult to define (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.6).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we have second order coherence then higher order correlation functions
 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma^{\left(N,M\right)}\left(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{N};y_{1},...,y_{N}\right) & \propto & U^{*}\left(x_{1}\right)...U^{*}\left(x_{N}\right)U\left(y_{M}\right)...U\left(y_{1}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the constant of proportionality is equal to 1 for a coherent state
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.7.2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A one photon pure state is second order coherent (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\left(1,1\right)}\left(x,y\right)=1$
\end_inset

) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.7.2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If only one mode is excited (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\rho_{k^{'}s^{'}}\prod_{ks\neq k^{'}s^{'}\ket{0_{ks}}\bra{0_{ks}}}$
\end_inset

) then all correlation functions are factorizable (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.7.3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A field satisfying the condition of second-order coherence must have a density
 operator of a particular form corresponding to the excitation of a only
 one mode (not necessarily a plane wave mode) of arbitrary form (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.7.4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have a 
\emph on
stationary 
\emph default
field if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[H,\rho\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right|$
\end_inset

 then we a sufficient (but not necessary condition for stationarity) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.8.1-2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Implications of stationarity to cross-spectral densities: (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.8.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Analysis of 
\emph on
Homogeneity
\emph default
 (the expectation value of any operator that is a function of position is
 invariant under translation of the origin of space): (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.8.4).
 Analysis of isotropy is given in section 12.8.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Counter and anti-normally ordered correlations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A quantum counter works by emitting (by use of atomic systems) instead of
 absorbing photons (as in a photodetector) which means it is less useful
 because it also measures the spontaneous emission of the atoms which are
 not wanted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.9) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Photon statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ n\right\} $
\end_inset

denote a definite set of photon occupation numbers,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(\left\{ n\right\} \right) & = & Tr\left(\rho\ket{\left\{ n\right\} }\bra{\left\{ n\right\} }\right)\\
 & = & \left\langle \prod_{ks}\left[\frac{\left|v_{ks}\right|^{2n_{ks}}e^{-\left|v_{ks}\right|^{2}}}{n_{ks}!}\right]\right\rangle _{\phi}\\
 & = & \left\langle :\prod_{ks}\left[\frac{\hat{n}_{ks}^{n_{ks}}e^{-\hat{n}_{ks}}}{n_{ks}!}\right]:\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the second equality is the average of a product of Poisson distributions
 with respect to the phase space functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The result is a product of Poisson distributions for coherent states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also show that the distribution for the total number of photons 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(m\right) & = & \left\langle :\frac{\hat{n}^{m}e^{-\hat{n}}}{m!}:\right\rangle .\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This can also be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(m\right) & = & \int P_{U}\left(U^{'}\right)\frac{U^{'m}e^{-U'}}{m!}dU'\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{U}\left(U^{'}\right)=\int\phi\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)\delta\left(U^{'}-U\right)d\left\{ v\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\equiv\sum_{ks}\left|v_{ks}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.10.0-1) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Tests for non-classical states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{o}$
\end_inset

 the probabilities for an even and an odd number of photons then if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{o}>1/2$
\end_inset

 then we have a quantum state without classical analog.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.10.2) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Factorial moment generating function 
\series default
(for definition, see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Factorialmoments"

\end_inset

): We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F\left(\xi\right) & = & \left\langle \left(1-\xi\right)^{\hat{n}}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle e^{-\xi U}\right\rangle _{\phi}\\
 & = & \left\langle :e^{-\xi\hat{n}}:\right\rangle .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{n}^{\left(r\right)}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle U^{r}\right\rangle _{\phi}\\
 & = & \left\langle :\hat{n}^{r}:\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This result is true for any state so that we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{n}^{\left(r\right)} & = & :\hat{n}^{r}:\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \left(\Delta\hat{n}\right)^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \hat{n}\right\rangle +\left\langle \left(\Delta U\right)^{2}\right\rangle _{\phi}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the first term can be interperted as the variance of randomly fluctuating
 particles (like statistical counting error 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

) and to a certain extent, we have that the second term is like the variance
 of fluctuating waves (but for quantum states it can be negative due to
 quasi-probability character of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

).
 A convenient way to characterize non-classical states is with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q & \equiv & \frac{\left\langle \left(\Delta\hat{n}\right)^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \hat{n}\right\rangle }{\left\langle \hat{n}\right\rangle },\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is negative whenever the statistics are 
\emph on
sub-Poissonian 
\emph default
and is at a minimum of -1 for a Fock state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.10.3) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homodyne detection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See section 2.3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

: Mediocre overview.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Scully treatment: Balanced Homodyne detection as applied to photon statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename homodyne.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Homodyne detection; The input field is superimposed on the field from a
 local oscillator (LO) at a lossless beam-splitter of transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and reflectivity 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R+T=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 The different bosonic operators are related by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c & = & \sqrt{T}a+i\sqrt{1-T}b\\
d & = & i\sqrt{1-T}a+\sqrt{T}b
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $R=1-T$
\end_inset

 and that there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

 phase shift between the reflected and transmitted waves for a symmetric
 beam-splitter which we have included by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 TODO: Show explictly that this is the case with the help of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scatteringMatrixBS"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the detectors measure 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\dagger}c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\dagger}d$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we have assumed that the frequency of LO is equal to the input
 frequency so that there is no time dependence.
 We also assume that the transmissivity of the beam-splitter is close to
 unity, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\gg R$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, only the photocurrent from detector 1 is measured and the LO
 mode is assumed to be in a 
\emph on
large
\emph default
 amplitude coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\beta_{l}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{l}$
\end_inset

.
 We can then say that the fluctuations in the photon statistics of detector
 1 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\Delta n_{c}\right)^{2} & = & \left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\left(\left(1-T\right)+4T\left(\Delta X_{\phi+\pi/2}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle c^{\dagger}c\right\rangle  & = & \braket{\psi_{a}\beta_{l}|n_{c}|\psi_{a}\beta_{l}}=T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle \left\langle b\right\rangle -\left\langle b^{\dagger}\right\rangle \left\langle a\right\rangle \right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle \beta_{l}-\beta_{l}^{*}\left\langle a\right\rangle \right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left|\beta_{l}\right|\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle e^{i\phi_{l}}-\left\langle a\right\rangle e^{-i\phi_{l}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left|\beta_{l}\right|\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle e^{i\phi_{l}+i\pi/2}-\left\langle a\right\rangle e^{-i\phi_{l}+i\pi/2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left|\beta_{l}\right|\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle e^{i\phi_{l}+i\pi/2}+\left\langle a\right\rangle e^{-i\phi_{l}-i\pi/2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+2\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left|\beta_{l}\right|\frac{1}{2}\left(\left\langle a^{\dagger}\right\rangle e^{i\phi_{l}+i\pi/2}+\left\langle a\right\rangle e^{-i\phi_{l}-i\pi/2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+2\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle X\left(\phi_{l}+\pi/2\right)\right\rangle ,\label{eq:avgnm}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(\phi\right)=X_{\phi}=\left(ae^{-i\phi}+a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi}\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
 We then make use of the fact that such a strong LO field is used so that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2} & \gg & T\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle \label{eq:bleh}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and we can ignore the first term in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:avgnm}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle c^{\dagger}c\right\rangle  & \approx & \left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+2\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle X\left(\phi_{l}+\pi/2\right)\right\rangle \\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

.
 We can also calculate the photon number fluctuations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\Delta n_{c}\right)^{2} & = & \left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle n_{c}\right\rangle ^{2}\\
n_{c}^{2} & = & Tn_{a}\left(Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right)+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\left(\left(1-T\right)n_{b}+Tn_{a}\right)+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)+\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]-T\left(1-T\right)\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)^{2}\\
n_{c}^{2} & = & Tn_{a}\left(Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right)+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\left(\left(1-T\right)n_{b}+Tn_{a}\right)+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)+\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]-T\left(1-T\right)\left(a^{\dagger2}b^{2}-n_{a}bb^{\dagger}-aa^{\dagger}n_{b}+b^{\dagger2}a^{2}\right)\\
\implies\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle Tn_{a}\left(Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\right)\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left\langle n_{b}^{2}\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)T\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle \\
 &  & +i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\right\rangle +\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\right\rangle -T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi_{l}}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}-n_{a}bb^{\dagger}-aa^{\dagger}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|a^{2}e^{-2i\phi_{l}}\right)\right\rangle \\
\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle Tn_{a}\left(Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\right)\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\left\langle bb^{\dagger}\right\rangle +\left(1-T\right)T\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle \\
 &  & +i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\right\rangle +\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}a\right)\left[Tn_{a}+\left(1-T\right)n_{b}\right]\right\rangle -T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi_{l}}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}-n_{a}bb^{\dagger}-aa^{\dagger}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|a^{2}e^{-2i\phi_{l}}\right)\right\rangle \\
\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & \approx & T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle \left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{4}+\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[T\left(n_{a}a^{\dagger}b-b^{\dagger}n_{a}a\right)+\left(1-T\right)\left(a^{\dagger}n_{b}b-n_{b}b^{\dagger}a\right)\right]\right\rangle +\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[T\left(a^{\dagger}n_{a}b-b^{\dagger}an_{a}\right)+\left(1-T\right)\left(a^{\dagger}bn_{b}-b^{\dagger}n_{b}a\right)\right]\right\rangle -\\
 &  & T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi_{l}}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}-\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle \left(1+\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\right)-aa^{\dagger}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|a^{2}e^{-2i\phi_{l}}\right)\right\rangle \\
\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & \approx & \left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{4}+\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[T\left|\beta_{l}\right|\left(n_{a}a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi_{l}}-n_{a}ae^{-i\phi_{l}}\right)+\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}\left(a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi_{l}}-ae^{-i\phi_{l}}+O\left(1/\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\right)\right)\right]\right\rangle +\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[T\left|\beta_{l}\right|\left(a^{\dagger}n_{a}e^{i\phi_{l}}-an_{a}e^{-i\phi_{l}}\right)+\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}\left(a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi_{l}}-ae^{-i\phi_{l}}+O\left(1/\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\right)\right)\right]\right\rangle -\\
 &  & T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi_{l}}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}-\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle \left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}-aa^{\dagger}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+\left|\beta_{l}^{2}\right|a^{2}e^{-2i\phi_{l}}\right)\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Where we have used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]=aa^{\dagger}-N=I\implies aa^{\dagger}=I+N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle ^{2}\ll T\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bleh}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & \approx & \left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{4}+\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}\left(a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi_{l}}-ae^{-i\phi_{l}}\right)\right]\right\rangle +\\
 &  & i\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left\langle \left[\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}\left(a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi_{l}}-ae^{-i\phi_{l}}\right)\right]\right\rangle -T\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\left\langle \left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi_{l}}-\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle -aa^{\dagger}+a^{2}e^{-2i\phi_{l}}\right)\right\rangle \\
\left\langle n_{c}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{4}+\left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+4\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}\left\langle X_{\phi+\pi/2}\right\rangle +4T\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\left\langle X_{\phi+\pi/2}^{2}\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where again we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bleh}\right)$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\gg\left\langle n_{a}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\phi+\pi/2}=i\left(-ae^{-i\phi}+a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi}\right)/2\implies X_{\phi+\pi/2}^{2}=-\left(a^{2}e^{-2i\phi}+a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\phi}-n_{a}-aa^{\dagger}\right)/4$
\end_inset

.
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle n_{c}\right\rangle ^{2} & = & \left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{4}+4\sqrt{T\left(1-T\right)}\left(1-T\right)\left\langle X\left(\phi_{l}+\pi/2\right)\right\rangle \left|\beta_{l}\right|^{3}+4T\left(1-T\right)\left\langle X\left(\phi_{l}+\pi/2\right)\right\rangle ^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\\
\implies\left(\Delta n_{c}\right)^{2} & = & \left(1-T\right)^{2}\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}+4T\left(1-T\right)\left|\beta_{l}\right|^{2}\left(\Delta X_{\phi+\pi/2}\right)^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{\phi+\pi/2}\equiv\frac{ae^{-i\phi}+a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi}}{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Delta X_{\phi+\pi/2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\phi+\pi/2}$
\end_inset

, the first term is the reflected LO noise (LO shot noise).
 Note that the second term is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $1/4$
\end_inset

 if the input state is squeezed (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\phi}=\left(ae^{-i\phi}+a^{\dagger}e^{i\phi}\right)/2$
\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(to see why go to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:SingleModeSqueezing}$
\end_inset

 and note that in the referenced section 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(\beta\right)=2X_{\phi}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset

) .
 Hence, in practice the input is first blocked to determine the shot-noise
 level then the input is turned on to calculate the variance in reference
 to the shot noise level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 4.4.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "scullyQO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Fabio-balanced-homodyne"

\end_inset

Fabio treatment: Balanced Homodyne detection as applied to measuring quadratures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename scheme of a homodyne detector.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:homodyneFabio"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{L}$
\end_inset

 is a strong coherent laser beam and we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{S}$
\end_inset

 are plane waves.
 Taken from Fig.
 1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fabio2006"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The layout of such a scheme is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:homodyneFabio"

\end_inset

.
 Write the electric fields in the complex amplitude picture: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{S} & \propto & a_{s}e^{-i\omega t}+c.c.\\
E_{L} & \propto & a_{L}e^{-i\omega t}+c.c.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The action of a beam-splitter can be represented by a unitary transformation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
c\\
d
\end{array}\right) & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sqrt{\eta} & \sqrt{1-\eta}e^{i\delta}\\
-\sqrt{1-\eta}e^{-i\delta} & \sqrt{\eta}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{s}\\
a_{L}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & \equiv & U_{BS}\vec{a},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the transmitivity of the BS and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 the phase shift between the transmitted and reflected waves*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Use Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scatteringMatrixBS"

\end_inset

 with the assumption that the BS is symmetric.
 Moreover, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\left|t^{2}\right|=\eta$
\end_inset

.
 We are assuming that the transmitted beam does not experience a phase shift.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|r\right|^{2}+\left|t\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 (see Eqs 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:stokesReciprocityRelations"

\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\sqrt{1-\eta}e^{i\delta}$
\end_inset

).
 We also have to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}t^{'}+t^{*}r^{'}=0$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}=-r^{'}$
\end_inset

 (because 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t^{'}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence that 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{'}=-\sqrt{1-\eta}e^{-i\delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Measure the difference between the output intensities (see Fig, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:homodyneFabio"

\end_inset

) to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle I\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle c^{\dagger}c\right\rangle -\left\langle d^{\dagger}d\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left(\left\langle n_{L}\right\rangle -\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle \right)+2\sqrt{\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left\langle e^{-i\delta}a_{S}^{\dagger}a_{L}+e^{i\delta}a_{S}a_{L}^{\dagger}\right\rangle .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We then use the fact that the local oscillator mode 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{L}$
\end_inset

 is nearly that of an intense coherent field of complex amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{L}$
\end_inset

 and so we will replace 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{L}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{L}$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\left\langle I\right\rangle \approx\left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{2\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|\left\langle X_{\eta-\delta}\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\arg\alpha_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\xi-\delta}$
\end_inset

 is the general quadrature operator: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{\lambda}\equiv\frac{e^{-i\lambda}a_{S}+e^{i\lambda}a_{S}^{\dagger}}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle I\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle c^{\dagger}c\right\rangle -\left\langle d^{\dagger}d\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left(\left\langle n_{L}\right\rangle -\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle \right)+2\sqrt{\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left\langle e^{-i\delta}a_{S}^{\dagger}a_{L}+e^{i\delta}a_{S}a_{L}^{\dagger}\right\rangle \\
 & \approx & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}-\left(1-2\eta\right)\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle +2\sqrt{\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left(\left\langle a_{S}^{\dagger}\right\rangle \alpha_{L}e^{-i\delta}+\left\langle a_{S}\right\rangle \alpha_{L}^{*}e^{i\delta}\right)\\
 & = & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}-\left(1-2\eta\right)\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle +2\sqrt{\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|\left(\left\langle a_{S}^{\dagger}e^{i\left(\xi-\delta\right)}\right\rangle +\left\langle a_{S}e^{-i\left(\xi-\delta\right)}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & = & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}-\left(1-2\eta\right)\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle +\sqrt{2\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|\left\langle X_{\xi-\delta}\right\rangle \\
 & \approx & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{2\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|\left\langle X_{\xi-\delta}\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because we expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle n_{S}\right\rangle \ll\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since the angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 (property of the local oscillator) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 (property of the beam-splitter) can be tuned and we know what 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{L}$
\end_inset

 are, we can measure the expectation value of any quadrature 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 We can also measure the quadrature probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(x,\lambda\right) & = & \braket{x_{\lambda}|\rho}{x_{\lambda}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I & \approx & \left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{2\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|X_{\eta-\delta}\\
\implies X_{\eta-\delta} & \approx & \frac{I-\left(1-2\eta\right)\left|\alpha_{L}\right|^{2}}{\sqrt{2\eta\left(1-\eta\right)}\left|\alpha_{L}\right|}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so the probability distribution of the intensity is directly related
 to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\eta-\delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heterodyne detection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section 2.3.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

: mediocre with not very clear explanations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Coherent states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They are defined to be the right eigenstates of the destruction operator:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a}\ket v & = & v\ket v\\
\implies\bra v\hat{a}^{\dagger} & = & v^{*}\bra v
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and as a result we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \hat{n}\right\rangle  & = & \left|v\right|^{2}\nonumber \\
\left\langle \hat{n}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \left|v\right|^{4}+\left|v\right|^{2}.\label{eq:photonStatisticsCoherentState}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The second equality follows from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle n^{2}\right\rangle  & = & \braket{v|a^{\dagger}aa^{\dagger}a|v}\\
 & = & \braket{v|a^{\dagger}a^{\dagger}aa|v}+\braket{v|a^{\dagger}a|v}\\
 & = & \left|v\right|^{4}+\left|v\right|^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Moreover,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket v & = & e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\ket n
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Displacement Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the 
\emph on
displacement operator
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
displacement operator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
, the operator that creates the coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket v$
\end_inset

 from the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket0=\ket{vac}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{D}\left(v\right) & = & \exp\left(v\hat{a}^{\dagger}-v^{*}\hat{a}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Displacement Operator for Continuum Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We work with the commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{\omega},a_{\omega^{'}}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the continuum description of the displacement operator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(\omega\right)\right\} } & = & \exp\left(\intop d\omega\left[\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right]\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & \equiv & \hat{D}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This can also be written in the equivalent form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(\omega\right)\right\} } & = & \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\int d\omega\left|\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right|^{2}+\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
as can be determined by using the 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff formula (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:baker formula"

\end_inset

) and by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=\intop d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}=-\intop d\omega\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x,y\right]=--\int d\omega\left|\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 and so we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(\omega\right)\right\} } & = & \exp\left(\intop d\omega\left[\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right]\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\int d\omega\left|\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right|^{2}\right)\exp\left(\intop d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)\right)\exp\left(-\intop d\omega\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\int d\omega\left|\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right|^{2}\right)\exp\left(\intop d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We can also work in the time domain with the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\alpha\left(t\right) & = & \left(2\pi\right)^{-1/2}\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\exp\left(-i\omega t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and with this definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(t\right)\right\} } & = & \exp\left(\int dt\left[\alpha\left(t\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(t\right)\hat{a}\left(t\right)\right]\right)\ket{vac}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We can also calculate that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{D}^{\dagger}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\hat{a}_{\Omega}\hat{D}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right) & = & \hat{a}_{\Omega}+\alpha\left(\Omega\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
where in the first line we used the operato expansion theorem (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:operatorExpansionTheorem"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\equiv-\intop d\omega\left[\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[A,a_{\Omega}\right]=-\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\left[\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right),a_{\Omega}\right]=\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\delta\left(\omega-\Omega\right)=\alpha\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 number and so higher order terms vanish.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
(from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blow1990"

\end_inset

 section II-A)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now generalize some of the above results with a more general commutation
 relation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{\omega},a_{\omega^{'}}^{\dagger}\right]=c_{1}\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

 and a more general definition of the displacement operator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(\omega\right)\right\} } & = & \exp\left(c_{2}\intop d\omega\left[\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right]\right)\ket{vac}\\
 & \equiv & \hat{D}_{c_{1},c_{2}}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(for the above equation to be true, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 would have to be related.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\left\{ \alpha\left(\omega\right)\right\} }\neq\hat{D}_{c_{1},c_{2}}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\ket{vac}$
\end_inset

).
 As a consequence, we now have that 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{D}_{c_{1}c_{2}}^{\dagger}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right)\hat{a}_{\Omega}\hat{D}_{c_{1}c_{2}}\left(\alpha\left(\omega\right)\right) & = & \hat{a}_{\Omega}+c_{1}c_{2}\alpha\left(\Omega\right).\label{eq:general displacement transformation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
where in the first line we used the operator expansion theorem (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:operatorExpansionTheorem"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(\hat{A}\right)\hat{B}\exp\left(-\hat{A}\right)=\hat{B}+\left[\hat{A},\hat{B}\right]+\frac{1}{2!}\left[\hat{A},\left[\hat{A},\hat{B}\right]\right]+\frac{1}{3!}\left[\hat{A},\left[\hat{A},\left[\hat{A},\hat{B}\right]\right]\right]+...$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\equiv-c_{2}\intop d\omega\left[\alpha\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)-\alpha^{*}\left(\omega\right)\hat{a}\left(\omega\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[A,a_{\Omega}\right]=-c_{2}\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\left[\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right),a_{\Omega}\right]=c_{1}c_{2}\int d\omega\alpha\left(\omega\right)\delta\left(\omega-\Omega\right)=c_{1}c_{2}\alpha\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 number and so higher order terms vanish.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:The-displacement-transformation"

\end_inset

The displacement transformation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
displacement transformation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\psi} & = & D^{\dagger}\ket{\psi}\\
O & \rightarrow & D^{\dagger}OD
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

leaves the physics invariant*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\rho & = & -\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H,\rho\right]\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The displacement operator is a unitary transformation so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(D^{\dagger}\rho D\right) & = & -\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[D^{\dagger}HD,D^{\dagger}\rho D\right],\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unitary transformation of a commutator"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Single mode laser: see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Simple-analysis-of single mode laser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
q-Representation (q wavefunction of a coherent state)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's find the coordinate representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{v}\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 of a coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket v$
\end_inset

, where (section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:Harmonic-Oscillator}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{q} & = & \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega}}\left[\hat{a}+\hat{a}^{\dagger}\right]\\
\hat{p} & = & i\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2}}\left[\hat{a}^{\dagger}-\hat{a}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

TODO: COMPLETE THE DERIVATION (RESULT IS A GAUSSIAN) 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{q|\hat{a}}v & = & v\left\langle q|v\right\rangle =v\psi_{v}\left(q\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but we know that from the Harmonic oscillator relations (section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:Harmonic-Oscillator}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{a} & = & \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\hbar\omega}}\left[\omega\hat{q}+i\hat{p}\right]\\
\hat{a}^{\dagger} & = & \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\hbar\omega}}\left[\omega\hat{q}-i\hat{p}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{q|\underbrace{\sqrt{\frac{1}{2\hbar\omega}}\left[\omega\hat{q}+i\hat{p}\right]}_{\hat{a}}}v & = & \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\hbar\omega}}\left[\omega q+\hbar\partial_{q}\right]\psi_{v}\left(q\right)\\
 & = & v\psi_{v}\left(q\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with a general solution that is a Gaussian because of the differential equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{v}\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfied.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Time evolution and expectation values of elementary operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time evolution of a coherent state is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\ket{v\left(t\right)} & = & e^{-i\omega t}\ket{ve^{-i\omega t}}.\label{eq:time evo}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{v\left(t\right)} & = & \exp\left(-i\hat{H}t/\hbar\right)\ket{v}\\
 & = & \exp\left(-i\omega\left(\hat{n}+\frac{1}{2}\right)t\right)\ket{v}=\exp\left(-i\omega t/2\right)\left[e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}e^{-i\omega t\hat{n}}\ket{n}\right]\\
 & = & \exp\left(-i\omega t/2\right)\left[e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}e^{-i\omega tn}\ket{n}\right]\\
 & = & \exp\left(-i\omega t/2\right)\left[e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\left(ve^{-i\omega t}\right)^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\ket{n}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Note that this is a coherent state with complex eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $ve^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the above relation we also obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle q\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left(\frac{2\hbar}{\omega}\right)^{1/2}\left|v\right|\cos\left(\omega t-\arg v\right)\label{eq:qHO}\\
\left\langle p\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & -\sqrt{2\hbar\omega}\left|v\right|\sin\left(\omega t-\arg v\right).\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We first use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:time evo}\right)$
\end_inset

to straightforwardly obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v|\hat{a}\left(t\right)|v} & = & ve^{-i\omega t}\\
\left\langle \hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & v^{*}e^{i\omega t}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We then use the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:harmEq}$
\end_inset

)to obtain their time dependence.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle q\left(t\right)\right\rangle  & = & \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega}}\left(ve^{-i\omega t}+c.c.\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2\omega}}\left|v\right|\left(e^{i\arg v-i\omega t}+c.c.\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{2\frac{\hbar}{\omega}}\left|v\right|\cos\left(\omega t-\arg v\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that these results are very similar to that of a harmonic oscillator.
 Indeed for a classical HO 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x\left(t\right) & \propto & \cos\left(wt+\phi\right)\\
v\left(t\right) & \propto & -\omega\sin\left(\omega t+\phi\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As can easily be shown by solving the simple DE 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}} & = & -kx\\
\omega & = & \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.5).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uncertainty relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not to be deduced from the previous subsection or from the fact that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left(\Delta a\right)^{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 (because the coherent state is a right eigenstate of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

) that a quantum oscillator in a coherent state behaves like a classical
 harmonic oscillator because we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\left\langle \Delta q^{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \Delta p^{2}\right\rangle }=\hbar/2$
\end_inset

 (which is a minimum uncertainty relation so in a way the real field behaves
 as close to a classical field as possible).
 Also, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right|\gg1$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta q\left(t\right)^{2}\right\rangle \ll\left\langle q\left(t\right)\right\rangle ^{2}$
\end_inset

 (as can be seen from eq.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:qHO}$
\end_inset

 and it can be easily calculated that from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta q\left(t\right)^{2}\right\rangle =\hbar/2\omega$
\end_inset

) so that the deviation from classical behavior for a large coherent state
 is negligible.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.5).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:OverCompleteness"

\end_inset

Over-completeness and other properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coherent states are eigenstates of a non-Hermitian operator, so they
 have some unusual properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\braket{v_{1}}{v_{2}}\right|^{2}=e^{-\left|v_{1}-v_{2}\right|^{2}}\neq\delta_{v_{1},v_{2}}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle v_{2}|v_{1}\right\rangle  & = & e^{-\left(\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}\right)/2}\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v_{1}^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\frac{v_{2}^{*m}}{\sqrt{m!}}\braket{m|n}\\
 & = & e^{-\left(\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}\right)/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\left(v_{1}v_{2}^{*}\right)^{n}}{n!}\\
 & = & e^{-\left(\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}\right)/2}e^{v_{1}v_{2}^{*}}=\exp\left(-\left(\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}-2v_{1}v_{2}^{*}\right)/2\right)\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\left(\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}-v_{1}v_{2}^{*}-v_{1}v_{2}^{*}\right)/2\right)\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\left|v_{1}-v_{2}\right|^{2}/2\right)\exp\left(-\left(v_{2}v_{1}^{*}-v_{1}v_{2}^{*}\right)/2\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v_{1}-v_{2}\right|^{2}=\left(v_{1}-v_{2}\right)\left(v_{1}^{*}-v_{2}^{*}\right)=\left|v_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|v_{2}\right|^{2}-v_{2}v_{1}^{*}-v_{1}v_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 And so no two coherent states are ever orthogonal.
 Note that because of the exponential 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\left|v_{1}-v_{2}\right|^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (which takes on some of the character of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{2}\left(v_{1}-v_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

), most states are almost orthogonal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Completeness - relation
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\intop\ket v\bra vd^{2}v,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}v=d\left(\mbox{Re}v\right)d\left(\mbox{Im}v\right)$
\end_inset

is over the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $v-$
\end_inset

plane
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop\ket{v}\bra{v}d^{2}v & = & \intop\ket{v}\bra{v}d\left(\mbox{Re}v\right)d\left(\mbox{Im}v\right)\\
 & = & \intop_{0}^{\infty}rdr\intop_{0}^{2\pi}d\theta e^{-\left(\left|v\right|^{2}+\left|v\right|^{2}\right)/2}\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v^{n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\frac{v^{*m}}{\sqrt{m!}}\ket{n}\bra{m}\\
 & = & \intop_{0}^{\infty}dr\intop_{0}^{2\pi}d\theta e^{-r^{2}}\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{r^{n+m+1}}{\sqrt{n!}}\frac{e^{i\left(n-m\right)\theta}}{\sqrt{m!}}\ket{n}\bra{m}\\
 & = & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{2\pi}{n!}\frac{1}{2}n!\ket{n}\bra{n}\\
 & = & \pi\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\ket{n}\bra{n}=\pi,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where from Mathematica we obtained that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop_{0}^{2\pi}e^{i\left(n-m\right)\theta}d\theta & = & \begin{cases}
\frac{i}{n-m}\left(1-e^{2\pi i\left(n-m\right)}\right)=0 & n\neq m\\
2\pi & n=m
\end{cases}\\
 & = & 2\pi\delta_{nm}\\
\intop_{0}^{\infty}r^{n+m+1}e^{-r^{2}}dr & = & \frac{1}{2}\Gamma\left(\left(2+m+n\right)/2\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(n\right)!
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are integers and after application of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It can be easily shown that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
0 & = & \intop\ket v\left[\frac{1}{\pi}e^{-\left|v-v^{'}\right|/2}e^{\left(v^{*}v^{'}-vv^{'*}\right)/2}-\delta^{2}\left(v-v^{'}\right)\right]d^{2}v\quad\mbox{for any \ensuremath{v^{'}}}\\
0 & = & \intop\ket vf\left(\left|v\right|\right)v^{n}d^{2}v\quad\mbox{for n}=0,1,2,...\mbox{ and for any \ensuremath{f}for which the integral exists}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The set is over-complete in that the set of states cannot be made exactly
 complete by substraction of a countable number of coherent states from
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.6).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Normal order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An operator is said to be in 
\emph on
normal order 
\emph default
if it is expressible as a sum of products of creation and annihilation operators
, with the creation operators always standing to the left of the annihilation
 operators; e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a^{\dagger n}a^{n+2}/n!$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)$
\end_inset

 be such an operator then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v^{'}|f\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)}{v^{''}} & = & f\left(v^{''},v^{'*}\right)e^{-\left|v^{'}-v^{''}\right|^{2}/2}e^{\left(v^{'*}v^{''}-v^{'}v^{''*}\right)/2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v^{'}|f\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)|v^{''}} & = & \sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}c_{n}d_{m}\braket{v^{'}|a^{\dagger n}a^{m}|v^{''}}\\
 & = & \sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}c_{n}d_{m}v^{'*n}v^{''m}\braket{v^{'}|v^{''}}\\
 & = & f\left(v^{''},v^{'*}\right)e^{-\left|v^{'}-v^{''}\right|^{2}/2}e^{\left(v^{'*}v^{''}-v^{'}v^{''*}\right)/2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have made use of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle v_{2}|v_{1}\right\rangle  & = & \exp\left(-\left|v_{1}-v_{2}\right|^{2}/2\right)\exp\left(-\left(v_{2}v_{1}^{*}-v_{1}v_{2}^{*}\right)/2\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(see the note in section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:OverCompleteness}$
\end_inset

 point 1).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.6.3-4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unique representation and usefulness of over-completeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An expansion of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}=\intop\ket v\braket{v|\psi}d^{2}v/\pi$
\end_inset

 is not unique because of the relations in section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:OverCompleteness}$
\end_inset

 point 3.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket v{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is unique: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket v{\psi} & = & e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{v^{*n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\left\langle n|\psi\right\rangle \\
 & \equiv & e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}F_{\psi}\left(v^{*}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $F_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is an entire analytic function (i.e.
 has a taylor series everywhere on the complex plane) that is a representation
 of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 The neat feature of entire functions is that uniquely determined by its
 values within some finite range - no matter how small.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Is this because an entire function can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f=u+iv$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are harmonic functions ??? (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fisherCA"

\end_inset

 section 2.1 and the Cauchy Riemann equations section).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A more rigorous reason in the context of coherent states is that say 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

 differ by some state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\chi}$
\end_inset

 but over some range 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

 are the same then they must be the same everywhere because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{v|\chi}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\chi}$
\end_inset

 is the null vector because all of the coherent states are linearly dependent:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v|\chi} & \propto & \intop\braket{v|v^{'}}\braket{v^{'}|\chi}\\
 & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{v|v^{'}}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{'}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{v^{'}|\chi}$
\end_inset

 must be equal to 0.
 This can be generalized: an entire function that vanishes in a finite range
 must vanish everywhere to remain analytic.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
A representation for positive definite Hermitian and traceable operators
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 in terms of coherent states
\emph default
: We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v|\hat{A}}{v^{'}} & = & e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}/2}e^{-\left|v^{'}\right|^{2}/2}\sum_{n=0}\sum_{m=0}\frac{v^{*n}}{\sqrt{n!}}\frac{v^{'m}}{\sqrt{m!}}\braket{n|\hat{A}}m\\
 & \equiv & \exp\left(-\left(\left|v\right|^{2}+\left|v^{'}\right|^{2}\right)/2\right)F_{A}\left(v^{*},v^{'}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $F_{A}$
\end_inset

 is also an entire analytic function 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, we first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{a}$
\end_inset

 is convergent: 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{n|\hat{A}|m}$
\end_inset

 is bounded because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A} & = & \sum_{i}\lambda_{i}\ket{\lambda_{i}}\bra{\lambda_{i}}\\
\implies\braket{n|\hat{A}|m} & = & \sum_{i}\lambda_{i}\braket{n|\lambda_{i}}\braket{\lambda_{i}|m}\\
\implies\left|\braket{n|\hat{A}|m}\right| & \leq & \sum_{i}\lambda_{i}\left|\braket{n|\lambda_{i}}\right|\left|\braket{\lambda_{i}|m}\right|\leq Tr\hat{A}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so we only need to know 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{A}$
\end_inset

 over a small range of 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{'}$
\end_inset

 to completely determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

.
 (In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{v|\hat{A}}v$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in a small range is all we need 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{n|\hat{A}|m} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{n!m!}}\left[\frac{\partial^{n+m}\braket{v|\hat{A}|v}e^{\left|v\right|^{2}}}{\partial v^{*n}\partial v^{m}}\right]_{v^{*}=0;v=0}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and once the 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{n|\hat{A}|m}$
\end_inset

 have been determined, we can determine the off-diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{v|\hat{A}|v^{'}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.7).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:p representation"

\end_inset

Diagonal coherent state representation of the density operator (Glauber-Sudarsha
n P-representation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Glauber-Sudarshan P-representation
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The density operator has a representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)\ket v\bra vd^{2}v
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Suppose the density operator has an anti-normal expansion of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \sum_{nm}C_{nm}a^{n}a^{\dagger m}\\
 & = & \sum_{nm}C_{nm}\frac{1}{\pi}\intop a^{n}\ket{v}\bra{v}a^{\dagger m}d^{2}v\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\intop\left(\sum_{nm}\frac{C_{nm}}{\pi}v^{n}v^{*m}\right)\ket{v}\bra{v}d^{2}v\\
 & \equiv & \intop\frac{\rho^{\left(A\right)}\left(v,v^{*}\right)}{\pi}\ket{v}\bra{v}d^{2}v.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

A more general formal derivation can be found in (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.10).
 (this is a double integral)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 is called a phase space density/weight function (and is sometimes denoted
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

) and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop\phi\left(v\right)d^{2}v=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This comes out from the unit trace condition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1 & = & Tr\rho\\
 & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)\sum_{n}\left|\braket{n|v}\right|^{2}d^{2}v\\
 & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}}\sum_{n}\frac{\left|v\right|^{2n}}{n!}d^{2}v\\
 & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}}e^{\left|v\right|^{2}}d^{2}v
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 behaves like a normal probability distribution (i.e.
 is non-negative and is not more singular than the delta function) then
 - by definition - we have a classical state of light (the idea is that
 coherent states are analaguous to a classical field of complex amplitude
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 so a distribution of them is also classical).
 Another consequence of the definition is that (ignoring the vacuum state
 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)=\delta^{2}\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 (probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 photons) is always 
\begin_inset Formula $>0$
\end_inset

 for a classical state
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(n\right) & = & Tr\left(\rho\ket{n}\bra{n}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{i}\frac{1}{\pi}\intop\phi\left(v\right)\braket{i|v}\braket{v|n}\braket{n|i}\\
 & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}}\frac{\left|v\right|^{2}}{n!}d^{2}v
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}}\frac{\left|v\right|^{2}}{n!}$
\end_inset

 is always positive so if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is classical then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(n\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.8-0,2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible integral representation is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\phi\left(v\right)e^{-\left|v\right|^{2}} & = & \frac{1}{\pi^{2}}\intop e^{\left|u\right|^{2}}\braket{-u|\rho}ue^{-uv^{*}+u*v}d^{2}u,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket u$
\end_inset

 is a coherent state and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-uv^{*}+u*v}$
\end_inset

 is like a Fourier Kernel
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=p+iq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=P+iQ$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-uv^{*}+u^{*}v}=\exp\left(2i\left(pQ-qP\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (because of the 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\left|u\right|^{2}}$
\end_inset

 we have to be careful with convergence; 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 might be a generalized function).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.8.5; good examples in section 11.8.6).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:opticaEquivalence"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Optical equivalence theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset

Optical equivalence theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle g^{\left(N\right)}\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)\right\rangle  & = & \int\phi\left(v\right)g^{\left(N\right)}\left(v,v^{*}\right)d^{2}v.\\
 & \equiv & \left\langle g^{\left(N\right)}\left(v,v^{*}\right)\right\rangle _{\phi},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\left(N\right)}\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a normally ordered function of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\dagger}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Use 
\begin_inset Formula $Tr\ket A\bra B=\left\langle A|B\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (proven in section
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:QMequs}$
\end_inset

) to write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(\rho g^{\left(N\right)}\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)\right) & = & Tr\left(\intop\phi\left(v\right)\sum_{nm}c_{nm}\ket v\bra va^{\dagger n}a^{m}d^{2}v\right)\\
 & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)\sum_{nm}c_{nm}\braket{v|a^{\dagger n}a^{m}|v}d^{2}v
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and remember 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \intop\phi\left(v\right)\ket v\bra vd^{2}v\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Anti-normal order
\end_layout

\end_inset

Anti-normal order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that for an anti-normally ordered function that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle f^{A}\left(\left\{ a\right\} ,\left\{ a^{\dagger}\right\} \right)\right\rangle  & = & \int Q\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right)f^{A}\left(\left\{ v\right\} .\left\{ v*\right\} \right)d\left\{ v\right\} \\
 & \equiv & \left\langle f^{A}\left(\left\{ v\right\} .\left\{ v*\right\} \right)\right\rangle _{Q}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q\left(\left\{ v\right\} \right) & = & \braket{\left\{ v\right\} |\rho}{\left\{ v\right\} }\prod_{\left[k,s\right]}\left[\frac{1}{\pi}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[k,s\right]$
\end_inset

 denotes a set of all the possible modes.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is mathematically well behaved (non-negative and bounded) but there is
 little correspondance between it and the classical phase space function
 (but for states for which a classical limit exists, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

- the p-functional (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:p representation"

\end_inset

) which would be exactly equal to the classical phase space function - tend
 to become equal in the classical limit).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 12.9.3) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Wigner Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wigner distribution is used to characterize the quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 in phase space and is defined to be: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W\left(q,p\right) & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\braket{q+\frac{1}{2}\hbar x|\rho}{q-\frac{1}{2}\hbar x}e^{ixp}dx,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket p$
\end_inset

 denote position and momentum, respectively.
 It can be shown that for a Weyl-ordered function (i.e.
 a function that is symmetric wrt to the order of the operators, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pq+qp$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}p+qpq+pq^{2}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle F^{\left(W\right)}\left(\hat{q},\hat{p}\right)\right\rangle  & = & \intop F^{\left(W\right)}\left(q,p\right)W\left(q,p\right)dqdp
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 acts like a 'joint probability distribution' (but may not be necessarily
 positive or less singular than a delta function); it is called a 
\emph on
quasi-probability density
\emph default
 and so is not directly measurable.
 We also have that for pure states 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop W\left(q,p\right)dp & = & \left|\psi\left(q\right)\right|^{2}\\
\intop W\left(q,p\right)dq & = & \left|\psi\left(p\right)\right|^{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{2\pi}\intop\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\braket{q+\frac{1}{2}\hbar x|\rho|q-\frac{1}{2}\hbar x}e^{ixp}dxdp & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\psi^{*}\left(q-\frac{1}{2}\hbar x\right)\psi\left(q+\frac{1}{2}\hbar x\right)\left(\intop\frac{e^{ixp}}{2\pi}dp\right)dx\\
 & = & \intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\psi^{*}\left(q-\frac{1}{2}\hbar x\right)\psi\left(q+\frac{1}{2}\hbar x\right)\delta\left(x\right)dx
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.8.1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W\left(x,p\right) & = & Tr\left[e^{ix\hat{X}+ip\hat{P}}\hat{\rho}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Squeezed states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:SingleModeSqueezing"

\end_inset

Introduction/Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, consider a 
\emph on
specific case
\emph default
: Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q^{'} & = & a^{\dagger}+a\\
P^{'} & = & i\left(a^{\dagger}-a\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[Q^{'},P^{'}\right] & = & 2i.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[Q^{'},P^{'}\right] & = & i\left[\left(a^{\dagger2}-a^{2}+aa^{\dagger}-a^{\dagger}a\right)-\left(a^{\dagger2}-a^{2}+a^{\dagger}a-aa^{\dagger}\right)\right]\\
 & = & i\left(\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]+\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]\right)=2i.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Hence, they behave like dimensionless canonical conjugates and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sqrt{\left\langle \Delta Q^{'2}\right\rangle \left\langle \Delta P^{'2}\right\rangle } & \geq & 1.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x,p\right]=i\hbar$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\left\langle \Delta x^{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \Delta p^{2}\right\rangle }\geq\hbar/2$
\end_inset

).
 It can also be calculated by the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{'}$
\end_inset

 that the relation is exactly satisfied for a coherent state because then
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\braket{v|\Delta Q^{'2}}v & = & 1\\
\braket{v|\Delta P^{'2}}v & = & 1.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename squeezed_phase space.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic diagram of the uncertainty areas in the generalized coordinate
 and momentum (X, P) phase space of a photon squeezed state (ellipse) and
 a coherent state (circle).
 In quantum optics, X and P are the two quadratures of the electric field.
 Notice that the coherent state has the same uncertainty area as the vacuum
 state (circle at the origin), and that its area is circular, while the
 squeezed state has an elliptical uncertainty area.
 Therefore, in the direction parallel to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

/2 line, the squeezed state has a smaller noise than the coherent state.
 Image Source: X.
 Hu, Quantum Fluctuations In Condensed Matter Systems, UM Ph.D.
 Thesis 1997, Page 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
General quadratures 
\emph default
can be accommodated with the definition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q\left(\beta\right) & = & a^{\dagger}e^{i\beta}+ae^{-i\beta}\label{eq:defQ}\\
P\left(\beta\right) & = & a^{\dagger}e^{i\left(\beta+\pi/2\right)}+ae^{-i\left(\beta+\pi/2\right)}.\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

These also satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q,P\right]=2i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[Q,P\right] & = & i\left[\left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\beta}-a^{2}e^{-2i\beta}+aa^{\dagger}-a^{\dagger}a\right)-\left(a^{\dagger2}e^{2i\beta}-a^{2}e^{-2i\beta}+a^{\dagger}a-aa^{\dagger}\right)\right]\\
 & = & i\left(\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]+\left[a,a^{\dagger}\right]\right)=2i.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Definition of a squeezed state
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists$
\end_inset

 a direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta Q^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is smaller than that of the corresponding vacuum state, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta Q^{2}\right\rangle <1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Interpertation through the electric field picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electric field for a single mode (single frequency), linearly polarized
 field is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & l\left(\omega\right)\vec{\epsilon}\left[ae^{i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}+c.c.\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

is some real function of frequency (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 11.5).
 From the definitions (
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:defQ}$
\end_inset

), we can then write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & l\left(\omega\right)\vec{\epsilon}\left(Q\cos\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t+\beta\right)-P\sin\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t+\beta\right)\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The visual representation of a coherent/squeezed state is shown below:
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename squeezing_efield.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the above, take 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}=P^{'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=Q^{'}$
\end_inset

.
 Taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "scullyQO"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $(b)$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a reduced amplitude uncertainty squeezed state while
 subfigure
\begin_inset Formula $\left(c\right)$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a squeezed state with reduced phase uncertainty.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mathematical treatment of single mode squeezing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the 
\emph on
squeeze operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S\left(z\right) & = & \exp\left[\frac{1}{2}\left(z^{*}a^{2}-za^{\dagger2}\right)\right]\\
z & = & re^{i\theta}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\emph default
We shall study 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{z,v}$
\end_inset

 that is the eigenvector of the unitary transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 (it is called the the 
\emph on
two-photon coherent state
\emph default
):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A\left(z\right) & = & S\left(z\right)aS^{\dagger}\left(z\right)\\
 & = & \mu a+\nu a^{\dagger}\\
\mu & \equiv & \cosh r\\
\nu & \equiv & e^{i\theta}\sinh r.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A & = & \sum_{n}\sum_{m}\frac{\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(z^{*}a^{2}-za^{\dagger2}\right)\right)^{m}}{m!}a\frac{\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n}}{n!}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,f\left(a,a^{\dagger}\right)\right]=\partial_{a^{\dagger}}f$
\end_inset

 (section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:identitiesQO}$
\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n} & = & \left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n}a+nza^{\dagger}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n-1}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

we got this by using the binomial expansion on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:QMequs}$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)^{n} & = & (A+B)^{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}S_{k}^{n}(a+b)^{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{k}S_{k}^{n}C_{j}^{k}A^{k-j}B^{j}\\
 & = & \sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{k}S_{k}^{n}C_{j}^{k}z^{k-j}a^{\dagger2\left(k-j\right)}B^{j}\\
\implies\partial_{a^{\dagger}}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)^{n} & = & \sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{k}S_{k}^{n}C_{j}^{k}z^{k-j}2\left(k-j\right)a^{\dagger2\left(k-j\right)-1}B^{j}\\
 & = & za^{\dagger}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{k}S_{k}^{n}C_{j}^{k}z^{k-j-1}2\left(k-j\right)a^{\dagger2\left(k-j-1\right)}B^{j}\\
 & = & 2za^{\dagger}\sum_{b=-1}^{n-1}\sum_{j=0}^{b+1}\left(b+1\right)S_{b+1}^{n}C_{j}^{b}z^{b-j}a^{\dagger2\left(b-j\right)}B^{j}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 only goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 because we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k-j\right)=\left(b+1-j\right)=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $j=b+1$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $b=-1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b+1-j\right)=-j=0$
\end_inset

 so the 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 limit is useless.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1=b$
\end_inset

 and in our case we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{j}^{k}\times\left(k-j\right) & = & \frac{k!}{\left(k-j-1\right)!j!}=kC_{j}^{b}\\
S_{k}^{n} & = & \begin{cases}
\frac{n!}{2^{\frac{n-k}{2}}\left(\frac{n-k}{2}\right)!k!}\\
0 & n-k\; odd
\end{cases}\\
\implies S_{b+1}^{n}\left(b+1\right) & = & \begin{cases}
\frac{n!}{2^{\frac{n-b-1}{2}}\left(\frac{n-b-1}{2}\right)!b!}\\
0 & n-b-1\; odd
\end{cases}\\
 & = & nS_{b}^{n-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\partial_{a^{\dagger}}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)^{n} & = & 2nza^{\dagger}\sum_{b=0}^{n-1}\sum_{j=0}^{b}S_{b}^{n-1}C_{j}^{b}z^{b-j}a^{\dagger2\left(b-j\right)}B^{j}\\
 & = & 2nza^{\dagger}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)^{n-1}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Continuing with calculating what 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A & = & \sum_{n}\sum_{m}\frac{\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(z^{*}a^{2}-za^{\dagger2}\right)\right)^{m}}{m!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n}a+\sum_{n}\sum_{m}\frac{\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(z^{*}a^{2}-za^{\dagger2}\right)\right)^{m}}{m!}nza^{\dagger}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(za^{\dagger2}-z^{*}a^{2}\right)\right)^{n-1}...\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This approach doesn't work (because we still have an 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 between two operators that it doesn't commute with) - just use approach
 of the book!!! or can try to expand 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(z^{*}a^{2}-za^{\dagger2}\right)\right)^{m}$
\end_inset

 directly at the beginning of the calculation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
squeeze parameter
\emph default
.
 Turns out that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{z,v} & = & S\left(z\right)\ket v\\
\implies A\ket{z,v} & = & v\ket{z,v}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
SaS^{\dagger}\left(S\ket{v}\right) & = & Sa\ket{v}\\
 & = & v\left(S\ket{v}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The dispersion of the quadratures defined in equs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:defQ}$
\end_inset

 is at a minimum for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\theta/2$
\end_inset

 at which point 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \Delta Q_{\beta=\theta/2}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & e^{-2r}\\
\left\langle \Delta P_{\beta=\theta/2}^{2}\right\rangle  & = & e^{2r}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Notice that this is a minimum uncertainty state: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta Q_{\beta=\theta/2}^{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \Delta P_{\beta=\theta/2}^{2}\right\rangle =1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.3.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can also be shown that the squeeze operator acting on any quantum state
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\rightarrow S\rho S^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

) reduces the dispersion of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 by the same factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-2r}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.3.2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ideal squeezed state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal squeezed is obtained by having acting 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(z\right)D\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 on the vacuum state.
 The 
\emph on
ideal squeezed state
\emph default
 is obtained by acting 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(v\right)S\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 on the vacuum state and has been called such because of its simple properties.
 It is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left(v,z\right)} & = & D\left(v\right)S\left(z\right)\ket{vac}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

They are related to the two-photon coherent state by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\left(v,z\right)} & = & \ket{z,v_{+}}\\
\ket{z,v} & = & \ket{\left(v_{-},z\right)}\\
v_{\pm} & = & \mu v\pm\nu v^{*}\\
\implies A\ket{\left(v,z\right)} & = & v_{+}\ket{\left(v,z\right)}\\
\braket{\left(v,z\right)|a|\left(v,z\right)} & = & v\\
\mbox{whereas }\braket{\left[z,v\right]|a|\left[z,v\right]} & = & v_{-}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The last two relations illustrate the simplicity of the ideal squeezed state:
 the ellipse in phase space characterizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\left(v,z\right)}$
\end_inset

 is centered on 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{z,v}$
\end_inset

 is centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Photon statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mandelQO"

\end_inset

 section 21.4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear Quantum system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, such a system has a hamiltonian that is at most quadratic
 in its canonical coordinates and momenta.
 Hence, the most general hamiltonian can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{H}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{ij}L_{2}^{ij}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{i}\hat{C}_{j}+\sum_{i}L_{1}^{i}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{i}+L_{0}\left(t\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we further impose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 be symmetric*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
a hamiltonian is hermitian which means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H & = & H^{\dagger}\\
\implies\sum_{ij}L_{2}^{ij}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{i}\hat{C}_{j}+\sum_{i}L_{1}^{i}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{i}+L_{0}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{ij}L_{2}^{*ij}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{j}\hat{C}_{i}+\sum_{i}L_{1}^{*i}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{i}+L_{0}^{*}\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because the observables 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 are hermitian and so the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

s have to be real.
 We also have the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
L_{2}^{ij}\hat{C}_{j}\hat{C}_{i} & = & L_{2}^{ji}\hat{C}_{j}\hat{C}_{i}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{ij}$
\end_inset

 has to be symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
i\hbar\frac{d\hat{C}_{jH}\left(t\right)}{dt} & = & \sum_{lm}2L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{mH}\left(t\right)+\sum_{l}L_{1}^{l}\left(t\right)C_{jl},\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 denotes the Heisenberg picture and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{jl}\equiv\left[\hat{C}_{jS},\hat{C}_{lS}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 number denoting the commutator between canonical operators*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}$
\end_inset

 the time evolution operator then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
i\hbar\frac{d\hat{C}_{jH}\left(t\right)}{dt} & = & U^{\dagger}\left[\hat{C}_{j},\hat{H}\right]U\\
 & = & U^{\dagger}\left(\sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)\left[\hat{C}_{j},\hat{C}_{l}\hat{C}_{m}\right]\right)U+\sum_{l}L_{1}^{l}\left(t\right)C_{jl}+0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)\left[\hat{C}_{j},\hat{C}_{l}\hat{C}_{m}\right] & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)\left(\left[\hat{C}_{j},\hat{C}_{l}\right]\hat{C}_{m}+\hat{C}_{l}\left[\hat{C}_{j},\hat{C}_{m}\right]\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)\left(C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}+C_{jm}\hat{C}_{l}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}+\sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jm}\hat{C}_{l}\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}+\sum_{lm}L_{2}^{ml}\left(t\right)C_{jm}\hat{C}_{l}\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}+\sum_{ml}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}+\sum_{lm}L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}\\
 & = & \sum_{lm}2L_{2}^{lm}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\hat{C}_{m}\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the before last equality we just interchange the order of summation
 and in the fifth equality we rename the indices of summation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This has a solution of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{C}_{jH}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{k}\alpha_{jk}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{k}+\beta_{j}\left(t\right)\label{eq:time evolution Cjh}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Plugging this trial solution in the previous D.E.
 we want that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{k}\partial_{t}\alpha_{jk}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{k}+\partial_{t}\beta_{j} & = & \frac{1}{i\hbar}\sum_{k}\left(\sum_{l}2L_{2}^{lk}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\right)\hat{C}_{kH}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{i\hbar}\sum_{l}L_{1}^{l}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{i\hbar}\sum_{k}\left(\sum_{l}2L_{2}^{lk}\left(t\right)C_{jl}\right)\left(\sum_{a}\alpha_{ka}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{a}+\beta_{k}\left(t\right)\right)+\frac{1}{i\hbar}\sum_{l}L_{1}^{l}\left(t\right)C_{jl}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which defines D.Es for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 that they have to satisfy.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buonanno2002"

\end_inset

 appendix)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:LinearObservables"

\end_inset

Linear observables and important results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is defined as any linear combination (either time dependent or time independe
nt) of the canonical coordinates and momenta of a linear system, plus a
 possible complex number (C number): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{j}a_{j}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{jH}\left(t\right)+b\left(t\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{jk}a_{j}\left(t\right)\alpha_{jk}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{kS}+\sum_{j}a_{j}\left(t\right)\beta_{j}\left(t\right)+b\left(t\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used equ.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:time evolution Cjh"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right),\hat{B}_{H}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \sum_{jk}\gamma_{j}^{A}\left(t\right)\gamma_{k}^{B}\left(t^{'}\right)C_{jk}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right),\hat{B}_{H}\left(t^{'}\right)\right] & = & \left[\sum_{jk}a_{j}\left(t\right)\alpha_{jk}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{kS}+\sum_{j}a_{j}\left(t\right)\beta_{j}\left(t\right)+b\left(t\right),\sum_{jk}b_{j}\left(t\right)\alpha_{jk}\left(t\right)\hat{C}_{kS}+\sum_{j}b_{j}\left(t\right)\beta_{j}\left(t\right)+b\left(t\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

if we expand this sum it is clear that we will end up with terms that depend
 on the lowest order of the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{C}_{jS},\hat{C}_{lS}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 number and hence, 
\emph on
in the Heisenberg picture, the commutator of the operators of any two linear
 observables at two times is a C number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buonanno2002"

\end_inset

 appendix)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:LinearClassical"

\end_inset

Linear system subjected to a classical force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interaction term between a quantum linear system and a classical generalized
 force 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{I} & = & -\hat{x}G\left(t\right)\quad\mbox{(like work=xF)}\\
\implies H & = & H_{0}-\hat{x}G\left(t\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

then for any linear observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)+\frac{i}{\hbar}\intop_{-\infty}^{t}dt^{'}C_{Ax}\left(t,t^{'}\right)G\left(t^{'}\right),\label{eq:linearResponse classical force}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Heisenberg picture of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 alone and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{Ax}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

-number called the 
\emph on
time-domain susceptibility
\emph default
 and is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{Ax}\left(t,t^{'}\right) & \equiv & \left[A_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right),\hat{x}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)\right].\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To show this, we first use the general relation for a hamiltonian of the
 form 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{0}+V_{s}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)+\frac{i}{\hbar}\intop_{-\infty}^{t}dt_{1}\left[\hat{V}_{I}\left(t_{1}\right),\hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)\right]+\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\right)^{2}\intop_{-\infty}^{t}dt_{1}\intop_{-\infty}^{t_{1}}dt_{2}\left[\hat{V}_{I}\left(t_{2}\right),\left[\hat{V}_{I}\left(t_{1}\right),\hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)\right]\right]+...,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{I}$
\end_inset

 is the interaction picture of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{S}$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buonanno2002"

\end_inset

 appendix).
 If the system is subjected to a classical force then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{S} & = & -xG\\
\implies V_{I} & = & U_{0}^{\dagger}V_{S}U_{0}=-\hat{x}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}G,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is a linear observable.
 We then use the result of the previous section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:LinearObservables"

\end_inset

 that the commutator of two linear observables is a 
\begin_inset Formula $c-$
\end_inset

number and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{V}_{I}\left(t_{2}\right),\left[\hat{V}_{I}\left(t_{1}\right),\hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)\right]\right]$
\end_inset

 and higher order commutators vanish.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buonanno2002"

\end_inset

 appendix)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Twolinearsystems"

\end_inset

Two independent linear systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Call them 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 the probe) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 the detector) and suppose they interact by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H & = & H_{\mathcal{P}}+H_{\mathcal{D}}-x\otimes F\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

then for any linear observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 of the system 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 of the system 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)+\frac{i}{\hbar}\intop_{-\infty}^{t}dt^{'}C_{Ax}\left(t,t^{'}\right)\hat{F}_{H}\left(t^{'}\right)\label{eq:linearResponse}\\
\hat{B}_{H}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{B}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right)+\frac{i}{\hbar}\intop_{-\infty}^{t}dt^{'}C_{Bx}\left(t,t^{'}\right)\hat{x}_{H}\left(t^{'}\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{Ax}\left(t,t^{'}\right) & \equiv & \left[A_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right),\hat{x}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]\\
C_{Bx}\left(t,t^{'}\right) & \equiv & \left[A_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right),\hat{F}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Follow the same logic as in the previous section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:LinearClassical"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 lives in a different Hilbert space than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 it is like it is a classical force.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Linear system with time independent hamiltonian"

\end_inset


\series bold
Fourier domain formalism when the zeroth order hamiltonian is time independent
\series default
: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A}_{H}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \hat{A}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(\Omega\right)+R_{Ax}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{F}_{H}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{B}_{H}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \hat{B}_{H}^{\left(0\right)}\left(\Omega\right)+R_{BF}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{x}_{H}\left(\Omega\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left(\Omega\right)=\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}dte^{i\Omega t}\hat{A}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{AB}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is the susceptibility in the Fourier-domain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{AB}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{i}{\hbar}\intop_{0}^{\infty}d\tau e^{i\Omega\tau}C_{AB}\left(0,-\tau\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a time indepedent hamiltonian we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U_{0}\left(t,t+\tau\right) & = & e^{-iH_{0}\tau/\hbar}\\
 & = & U_{0}\left(\tau\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and hence for any two linear observables 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

