\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Indirect measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Intro and Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

von Neumann's postulate of the reduction of the wave function [[(see section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:WFC"

\end_inset

)]] answers the question of what happens to the quantum object during the
 measurement.
 However, the reduction postulate does not answer the question of how the
 measuring device must be designed to realize the desired measurement.
 To answer this second question, one must understand the connection between
 the measuring device as an ordinary physical system, and the nature of
 the desired measurement (the quantity to be measured, the desired precision,
 and the choice of how the measurement is to perturb the quantum object).
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 (Section 3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Quantum measurements in which the measured object interacts directly with
 the classical measuring device are called "
\emph on
direct measurements
\emph default
." A typical example of a direct measurement is the measurement of the position
 of a microparticle by the path it produces in a photoemulsion.
 In a direct measurement, there typically is considerable randomness in
 the interaction of the object with the many degrees of freedom of the classical
 measuring device (e.g.
 the random motion of the microparticle in the photoemulsion, which resembles
 Brownian motion).
 As a result, the measuring device perturbs the object far more strongly
 than the minimum perturbation required by the uncertainty relations.
 Moreover, the device usually perturbs not only the degree of freedom that
 it measures, but also other degrees of freedom.
 For example, the photoemulsion perturbs not only the components of the
 microparticle's momentum parallel to the photographic plate (the momenta
 whose corresponding coordinates are being measured), but also the perpendicular
 component of the momentum.
 Such perturbations are inevitable because many different degrees of freedom
 of the photoemulsion participate in the random extraction of energy from
 the microparticle.
 The energy absorbed by each photoemulsion degree of freedom is rather large:
 typically several electron volts, and the same is true for the Wilson cloud
 chamber and other typical direct measurement devices.
 [[As a result]] When the microparticle is an optical photon (which has
 a total energy of only a few electron volts), this interaction causes the
 photon to be completely absorbed.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Section 3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Indirect-measurements"

\end_inset

Description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a two-step process: The quantum object we which to measure interacts
 with a quantum system (called the 
\emph on
quantum probe
\emph default
) that has been prepared in advance in some special initial quantum state.
 The second step is a direct measurement of some chosen observable of the
 quantum probe (and so its quantum state is reduced and because of its correlati
on with the quantum object, there is a corresponding reduction of the object's
 state).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also write a formal theory: Assume the first step described above
 ends before the second step begins (in order to achieve high precision^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
as then it would be like we are doing a direct measurement: probe and clasical
 device are directly coupled while the probe and quantum system we would
 like to measure are still coupled.
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and that the second step contributes negligibly to the error of measurement.
 Let the initial state of the probe be 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{probe}$
\end_inset

 and that of the object 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{init}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding state of the probe after the interaction is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr_{obj}\left(U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{q}$
\end_inset

 the state the probe is in after the second step (which is inferred by obtaining
 an eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 from a precisely measured observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

- again we are idealizing the second step of the indirect measurement).
 We also assume that the experiment is designed in such a way that there
 is a 1-1 correspondance between the values 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and the values of an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of the measured object so that from 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 we can infer the value of the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and we can regard 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 as the outcome of the entire 2-step measurement.
 The probability distribution for the result of the measurement is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w\left(q\right) & = & Tr_{probe}\left(\ket{q}\bra{q}\left[Tr_{obj}\left(U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\right]\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{object}\left(\Pi\left(q\right)\rho_{init}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi\left(q\right)\equiv Tr_{probe}\left(U^{\dagger}\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{probe}\right)$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w\left(q\right) & = & Tr_{probe}\left(\ket{q}\bra{q}\left[Tr_{obj}\left(U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\right]\right)\\
 & = & \int\braket{s|q}\bra{q}\left[Tr_{obj}\left(U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\right]\bra{s}ds\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}\left(\int\braket{s|q}\bra{q}U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\bra{s}ds\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}Tr_{probe}\left(\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}Tr_{probe}\left(\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}Tr_{probe}\left(U^{\dagger}\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{init}\otimes\rho_{probe}\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}Tr_{probe}\left(U^{\dagger}\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{probe}\otimes\rho_{init}\right)\\
 & = & Tr_{obj}\left[Tr_{probe}\left(U^{\dagger}\ket{q}\bra{q}U\rho_{probe}\right)\otimes\rho_{init}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The back action of the entire indirect measurement is embodied in the object's
 final state, which is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho\left(q\right) & = & \frac{1}{w\left(q\right)}\braket{q|U\rho_{init}\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}|q}\label{eq:temp454}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is just simple wave function collapse after the second step: the system
 evolves into 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $U\rho_{init}\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and then we do a projective measurement into 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{q}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{probe}=\sum_{j}\ket{\chi_{j}}x_{j}\bra{\chi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 allows us to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho\left(q\right) & = & \frac{1}{w\left(q\right)}\sum_{j}x_{j}\Omega_{j}\left(q\right)\rho_{init}\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\left(q\right)\nonumber \\
\Omega_{j}\left(q\right) & = & \braket{q|U|\chi_{j}}\label{eq:final indirect measurement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Simple rearragement of equ.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:temp454}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that this looks like a Kraus representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

; let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M_{j} & = & \sqrt{\frac{x_{j}}{w\left(q\right)}}\braket{q|U|\chi_{j}}\\
\sum_{j}M_{j}M_{j}^{\dagger} & = & \sum_{j}\frac{x_{j}}{w\left(q\right)}\braket{q|U|\chi_{j}}\braket{\chi_{j}|U^{\dagger}|q}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{w\left(q\right)}\braket{q|U\rho_{probe}U^{\dagger}|q}\\
 & \neq & I\mbox{ in general}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So that this is not exactly the same but similar ...
 here the second step (i.e.
 measurement of the probe by a classical device) is extra / that should
 explain it.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is a mixture of states and so has additional non-fundamental uncertainti
es: if the probe's initial state was then the final state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

's final uncertainty would be reduced as we would have only one 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be interperted as the amplitude for the probe state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\chi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 to have evolved to state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

