(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

 section 3 with examples; note that http://faculty.wwu.edu/vawter/PhysicsNet/Topic
s/Capacitors/ParallCap.html might help with understanding EM parts).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantum Limit on measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simple argument for deriving the standard quantum limit (SQL) of a free
 particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we do a couple of quick measurements of the position of a particle
 with each measurement separated by a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Say at time 0, the particle's position is measured with error 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{measure,1}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta P_{perturb} & = & \frac{\hbar}{2\Delta x_{measure,1}}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

After time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 this would cause a back action on the second position measurement: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta x_{add} & = & \frac{\hbar\tau}{2m\left(\Delta x_{measure,1}\right)},\label{eq:xAdd}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because of the first measurement the particle will be moving with a velocity
 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{perturb}/m$
\end_inset

 and so in time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would have moved by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta x & = & \frac{\Delta P_{perturb}}{m}\tau\\
 & = & \frac{\hbar}{2\Delta x_{measure,1}}\frac{\tau}{m}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

which will superimpose with first measurement error.
 The momentum can be measured by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P & = & m\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}\pm\Delta P\\
 & = & m\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{\tau}\pm\frac{m}{\tau}\sqrt{\Delta x_{2}^{2}+\Delta x_{1}^{2}}\\
 & = & m\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{\tau}\pm\frac{m}{\tau}\sqrt{\Delta x_{measure,1}^{2}+\left(\Delta x_{measure,2}^{2}+\Delta x_{add}^{2}\right)}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

What is the optimal accuracy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P$
\end_inset

? Using equ.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:xAdd}\right)$
\end_inset

, it is easy to calculate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P$
\end_inset

 is at minimum for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{measure,1}=\sqrt{\hbar\tau/2m}=\Delta x_{add}$
\end_inset

.
 Sor for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{measure,2}$
\end_inset

 negligibly small, we arrive at the 
\emph on
standard quantum limit 
\emph default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta P_{SQL} & = & \sqrt{\frac{\hbar m}{\tau}}\\
\Delta P & \geq & \Delta P_{SQL}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

 section 1.4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SQL for the energy of an oscillator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

 section 4.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectral densities in quantum measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calculating spectral densities of quantum noise in linear optical measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the readout quantity of a meter is linear (in Fourier space; measurements
 aren't usually instantaneous) then it's most general form is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{Y}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right)\\
 & = & H_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+H_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right)\\
 & \equiv & \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{a}}$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defA2photon"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
H_{c} & H_{s}\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 characterized how light is transformed by the device, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the spectrum of the measured quantity and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 represents the quantum noise in the system.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{cs}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is a real valued function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s=i\Omega$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is an observable and so it is hermitian and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{Y}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \hat{Y}\left(-\Omega\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which entails that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{sc}^{*}\left(\Omega\right) & = & H_{sc}\left(-\Omega\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Write 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 as a taylor series then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H^{*} & = & \sum a_{n}^{*}\Omega^{n}\\
 & = & \sum a_{n}\left(-1\right)^{n}\Omega^{n}=H\left(-\Omega\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}^{*}=a_{n}\left(-1\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=i^{n}\times RealConstant$
\end_inset

 and we can absorb the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{n}$
\end_inset

 and define a new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s=i\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Define the 
\series bold
\emph on
double-sided 
\series default
power spectral density 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $S_{Y}$
\end_inset

 (a measure of the quantum noise) by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
2\pi S_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right) & = & \left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Y}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}.\label{eq:def spectral density quantum}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The single-sided power spectral density is defined in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Define the 
\series bold
\emph on
single-sided 
\series default
power spectral density 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $S_{Y}^{1}$
\end_inset

 (a measure of the quantum noise) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi S_{Y}^{1}\left(\Omega\right)\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)=\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Y}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the double-sided power spectral density of a vacuum state is
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{Y}^{vac}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\left|H_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\right|^{2}+\left|H_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\right|^{2}}{2}=\frac{\vec{H}\vec{H}^{\dagger}}{2}\label{eq:vacuum-spectral-density}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \left\langle \vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{H}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\hat{\vec{a}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
 & = & \vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\left\langle \hat{\vec{a}}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\vec{H}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not a quantum operator.
 Then we use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralVacuum"

\end_inset

 (remembering that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)=\hat{a}\left(-\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

) to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \left(2\pi\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\right)\vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\mathbb{S}_{vac}\vec{H}\left(\Omega\right)\\
 & = & \left(2\pi\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)\right)\frac{\vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{H}\left(\Omega\right)}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

and for a squeezed state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{r,\phi}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{Y}^{sqz}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{\left|H_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\right|^{2}}{2}\left(\cosh2r+\sinh2r\cos2\phi\right)+\frac{\left|H_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\right|^{2}}{2}\left(\cosh2r-\sinh2r\cos2\phi\right)\\
 &  & -Re\left[H_{c}\left(\Omega\right)H_{s}^{*}\left(\Omega\right)\right]\sinh2r\sin2\phi.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We might also be interested in calculating cross-correlations between 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and some other quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 with quantum noise defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{N}_{Z}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \vec{Z}\hat{\vec{a}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

then simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
2\pi S_{YZ}\left(\Omega\right)\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right) & = & \left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Z}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For example, for a vacuum state we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{YZ}^{vac}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{H_{c}^{*}Z_{c}+H_{s}^{*}Z_{s}}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Z}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \left\langle \vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{Z}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\hat{\vec{a}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
 & = & \vec{H}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\left\langle \hat{\vec{a}}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\vec{Z}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and for a squeezed state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{r,\phi}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{YZ}^{sqz}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{H_{c}^{*}Z_{c}}{2}\left(\cosh2r+\sinh2r\cos2\phi\right)+\frac{H_{s}^{*}Z_{s}}{2}\left(\cosh2r-\sinh2r\cos2\phi\right)\\
 &  & -\frac{H_{s}^{*}Z_{c}+H_{c}^{*}Z_{s}}{2}\sinh2r\sin2\phi.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 3.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generalization to the readout of many independent incoming EM fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality, the readout observable of detectors can be a combination of
 independent EM fields (e.g.
 a GW detector measures a combination of the input light field and vacuum
 field).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{a}}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 stand for the quadrature amplitude vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 independent EM fields then now the output observable of the detector can
 be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{Y}\left(\Omega\right) & \rightarrow & \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{\boldsymbol{a}}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{YY}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}\vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\mathbb{S}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{H}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\\
S_{YZ}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}\vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\mathbb{S}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{Z}_{i}\left(\Omega\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defSpectral2photon"

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the first equality we have 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \sum\left\langle \vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}_{i}}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{H_{i}}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\hat{\vec{a}_{i}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
 & = & \sum\vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\left\langle \hat{\vec{a}_{i}}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a_{i}}}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\vec{H}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not a quantum operator.
 Then we use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralVacuum"

\end_inset

 (remembering that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)=\hat{a}\left(-\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

)
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the second equality, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \hat{N}_{Y}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{N}_{Z}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm} & = & \sum\left\langle \vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\vec{Z_{i}}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\hat{\vec{a}}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\\
 & = & \sum\vec{H}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega\right)\left\langle \hat{\vec{a}}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{\vec{a}}_{i}^{\dagger}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}\vec{Z}_{i}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 3.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Double sided versus single sided spectral density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection between the two spectral densities is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{o}^{+}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \begin{cases}
2S_{o}\left(\Omega\right) & \mbox{for }\Omega\ge0\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{o}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is the single sided spectral density and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{o}$
\end_inset

 the double sided spectral density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Free space example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename free test mass.png
	scale 75

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Free test mass example"

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 See Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Free test mass example"

\end_inset

 for the setup.
 We assume that the laser's input optical field is a single mode coherent
 state and so we can write it's electric field in the following (unnormalized)
 form (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:final simple single mode laser"

\end_inset

 without the normalization constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}$
\end_inset

 )
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and the output field is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{out}\left(t\right) & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c\right),\\
 & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{b}_{1}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{b}_{2}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=L/c$
\end_inset

 is the time taken to reach the test mass in its rest position*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that (using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadraturesFreeSpacePropagation"

\end_inset

) 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{E}_{out}\left(t\right)=\hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because the output field is the input field after it has traveled a distance
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $2L+2\hat{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We divide by the velocity to obtain the desired result.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{b}_{1}\left(t\right) & \approx & \hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)\nonumber \\
\hat{b}_{2}\left(t\right) & \approx & \hat{a}_{s}\left(t-2\tau\right)+2\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{\omega_{0}}{c}\hat{x}\left(t-\tau\right)\label{eq:outputQuadraturesSimpleNoiseExample}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

[[TYPO: Eq.
 2.25 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset

 should have a + not -]]where we have assumed that the displacement of the
 test mirror (and its uncertainty) is small and so we can Taylor expand
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{out}$
\end_inset

 (note that we make the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}L/c=n\pi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{t}=t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{x} & = & \omega_{0}x/c\\
\implies\tilde{t} & = & t-2\tau-2\tilde{x}/\omega_{0}\\
\implies\omega_{0}\tilde{t} & = & \omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right)-2\tilde{x},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

we have (letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\equiv\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}$
\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{out} & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c\right)\\
 & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\left(\frac{\omega_{0}\hat{x}}{c}\right)\frac{d}{d\tilde{x}}E_{out}|_{\tilde{x}=0}+...\\
 & \approx & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\left(\frac{\omega_{0}\hat{x}}{c}\right)\frac{d}{d\tilde{x}}\left(\left[\xi+\hat{a}_{c}\left(\tilde{t}\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}\tilde{t}+\hat{a}_{s}\sin\omega_{0}\tilde{t}\right)|_{\tilde{x}=0}\\
 & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\left(\frac{\omega_{0}\hat{x}}{c}\right)\times\\
 &  & \left(2\left(\hat{a}_{c}\left(\tilde{t}\right)+\xi\right)\sin\omega_{o}\tilde{t}+\frac{d}{d\tilde{x}}\hat{a}_{c}\left(\tilde{t}\right)\cos\omega_{0}\tilde{t}-2\hat{a}_{s}\left(\tilde{t}\right)\cos\omega_{0}\tilde{t}+\frac{d}{d\tilde{x}}\hat{a}_{s}\left(\tilde{t}\right)\sin\omega_{0}\tilde{t}\right)_{\tilde{x}=0}\\
 & = & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\left(\frac{\omega_{0}\hat{x}}{c}\right)\times\\
 &  & \left(2\left(\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\xi\right)\sin\omega_{o}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right)-2\hat{a}_{s}\left(t-2\tau\right)\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t-2\tau\right)\sin\omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right)\right),\\
 & \approx & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\\
 &  & \left(\frac{\omega_{0}\hat{x}}{c}\right)\times\left(2\left(\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)+\xi\right)\sin\omega_{o}t+\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\cos\omega_{0}t-2\hat{a}_{s}\left(t-2\tau\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right)\\
 & \approx & \hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau\right)+O\left(\hat{x}\times\hat{a}_{c}\right)+\xi\hat{x}\sin\omega_{0}t+O\left(\hat{a}_{c}\times\hat{x}\right)+O\left(\hat{x}\times\hat{a}_{s}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sin\omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right) & \approx & \sin\omega_{0}t\cos\left(2\tau\omega_{0}\right)-\cos\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(2\tau\omega_{0}\right)\approx\sin\omega_{0}t\\
\cos\omega_{0}\left(t-2\tau\right) & \approx & \cos\omega_{0}t\cos\left(2\omega_{0}\tau\right)+\sin\left(\omega_{0}t\right)\sin\left(2\tau\omega_{0}\right)\approx\cos\omega_{0}t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because we have assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\times(\mbox{time to reach test mass})\approx n\pi$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $2\tau\omega_{0}\approx2n\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have used that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{sc}\left(t\right) & = & \int d\omega e^{-i\omega t}a_{sc}\left(\omega\right)\\
\implies a_{sc}\left(\tilde{t}\right) & = & \int e^{-i\omega\tilde{t}}a_{sc}\left(\omega\right)d\omega\\
 & \approx & e^{2i\omega_{0}\left(\tau+\hat{x}/c\right)}a_{sc}\left(t\right)\quad\left(\mbox{because singleModeLaser}\right)\\
 & \approx & \left(1+2i\omega_{0}\left(\tau+\hat{x}/c\right)\right)a_{sc}\left(t\right)\quad(x\mbox{ is small})\\
 & = & \left(1+2i\left(\omega_{0}\tau+\tilde{x}\right)\right)a_{sc}\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{because singleModeLaser}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means that we have a single mode laser so it is monochromatic and so in
 the Hilbert space we are interested in 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{sc}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 can be treated to be approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\neq\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left.\frac{d}{d\tilde{x}}\hat{a}_{sc}\left(\tilde{t}\right)\right|_{\tilde{x}=0} & = & \left(1+2i\omega_{0}\tau\right)a_{sc}\left(t\right)\\
 & \approx & e^{-2i\omega_{0}\tau}a_{sc}\left(t\right)\approx a_{sc}\left(t-2\tau\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for the same reason we previously discussed: we have a single mode laser.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The equation of motion of the system is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m\ddot{\hat{x}} & = & \hat{F}_{rp}+G\left(t\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is a classical force and the radiation pressure force is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{F}_{rp} & = & 2\frac{\hat{I}}{c}\approx\frac{2I_{0}}{c}\left[1+\sqrt{\frac{2\hbar\omega_{0}}{I_{0}}}\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-\tau\right)\right],\label{eq:radiationPressureSimpleExNoise}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Classically the radiation pressure is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{dp}{dt} & = & \frac{2\hbar k\times n=\#Photons}{dt}\\
 & = & \frac{2\hbar\omega n}{cdt}=2\frac{I}{c}\left[SI\right]\\
 & = & 2\frac{\mathcal{A}c}{4\pi}\frac{1}{c}I\left[CGS\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}=\hbar k\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 (see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:momentumQMfield"

\end_inset

; we have a factor of 2 in our expression because of the reflection of light
 from the test mass) and that in SI the intensity per area is of the form
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poynting in cgs"

\end_inset

 and in addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is so we can get the intensity in the cross sectional area of the beam.
 And hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{dp}{dt} & = & 2\frac{\mathcal{A}}{4\pi}\overline{\left|\hat{E}_{in}\left(t-\tau\right)\right|^{2}}\quad(\mbox{The factor of }t-\tau\mbox{ is because that is when light reaches the test mass)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the following let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}=\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $t=b-\tau$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $b=t$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{W}}\equiv dp/dt$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=2\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and we take the time average over a period 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta$
\end_inset

 (note we also reintroduce the correct normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}=\sqrt{4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}/\mathcal{A}c}$
\end_inset

 (see Eq 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:final simple single mode laser"

\end_inset

)) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}_{in}\left(t\right) & = & \mathcal{C}_{0}\left[\left(A_{c}+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}\left(t\right)\right)\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{\mathcal{E}_{s}}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t\right].\\
\implies\hat{\mathcal{W}} & = & \frac{v}{4\pi}\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}\left(\frac{A_{c}^{2}}{2}+A_{c}\frac{1}{\vartheta}\int\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)dt+\frac{\overline{\hat{\mathcal{E}_{c}}^{2}\left(t\right)}}{2}+\frac{\bar{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{s}^{2}}}{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(where in the second equality we used that the time average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\sin$
\end_inset

 over one period is 0).
 We ignore terms 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{sc}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 as they are small 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\implies\hat{\mathcal{W}} & = & \frac{v}{8\pi}A_{c}^{2}\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}+\frac{v\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}}{4\pi\vartheta}A_{c}\int\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)dt\\
 & = & \frac{v}{8\pi}A_{c}^{2}\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}+\frac{2\mathcal{A}\mathcal{C}_{0}^{2}}{4\pi}A_{c}\frac{1}{\vartheta}\int\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)dt\\
 & = & \frac{\mathcal{A}}{4\pi}\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}\frac{4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}}{\mathcal{A}c}+\frac{2\mathcal{A}}{4\pi}\frac{4\pi\hbar\omega_{0}}{\mathcal{A}c}\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{1}{\vartheta}\int\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)dt\\
 & = & \frac{2I_{0}}{c}+2\frac{\sqrt{2I_{0}\hbar\omega_{0}}}{c}\frac{1}{\vartheta}\int\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}\left(t\right)dt\\
 & = & \frac{2I_{0}}{c}\left(1+\sqrt{\frac{2\hbar\omega_{0}}{I_{0}}}\overline{\hat{\mathcal{E}}_{c}}\right)=\frac{2I_{0}}{c}\left(1+\sqrt{\frac{2\hbar\omega_{0}}{I_{0}}}\overline{\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-\tau\right)}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where we have assumed that amplitude and phase fluctuations are small.
 The DC component 
\begin_inset Formula $2I_{0}/c$
\end_inset

 can be neglected in the analysis of the noise as it can be compensated
 for*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Work around the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 or modify the experiment by for example using an actuator or a wire tension
 in the case of a suspended pendulum.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
Assume that the radiation pressure force is tuned in such a way that it
 exactly cancels 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

; i.e.
 we are working in an inertial frame and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{x}}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve this problem, work in Fourier space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \mathbf{M}\vec{a}\left(\Omega\right)+\vec{D}G\left(\Omega\right),\label{eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=\left(\hat{a}_{s},\hat{a}_{c}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\left(\hat{b}_{1},\hat{b}_{2}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{M} & = & e^{2i\Omega\tau}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\kappa & 1
\end{array}\right]\\
\vec{D} & = & -\frac{e^{i\Omega\tau}}{g_{SQL}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\sqrt{2\kappa}
\end{array}\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\kappa & = & \frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\quad g_{SQL}=\sqrt{2\hbar m\Omega^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadraturesSimpleNoiseExample"

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)\right]\\
\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{a}_{s}\left(t-2\tau\right)\right]
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
2\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{\omega_{0}}{c}\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{x}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]
\end{array}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We have that, using the shift property of Fourier transforms (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shiftPropertyFourierTransforms"

\end_inset

 with the Fourier transform defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[g\right]\propto\int e^{ixk}g\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-2\tau\right)\right] & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:radiationPressureSimpleExNoise"

\end_inset

 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
-m\Omega^{2}x\left(\Omega\right) & = & \frac{2I_{0}}{c}\sqrt{\frac{2\hbar\omega_{0}}{I_{0}}}\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{a}_{c}\left(t-\tau\right)\right]+G\left(\Omega\right)\\
 & = & \frac{2\sqrt{2I_{0}\hbar\omega_{0}}}{c}e^{i\Omega\tau}a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right)\\
\implies\mathcal{F}\left(x\left(t-\tau\right)\right) & = & \frac{-e^{i\Omega\tau}}{m\Omega^{2}}\left(\frac{2\sqrt{2I_{0}\hbar\omega_{0}}}{c}e^{i\Omega\tau}a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right)\right)\\
\implies2\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{\omega_{0}}{c}\mathcal{F}\left[\hat{x}\left(t-\tau\right)\right] & = & -2\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{\omega_{0}}{c}\frac{e^{i\Omega\tau}}{m\Omega^{2}}\left(\frac{2\sqrt{2I_{0}\hbar\omega_{0}}}{c}e^{i\Omega\tau}a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+G\left(\Omega\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-4\times2I_{0}\frac{\omega_{0}}{m\Omega^{2}c^{2}} & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)-\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}2\sqrt{\frac{2I_{0}}{\hbar\omega_{0}}}\frac{\omega_{0}}{c}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{m\Omega^{2}}\\
 & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\kappa & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)-\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{\frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{m\Omega^{2}c^{2}}}\sqrt{2}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{\hbar m\Omega^{2}}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\
 & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\kappa & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)-\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{\hbar m\Omega^{2}}}\sqrt{2}\\
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\kappa & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)-\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{g_{SQL}},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{SQL}=\sqrt{2\hbar m\Omega^{2}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We observe that the quadrature 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 carries the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and so we can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa}G\left(\Omega\right)/g_{SQL}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{b}_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\hat{b}_{2}=e^{2i\Omega\tau}\left[-\kappa\hat{a}_{c}\left(\Omega\right)+\hat{a}_{s}\left(\Omega\right)\right]$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{b}_{2}\right\rangle =e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa}/g_{SQL}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a_{s}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and in with the displacement transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a_{c}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 (See Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expectations quadratures 1mode laser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We identify the second term as the shot noise: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{n}_{sh} & \equiv & e^{2i\Omega\tau}\hat{a}_{s},\label{eq:shotNoiseSimpleExNoise}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which arises from the phase-quadrature fluctuation of the input optical
 field and has a flat spectrum 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
with the definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi S_{n}\left(\Omega\right)\delta\left(\Omega-\Omega^{'}\right)=\left\langle \hat{n}\left(\Omega\right)\hat{n}\left(\Omega^{'}\right)\right\rangle _{symm}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 for a vacuum state: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{sh}\left(\Omega\right) & = & 1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that here we used the single-definition definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:def spectral density quantum"

\end_inset

 but with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 will be twice as large as the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:def spectral density quantum"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To show this result we use Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vacuum-spectral-density"

\end_inset

 (multiplying by 2) by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2i\Omega\tau}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

and the second term is a the radiation pressure noise 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{rp}\equiv-e^{2i\Omega\tau}\kappa\hat{a}_{c}$
\end_inset

 which has the following noise spectrum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{rp}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \kappa^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Because we have a coherent state, the amplitude and phase-quadrature fluctuation
s are not correlated*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Note1"

\end_inset

For a coherent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, we have that - using the 2 photon formalism: see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sidesbands2photonAcAs"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle a_{c}\left(t\right)a_{s}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\left\langle a_{1}\left(x\right)a_{2}\left(y\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & -\frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\left\langle a_{\omega_{0}+x}a_{\omega_{0}+y}-a_{\omega_{0}+x}a_{\omega_{0}-y}^{\dagger}-a_{\omega_{0}-x}^{\dagger}a_{\omega_{0}+y}+a_{\omega_{0}-x}^{\dagger}a_{\omega_{0}-y}^{\dagger}\right\rangle \\
 & = & -\frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\left\langle a_{\omega_{0}+x}a_{\omega_{0}+y}-\left(2\pi\right)\delta\left(x+y\right)-2a_{\omega_{0}-x}^{\dagger}a_{\omega_{0}+y}+a_{\omega_{0}-x}^{\dagger}a_{\omega_{0}-y}^{\dagger}\right\rangle \\
 & = & -\frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\left(\alpha^{2}-2\left|\alpha\right|^{2}+\alpha^{*2}\right)\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\delta\left(x\right)\delta\left(y\right)+\frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)\int dye^{ix\left(t-\tau\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}4Im\left[\alpha\right]^{2}+\frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)\int dye^{ix\left(t-\tau\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{i}{2}\left(\frac{Im\left[\alpha\right]^{2}}{\pi^{2}}+\delta\left(t-\tau\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle a_{c}\left(t\right)\right\rangle \left\langle a_{s}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle  & = & \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\left\langle a_{1}\left(x\right)\right\rangle \left\langle a_{2}\left(y\right)\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}\int dxdye^{ixt}e^{iy\tau}\left(\delta\left(x\right)Re\left[\alpha\right]\sqrt{2}\right)\left(\delta\left(y\right)Im\left[\alpha\right]\sqrt{2}\right)\\
 & = & \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{2}2Re\left[\alpha\right]Im\left[\alpha\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 - which we have because we applied the displacement transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}\rightarrow D^{\dagger}\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 - (or 
\begin_inset Formula $Re\left[\alpha\right]=0$
\end_inset

) then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle a_{c}\left(t\right)a_{s}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle  & = & \frac{i}{2}\delta\left(t-\tau\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 which is white.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so we can obtain the total noise spectrum by summing up 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{sh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{rp}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{tot}=S_{sh}+S_{rp}=1+\kappa^{2}$
\end_inset

 but in reality we usually would like to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 directly so we normalize Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right)}{\left|D\right|} & = & \frac{\mathbf{M}\vec{a}\left(\Omega\right)}{\left|D\right|}+G\left(\Omega\right),\nonumber \\
\implies S_{tot,Normalized} & = & S_{tot}\left|\frac{g_{SQL}}{e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa}}\right|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(\frac{1}{\kappa}+\kappa\right)\frac{g_{SQL}^{2}}{2}\ge g_{SQL}^{2}\label{eq:SnormalizedFreeSpace}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In[2]:= Minimize[{1/x + x, x > 0}, x]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Out[2]= {2, {x -> 1}}
\end_layout

\end_inset

and we notice that the shot noise is inversely proportional to the optical
 power while the radiation pressure noise (second term) is proportional
 to the optical power 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that this is the noise we care about as 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle b_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left\langle \hat{b}_{2}\right\rangle }{\left|D\right|}=e^{i\Omega\tau}G\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{tot,Normalized}$
\end_inset

 gives us the noise at that frequency.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 2.5.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tuned Fabry-Perot Cavity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename tuned fabry perot.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:tuned fabry perot noise"

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

See Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tuned fabry perot noise"

\end_inset

 for the setup.
 The mirror has transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and reflectivity 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we assume that we have a symmetric mirror that inflicts a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 phase shift on its input side*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We must have a phase shift because by the reciprocity relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r^{*}t^{'}+t^{*}r^{'} & = & 0\\
\implies r^{*} & = & -r^{'}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so its scattering matrix is given by (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scatteringMatrixBS"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out}^{'}\\
E_{in}
\end{array}\right) & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sqrt{T} & -\sqrt{R}\\
\sqrt{R} & \sqrt{T}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out}\\
E_{in}^{'}
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:scattering equation of tuned fabry perot - qNoise}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Let the bosonic operators associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 And so we obtain from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scattering equation of tuned fabry perot - qNoise"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{a} & = & \sqrt{R}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The input and output variables (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, respectively) can be directly related to each other by making use of the
 above linear system of equations and Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can relate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{out}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{in}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{out}\left(t\right)=\hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c\right),$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 obey Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

, which was derived for the propagation of the electric field in a single
 mirror setup (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Free test mass example"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, we can relate 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 by using Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

 to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\vec{a}=g\left(\vec{b}\right)\right)=\sqrt{R}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the function that relates 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

.
 And, finally we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}=\sqrt{T}\left(\vec{b}=h\left(\vec{\alpha}\right)\right)-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To simplify the algebra, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is small (which is a characteristic of high-finesse cavities).
 We will also assume that we wish to measure the low frequency (around 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}$
\end_inset

 Hz) components of the force 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 that affects the test-mass.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the time the electric field takes to go from the mirror to the left
 to the test-mass, is of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(10^{-3}\right)$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "note3"

\end_inset

Say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the equilibrium distance between the mirrors, is around 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 km and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Omega\tau & = & 10^{2}\times\frac{4\; km}{3\times10^{5}}\\
 & \approx & 10^{-3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx10^{-3}$
\end_inset

 - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "advancedLIGOdata"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Making a Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

 and using that both are of comparable norm*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "note4"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain (to zeroth order) that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G\left(\Omega\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{H} & = & e^{2i\phi}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\mathcal{K}/2 & 1
\end{array}\right)\\
\vec{F} & = & -\frac{e^{i\phi}}{g_{SQL}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\mathcal{\sqrt{K}}
\end{array}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\phi & \equiv & \tan^{-1}\left(\Omega/\gamma\right)\quad\gamma\equiv\frac{Tc}{4L}\\
\mathcal{K} & \equiv & \frac{2\gamma\iota_{c}}{\Omega^{2}\left(\Omega^{2}+\gamma^{2}\right)}\quad\iota_{c}\equiv\frac{8\omega_{0}I_{c}}{mLc}\quad I_{c}\equiv\frac{4I_{0}}{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \left(T\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}-\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{\alpha}+\sqrt{T}\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\kappa^{'} & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa^{'}}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{g_{SQL}}\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{M}\vec{a}+\vec{D}G,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{SQL}=\sqrt{2\hbar m\Omega^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{'}$
\end_inset

 equal to? In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

, it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 but the cavity is tuned so we do not have to worry about it).
 However, now, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 are inside the cavity (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tuned fabry perot noise"

\end_inset

).
 Inside the cavity, at steady state, there will be a very large power stored
 in the cavity: 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{c}=4I_{0}/T$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "rem:intracavity power LM T0"

\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\kappa^{'} & = & \frac{8I_{c}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{8\left(4I_{0}/T\right)\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{4\kappa}{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=\sqrt{R}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \mathbf{M}\left(\sqrt{R}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\right)+\vec{D}G\\
\implies\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{b} & = & \mathbf{M}\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{D}G\\
\vec{b} & = & \left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then, we use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}=\sqrt{T}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \left(T\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}-\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{\alpha}+\sqrt{T}\left(I-\mathbf{M}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(Note: Longer approach: 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Slower derivation
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \mathbf{M}\vec{a}+\vec{D}G\\
\implies\vec{a} & = & \mathbf{M}^{-1}\left(\vec{b}-\vec{D}G\right)=g\left(\vec{b}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{a}=g\left(\vec{b}\right) & = & \sqrt{R}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\implies\mathbf{M}^{-1}\left(\vec{b}-\vec{D}G\right)-\sqrt{R}\vec{b} & = & \sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\implies\mathbf{M}^{-1}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{b} & \equiv & \mathbf{P}\vec{b}=\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\mathbf{M}^{-1}\vec{D}G\\
\implies\vec{b} & = & \sqrt{T}\mathbf{P}^{-1}\vec{\alpha}+\mathbf{P}^{-1}\mathbf{M}^{-1}\vec{D}G,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}=\left(\mathbf{M}^{-1}-\sqrt{R}1_{2\times2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Then use 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}=\sqrt{T}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \left(\sqrt{T}\sqrt{T}\mathbf{P}^{-1}-\sqrt{R}1_{2\times2}\right)\vec{\alpha}+\sqrt{T}\mathbf{P}^{-1}\mathbf{M}^{-1}\vec{D}G\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim*
:
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "note6"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $4\kappa/T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

 are all comparable in strength.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "note4"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma & \equiv & \frac{Tc}{4L}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

then (under the approximation that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\approx0$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\Delta\omega/4$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

 is the FWHM of the output intensity of the Fabry Perot cavity (see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx FWHM of Iout Fabry"

\end_inset

) *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx FWHM of Iout Fabry"

\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega\approx FSR/F$
\end_inset

 and we have that the finesse is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F & = & \frac{\pi\sqrt{R}}{1-R}\\
 & = & \frac{\pi\sqrt{1-T}}{T}\approx\pi\left(\frac{1}{T}-\frac{1}{2}\right)\approx\frac{\pi}{T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is small and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta\omega & \approx & \frac{\pi c}{d}\times\frac{T}{\pi}\\
 & = & \frac{Tc}{d},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this note, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\equiv L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 such is picked such that is comparable to the sideband frequency (
\begin_inset Formula $=\Omega$
\end_inset

) we are interested in (as this is the signal we are interested in [[TODO:
 Make precise]]): i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma & \propto & \frac{Tc}{L}\propto\Omega\\
\implies T & \propto & \Omega\frac{L}{c}=\Omega\tau,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

 are of the same order of magnitude 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(note that this can also be seen from the experimental data of advanced
 Ligo (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.ligo.caltech.edu/advLIGO/scripts/ref_des.shtml
\end_layout

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim0.5\%=5\times10^{-3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

 has been estimated in this section to be 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(10^{-3}\right)$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "note3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

\SpecialChar \@.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finally, we estimate the order of magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

: An order of magnitude (using the LIGO data: 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.ligo.caltech.edu/advLIGO/scripts/ref_des.shtml
\end_layout

\end_inset

) gives us (note that I assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}$
\end_inset

 W; this is what Haixing told me to assume 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is equal to).
 We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa=\frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\kappa & = & \frac{8\times1\times2.5}{4\times9\times4\pi^{2}}\frac{1\times100\times10^{15}}{10\times10^{16}\times10^{4}}\\
 & \approx & \frac{1}{400}\frac{1}{10^{4}}\approx10^{-6}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4\kappa/T\approx\frac{4}{400}\frac{1}{10^{4}}10^{-3}\approx10^{-3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $4\kappa/T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

 are all dimensionless quantities of the same order of magnitude: 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using Mathematica (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

..
\backslash

\backslash
Mathematica files
\backslash

\backslash
tuned fabry perot output operators.nb
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and the above claim, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{12}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{11}=H_{22}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{21}\propto H_{11}$
\end_inset

 and the constant of proportionality is real (from Tag: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exact observations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Moreover, we obtain, after a Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\tau$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{11} & \approx & \exp\left(2i\phi\right)\\
\phi & \equiv & \tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4x}{T}\right)+O\left(x\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(From Tag: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

result H11
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\Omega\tau=\Omega L/c$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\tan^{-1}\left(\Omega4L/Tc\right)=\tan^{-1}\left(\Omega/\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We also obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{21} & = & -e^{2i\phi}\frac{T}{8}\frac{2\gamma\iota_{c}}{\Omega^{2}\left(\gamma^{2}+\Omega^{2}\right)}+O\left(0\right)\\
 & \equiv & -e^{2i\phi}\frac{1}{2}\mathcal{K}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(From tag: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

result H21
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Hence, combining the above results, we can now write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{H} & \approx & e^{2i\phi}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\mathcal{K}/2 & 1
\end{array}\right)\\
\phi & \equiv & \tan^{-1}\left(\Omega/\gamma\right)\quad\gamma\equiv\frac{Tc}{4L}\\
\mathcal{K} & \equiv & \frac{2\gamma\iota_{c}}{\Omega^{2}\left(\Omega^{2}+\gamma^{2}\right)}\quad\iota_{c}=\frac{8\omega_{0}I_{c}}{mLc}\quad I_{c}=\frac{4I_{0}}{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From tag:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

resultF2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{F} & = & -\frac{e^{i\phi}}{g_{SQL}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\sqrt{\mathcal{K}}
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Exact Results 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "note5"

\end_inset

The exact results are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{-e^{2ix}+\sqrt{1-T}}{-1+e^{2ix}\sqrt{1-T}} & 0\\
-\frac{4e^{2ix}\kappa}{\left(-1+e^{2ix}\sqrt{1-T}\right)^{2}} & \frac{-e^{2ix}+\sqrt{1-T}}{-1+e^{2ix}\sqrt{1-T}}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 (from tag:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

Hexact
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
-\frac{2\sqrt{2}e^{ix}\sqrt{\kappa}}{\text{gSQL}-e^{2ix}\text{gSQL}\sqrt{1-T}}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(From tag:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

Fexact
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

