\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:detunedCavity"

\end_inset

Let the bosonic operators associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haixingThesis"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let the bosonic operators associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}^{'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{out}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
We assume that the laser's input optical field is a single mode coherent
 state and so we can write all relevant electric field in the (unnormalized)
 form (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:final simple single mode laser"

\end_inset

 without the normalization constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{0}$
\end_inset

 )
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\left(t\right) & = & \left[\sqrt{2I_{0}/\hbar\omega_{0}}+\hat{a}_{c}\left(t\right)\right]\cos\omega_{0}t+\hat{a}_{s}\left(t\right)\sin\omega_{0}t,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{s}$
\end_inset

 are the cosine and sine quadratures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
The mirror has transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and reflectivity 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we assume that we have a symmetric mirror that inflicts a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 phase shift on its input side*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We must have a phase shift because by the reciprocity relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r^{*}t^{'}+t^{*}r^{'} & = & 0\\
\implies r^{*} & = & -r^{'}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so its scattering matrix is given by (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scatteringMatrixBS"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sqrt{T} & -\sqrt{R}\\
\sqrt{R} & \sqrt{T}
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having a detuned cavity means that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{0}\tau=\theta+n\pi,\label{eq:detunedCavityMeaning1382}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the travel time of a photon to cross the cavity of length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=L/c$
\end_inset

^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
usually we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $2L$
\end_inset

 is tuned to be integer multiple of wavelength, so 
\begin_inset Formula $2L=l\lambda,$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2L=l\frac{c}{f_{0}}=2\pi l\frac{c}{\omega_{0}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sillyRelationsFrequencyWavelength"

\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
L & = & \pi l\frac{c}{\omega_{0}}\\
\implies\omega_{0}\frac{L}{c} & = & \omega_{0}\tau=\pi l.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

So to add detuning, we just add an extra phase to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\left(0,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 How does the detuning affect our formalism? We now have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{a} & = & \sqrt{R}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{\alpha}\\
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\bf R}_{\theta}\equiv e^{i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First of all, by the definition of the scattering matrix, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out}^{'}\\
\tilde{E}_{in}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sqrt{T} & -\sqrt{R}\\
\sqrt{R} & \sqrt{T}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\tilde{E}_{out}\\
E_{in}^{'}
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{in,out}$
\end_inset

 are defined in 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename understandingDetunedCavity.svg
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Introducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{out}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Hence, we have that (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}$
\end_inset

 are the bosonic operators associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{out}$
\end_inset

, respectively)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\tilde{a}} & = & \sqrt{R}\vec{\tilde{b}}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}\vec{\tilde{b}}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{in,out}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{in,out}$
\end_inset

 are simply related to each other.
 Specifically, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{in}\left(t\right) & = & \tilde{E}_{in}\left(t-\frac{\theta}{\omega_{0}}\right)\\
\tilde{E}_{out}\left(t\right) & = & E_{out}\left(t-\frac{\theta}{\omega_{0}}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{\omega_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is the time taken to travel the distance that adds the phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:quadraturesFreeSpacePropagation"

\end_inset

 (let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\theta/\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{a}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{a}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)=e^{i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\tilde{a}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\tilde{a}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\tilde{b}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\tilde{b}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)=e^{i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{b}_{1}\left(\Omega\right)\\
\hat{b}_{2}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Letting
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\bf R}_{\theta}\equiv e^{i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{a} & = & {\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{\tilde{a}}\\
\implies\vec{\tilde{a}} & = & {\bf R}_{\theta}^{-1}\vec{a}\\
\vec{\tilde{b}} & = & {\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{b}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Hence, 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\tilde{a}} & = & \sqrt{R}\vec{\tilde{b}}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}\vec{\tilde{b}}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
{\bf R}_{\theta}^{-1}\vec{a} & = & \sqrt{R}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\implies\vec{a} & = & \sqrt{R}\left({\bf R}_{\theta}\right)^{2}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}\\
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf R}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is equal to a phase multiplied by the rotation matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf R}_{\theta}=e^{i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}R_{\theta,2D}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\theta,2D}$
\end_inset

 is the 2D rotation matrix.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left({\bf R}_{\theta}\right)^{2}=e^{2i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}\left(R_{\theta,2D}\right)^{2}=e^{2i\theta\Omega/\omega_{0}}R_{2\theta,2D}={\bf R}_{2\theta}$
\end_inset

, thus obtaining the desired result.
\end_layout

\end_inset

The input and output variables (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, respectively) can be directly related to each other by making use of the
 above linear system of equations and Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

, which tells us that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right)=\mathbf{M}\vec{a}\left(\Omega\right)+\vec{D}G\left(\Omega\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can relate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{out}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{in}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{out}\left(t\right)=\hat{E}_{in}\left(t-2\tau-2\hat{x}/c\right),$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 obey Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

, which was derived for the propagation of the electric field in a single
 mirror setup (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Free test mass example"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{M} & = & e^{2i\Omega\tau}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-\kappa & 1
\end{array}\right]\\
\vec{D} & = & -\frac{e^{i\Omega\tau}}{g_{SQL}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\sqrt{2\kappa}
\end{array}\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\kappa & = & \frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\\
g_{SQL} & = & \sqrt{2\hbar m\Omega^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\vec{\beta}=\mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G\left(\Omega\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\left(1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\right)\sqrt{1-T}T+e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-2+T)(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])}{\left(-1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-1+T)\right)T+2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\sqrt{1-T}(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])} & \frac{2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}T\text{Sin}[\theta](T\text{Cos}[\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[\theta])}{\left(-1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-1+T)\right)T+2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\sqrt{1-T}(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])}\\
-\frac{2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}T\text{Cos}[\theta](-2\kappa\text{Cos}[\theta]+T\text{Sin}[\theta])}{\left(-1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-1+T)\right)T+2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\sqrt{1-T}(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])} & \frac{\left(1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\right)\sqrt{1-T}T+e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-2+T)(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])}{\left(-1+e^{4i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}(-1+T)\right)T+2e^{2i(x+\theta\Omega\text{\ensuremath{\omega}0})}\sqrt{1-T}(T\text{Cos}[2\theta]+2\kappa\text{Sin}[2\theta])}
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\Omega\tau.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \left(T{\bf R}_{\theta}\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{\theta}-\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{\alpha}+\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G\left(\Omega\right)\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G\left(\Omega\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & e^{i2\Omega\tau}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\kappa^{'} & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{c}\left(\Omega\right)\\
a_{s}\left(\Omega\right)
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
e^{i\Omega\tau}\sqrt{2\kappa^{'}}
\end{array}\right)\frac{G\left(\Omega\right)}{g_{SQL}}\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{M}\vec{a}+\vec{D}G,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{SQL}=\sqrt{2\hbar m\Omega^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{'}$
\end_inset

 equal to? It is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $4\kappa/T$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:outputQuadratures_freeSpaceNoise"

\end_inset

, it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\frac{8I_{0}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 However, now, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 are inside the cavity (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tuned fabry perot noise"

\end_inset

).
 Inside the cavity, at steady state, there will be a very large power stored
 in the cavity: 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{c}=4I_{0}/T$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "rem:intracavity power LM T0"

\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\kappa^{'} & = & \frac{8I_{c}\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{8\left(4I_{0}/T\right)\omega_{0}}{mc^{2}\Omega^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{4\kappa}{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=\sqrt{R}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{b}\left(\Omega\right) & = & \mathbf{M}\left(\sqrt{R}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\vec{b}+\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{\alpha}\right)+\vec{D}G\\
\implies\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{b} & = & \mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{\theta}\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{D}G\\
\vec{b} & = & \left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{\theta}\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then, we use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}=\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\vec{b}-\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{\beta} & = & \sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\left\{ \left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{\theta}\sqrt{T}\vec{\alpha}+\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G\right\} -\sqrt{R}\vec{\alpha}\\
 & = & \left(T{\bf R}_{\theta}\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{\theta}-\sqrt{R}\right)\vec{\alpha}+\sqrt{T}{\bf R}_{\theta}\left(I-\mathbf{M}{\bf R}_{2\theta}\sqrt{R}\right)^{-1}\vec{D}G\\
 & \equiv & \mathbf{H}\vec{\alpha}+\vec{F}G.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

