\begin_layout Subsection
Uncertainty principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Energy phase uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are told that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E\Delta\phi\ge\hbar\omega/2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 is the uncertainty in the phase (e.g.
 section of 4.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

).
 The phase operator is not well defined in Quantum Mechanics.
 This relationship can be derived
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
in the context of a specific experiment (e.g.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:energy phase uncertainty simple example"

\end_inset

);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
from the energy/time uncertainty relation
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E\Delta t\geq\hbar/2$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi=\omega\Delta t$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
which comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $E\propto\cos\left(kr-\omega t\right)$
\end_inset

 so as time progresses an extra phase is introduced.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E\Delta\omega\ge\hbar\omega/2$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
by looking classically at the Fourier transform uncertainty relation that
 holds for light waves: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega\tau\gtrsim1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

 is the bandwith of the wave packet and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 its duration (Eq.
 1.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

).
 Then we use that the energy of a photon is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{photon}\tau\gtrsim\hbar$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, there will be an uncertainty in the energy of the photon: 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\hbar\bar{\omega}\pm\hbar/2\tau$
\end_inset

.
 And this is useful for understanding the following experimental preparation
 of a monophotonic state:
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename braginsky preparation monophotonic state.png
	lyxscale 80
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Experiments illustrating unavoidable noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two possible experiments are the Heisenberg microscope (Fig.
 1.4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

) and von Neumann's Doppler speed meter (Fig.
 1.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

).
 From these examples, the following lesson can be learned:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Despite the similar forms of the formulae 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\Delta p\gtrsim\hbar/2$
\end_inset

 [equation (1.10) for a monophotonic state [[i.e.
 standard uncertainty principle that we learn in class]]] and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{measure}\Delta p_{perturb}\gtrsim\hbar/2$
\end_inset

 [equation (1.13) for the Heisenberg microscope [[
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{measure}$
\end_inset

 is the uncertainty of the object's position that we would like to measure
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{perturb}$
\end_inset

 is a perturbation on the object's momentum]], their essences are fundamentally
 different.
 Equation (1.10) is a fundamental property of the physical state of a quantum
 object; in it the object's position and momentum have equal footing.
 According to it, a quantum object, independently of its prehistory (how
 its state was prepared) cannot have precisely defined values of its position
 and momentum simultaneously—and this is true in the same sense as a classical
 wave packet's inability to have simultaneous, precise values of its position
 and wave number (or frequency).
 By contrast, equation (1.13) is a fundamental property of the process of
 measurement; and the uncertainties in the object's position and momentum
 appear in it in different ways: the position uncertainty is an error in
 the measurement, the momentum uncertainty is a perturbation given to the
 object by the measuring process.
 Nevertheless, both equation (1.10) and equation (1.13) carry the name "Heisenberg
 uncertainty relation." 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In fact, the physical roots of the two relations (1.10) and (1.13) are the
 same (see chapters II and III and also the beginning of chapter V): From
 the fact that the state of the measuring device has unavoidable uncertainties
 described by (1.10), it follows that a measurement of the mass's position
 inevitably perturbs its momentum in the manner of (1.13) ...
 Conversely, the perturbation that inevitably accompanies any measurement
 prevents one from ever preparing a quantum object in a state with simultaneous,
 precise values of its position and momentum.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Fundamental-postulate-of-measurements"

\end_inset

Fundamental postulate of measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum measurements are described by a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ M_{m}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of measurement operators that reside in the same Hilbert space as the object
 that is being measured.
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 refers to the measurement outcomes that may occur in the experiment.
 If the state of the quantum system is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

 immediately before the measurement then the probability that result 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 occurs is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(m\right) & = & \braket{\psi|M_{m}^{\dagger}M_{m}|\psi}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and the state after the measurement is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\psi_{after}} & = & \frac{M_{m}\ket{\psi}}{\sqrt{p\left(m\right)}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and they satisfy the completeness equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}M_{m}^{\dagger}M_{m}=I$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum p\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The status of this Postulate as a fundamental postulate intrigues many people.
 Measuring devices are quantum mechanical systems, so the quantum system
 being measured and the measuring device together are part of a larger,
 isolated, quantum mechanical system.
 The evolution of this larger isolated system can be described by a unitary
 evolution.
 Might it be possible to derive the measurement postulate as a consequence
 of this picture? Despite considerable investigation along these lines there
 is still disagreement between physicists about whether or not this is possible.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (section 2.2.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nielsenQI"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:WFC"

\end_inset

Measurements and the wave function collapse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Intro to the concept of wave function collapse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See section 2.4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

 for a good formal introduction with connection to experiments (note that
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\lambda/\Delta y$
\end_inset

 equation at the bottom of page 26 is the result of single slit diffraction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Intro to Von Neumann postulate of reduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say we have an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

 and an initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

 then the 
\emph on
Von Neumann postulate
\emph default
 states (for a vanilla/simple projective measurement):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The probability of obtaining an eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}$
\end_inset

 of an eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{q_{n}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w_{n} & = & Tr\left[\ket{q_{n}}\bra{q_{n}}\hat{\rho}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After the measurement, the object collapses into the state 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho_{n} & = & \frac{1}{w_{n}}\ket{q_{n}}\braket{q_{n}|\hat{\rho}|q_{n}}\bra{q_{n}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in reality, there might be experimental impefections that complicate
 the situation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It is important to note that in many real measurements the final state of
 the object differs substantially from 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{q_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 A simple example is the measurement of the number of photons in an electromagne
tic resonator by absorbing them into a photodetector; in this example, the
 measurement leaves the resonator devoid of photons.
 This photon destruction is an example of the fact that a real measuring
 device can produce additional back-action effects on the measured object,
 above and beyond the fundamental back action demanded by the von Neumann
 postulate.
 Such additional back actions are not fundamental.
 In principle, they can be avoided.
 For example, in the case of a resonator one can measure the photons without
 absorption, von Neumann's postulate of reduction is restricted to ideal
 measurements in which all such avoidable back actions are excluded.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 2.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orthogonal/Projective Measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A measurement can be described by a set of operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \hat{E}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 that satisfy (i) 
\emph on
completeness
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}\hat{E}_{j}=\hat{I}$
\end_inset

 and (ii) 
\emph on
orthgonality
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}\hat{E}_{k}=\delta_{jk}\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The observable associated with such a measurement can be represented with
 the operator: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}=\sum q_{j}\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be interperted as the projector onto the eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}\hat{E}_{k}=\delta_{jk}\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 behaves like a projection operator with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}^{2}=E_{j}$
\end_inset

 just like an actual projector 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Von Neumann's principle becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The probability of obtaining the measurement result 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w_{n} & = & Tr\left[\hat{E}_{n}\hat{\rho}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

And so the expected values of the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle q^{n}\right\rangle =Tr\left[\hat{Q}^{n}\hat{\rho}\right]$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle q^{n}\right\rangle  & = & \sum w_{r}q_{r}^{n}\\
 & = & Tr\left[\sum q_{r}^{n}E_{r}\rho\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

now 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{n}=\sum q_{i_{1}}q_{i_{2}}...q_{i_{n}}E_{i_{1}}...E_{i_{n}}=\sum q_{r}^{n}E_{r}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}\hat{E}_{k}=\delta_{jk}\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After the measurement, the object collapses into the state 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{\rho}_{n} & = & \frac{1}{w_{n}}\hat{E}_{j}\hat{\rho}\hat{E}_{j}.\label{eq:orthogonal meas WFC}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of such a measurement (shown below) would the measurement of
 the position of a moving particle by use of a 'meter' divided into different
 cells and each of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q$
\end_inset

: we measure the position of the particle by checking in which cell it ends
 up in.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{E}_{j} & = & \int_{q_{j}}^{q_{j}+\Delta q}\ket{q}\bra{q}dq\label{eq:example orthogonal measurement}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the starting position of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th cell.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename temp2.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Measurement of the position of a particle
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Section 2.6 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

; also looked at section 2.2.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nielsenQI"

\end_inset

 which is more clearly written and organized with the rest of the measurement
 topics but not as physical)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Orthogonal (general) Measurements and POVMs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Orthogonal measurements are not the most general type of measurements*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A peculiar characteristic of orthogonal measurements is the discontinuous
 nature of the decomposition of unity (i.e.
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 that appears in the decomposition of unity is orthogonal to the other 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

) which can lead to discontinuous wave functions*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example we measure the position exactly leading to a collapse of the
 initial state to a delta function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is not always the case.
 Moreover, orthogonal measurements give full information about the quantity
 we are observing as repeating the exact same measurement reveals the exact
 same information.
 This is not always the case: some measurements if repeated reveal new informati
on (this is the case for measurements that do not perturb the observable
 being studied and that have an error associated with them: repeating the
 experiment improves the error of the experiment).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A more general set of measurement operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \hat{\Pi}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 only satisfies a decomposition of unity relation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\intop_{\left\{ \tilde{q}\right\} }\hat{\Pi}\left(\tilde{q}\right)d\tilde{q} & = & \hat{I},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{q}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the set of all possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 and can be a discrete/continuous scalar or a vector (if several observables
 are measured simultaneously)^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The decomposition into unity is necessary because we must have that the
 probibilities sum to 1
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The probability of obtaining a particular result is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & Tr\left(\hat{\Pi}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Pi}\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive (otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 cannot be interperted as a probability).
 This type of measurement might leave the object's state, after the measurement,
 
\emph on
undetermined
\emph default
 as sometimes we do not know all the details of the measurement process^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For us the most important feature of this general theory is the fact that
 it leaves the object's quantum state, after the measurement, undetermined.
 This is probably inevitable for so general a theory: to determine the object's
 final state in a realistic measurement, one must supply information about
 the details of the apparatus and measurement that probably are not fully
 incorporatable into the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Pi}\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In view of this, we shall now specialize our discussion to approximate
 measurements of a single observable, and shall expand it to include more
 information about the measurement than what is contained in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Pi}\left(q\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)$
\end_inset

 be the probability that the measuring device will report a value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 when the observable is in an eigenstate with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (for example in the case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example orthogonal measurement"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\left[\tilde{q},\tilde{q}+\Delta q\right]$
\end_inset

 and 0 otherwise).
 Then, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tilde{q}\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\rho\left(q\right)dq,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(q\right)=\braket{q|\hat{\rho}|q}$
\end_inset

 is the initial state's 
\emph on
a priori 
\emph default
probability distribution for the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
w\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & Tr\left[\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\right]\nonumber \\
\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\ket{q}w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\bra{q}dq\label{eq:expression non orthgonal measurement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and we also have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right),\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}^{'}\right)\right] & = & 0\quad\forall\tilde{q},\tilde{q}^{'}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\ket{q}w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\bra{q}dq$
\end_inset

 implies that all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

s are diagonal in the same representation.
 And a necessary and sufficient condition for a set of operators to commute
 is the possibility to diagonalize them all simultaneously in a common represent
ation (see section 2.3.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bellacQM"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)$
\end_inset

 is an indicator of the precision of the measurement process.
 (Section 2.7 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Wave function collapse
\emph default
: The state after the measurement will be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\rho}_{n} & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}\hat{\Omega}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger}\left(\tilde{q}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right)=\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\Omega}\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(\hat{\rho}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\right) & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}Tr\hat{\Omega}\hat{\rho}\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger}=1\\
\implies Tr\hat{\Omega}\hat{\rho}\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger} & = & Tr\left[\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\right]=Tr\left(\Omega^{\dagger}\Omega\rho\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cyclic permutation trace"

\end_inset

 and hence we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W & = & \Omega^{\dagger}\Omega
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Omega}\left(\tilde{q}\right)=\hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}$
\end_inset

 is a unitary operator*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\Omega}\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & W^{1/2}U^{\dagger}UW^{1/2}=W^{1/2}W^{1/2}\\
 & = & W
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expression non orthgonal measurement"

\end_inset

, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\ket{q}w^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\bra{q}dq
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Note that this does not contradict Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:orthogonal meas WFC"

\end_inset

 because for orthgonal measurements, we can pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Omega}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a projection and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}^{\dagger}E_{j}=E_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this more clearly, note that for a projective measurement 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}_{j}\hat{E}_{k}=\delta_{jk}\hat{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and so in addition we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}\Omega_{k}^{\dagger}\Omega_{k} & = & \delta_{jk}\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}\\
\implies\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j} & = & \Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}$
\end_inset

 is hermitian because in general a measurement operator is hermitian (
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{W}\left(\tilde{q}\right)=\hat{\Omega}^{\dagger}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\Omega}\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

) and so if try to pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=E$
\end_inset

 then we have that (since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}^{2}=E_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}^{\dagger}=E_{j}$
\end_inset

; both of which imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\dagger}\Omega=E$
\end_inset

) the above relation is satisfied: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}\Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}=E_{j} & = & \Omega_{j}^{\dagger}\Omega_{j}=E_{j}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=E$
\end_inset

 is a valid solution.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the transition from 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

 to the final state 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}_{f}$
\end_inset

 can be described by a 2 step process, where first we have a collapse
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\rho}_{f}^{'}\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

that is followed by a unitary transformation (from which we extract no new
 information^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 is unitary, it cannot change the object's entropy, and correspondingly,
 this step of the reduction is not accompanied by the experimenter's extraction
 of any new information
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\rho}_{f}\left(\tilde{q}\right) & = & \hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}_{f}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{U}^{\dagger}\left(\tilde{q}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This measurement scheme leaves the measured quantity unperturbed (if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right),\hat{q}\right]=0$
\end_inset

)^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "comment 1"

\end_inset

We should note that this general type of measurement leaves the value of
 the observable unchanged because: first calculate the probability of obtaining
 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 after a second measurement (in this analysis we will be ignoring the unitary
 transformation applied in the process of WFC)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(q\right) & = & \braket{q|\hat{\rho}_{f}^{'}\left(\tilde{q}\right)|q}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}\braket{q|\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right)\hat{\rho}\hat{W}^{1/2}\left(\tilde{q}\right)|q}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\sqrt{w\left(\tilde{q}|r\right)w\left(\tilde{q}|s\right)}\braket{q|r}\braket{r|\rho|s}\braket{s|q}drds\\
 & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\sqrt{w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)w\left(\tilde{q}|s\right)}\braket{q|\rho|s}\braket{s|q}ds\\
 & = & \frac{1}{w\left(\tilde{q}\right)}w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\braket{q|\rho|q}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int p\left(q\right)w\left(\tilde{q}\right)d\tilde{q} & = & \int w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)\braket{q|\rho|q}d\tilde{q}\\
 & = & \braket{q|\rho|q}\int w\left(\tilde{q}|q\right)d\tilde{q}\\
 & = & \braket{q|\rho|q}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
which means that probability is conserved: the expected value of the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 is the same as the initial propability to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

This step [[i.e.
 the first step: WFC]] leaves the measured value of the observable [[
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

]] unchanged: if it is applied to an ensemble of objects, then the probability
 distribution for the chosen observable after the measurements would be
 the same as before
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In addition, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right),\hat{q}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 then the whole measurement process does not perturb the measured quantity
 because then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\left(q\right) & = & \braket{q|\hat{\rho}_{f}^{'}\left(\tilde{q}\right)|q}=\braket{q|\hat{\rho}_{f}\left(\tilde{q}\right)|q}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{U}\left(\tilde{q}\right),\hat{q}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}$
\end_inset

 share the same eigenvectors and so 
\begin_inset Formula $U\ket{q}=\chi\ket{q}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is a complex number.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The observables that do not commute with the measured quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}$
\end_inset

 (for example its canonically conjugate operator's observable) will be perturbed
 by the measurement*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because then the derivation presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "comment 1"

\end_inset

 would not hold anymore.
 Particularly, for canonically conjugate variables we no longer have that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{q|p}\propto\delta\left(q-p\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
