\begin_layout Subsubsection
Comments on the interpertation of the postulate of wave function collapse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The impossibility of describing the quantum measurement process within the
 framework of the standard evolutionary apparatus of quantum mechanics can
 be traced to the fact that the receiver of the measurement's information
 is a macroscopic observer.
 The question of whether quantum mechanics can describe fully the macroscopic
 world is an open one, and is widely discussed by physicists and philosophers.
 One thing, however, is evident: The observer cannot even in principle write
 down a wave function for himself.
 To do so, it would be necessary to define the initial states of all the
 elementary particles from which the observer is made.
 However, the amount of information that the observer is able to comprehend
 is determined by the number of neurons in his brain (~ 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10}$
\end_inset

).
 This number is far smaller than the number of particles that make up his
 brain and body (after all, each neuron itself is made out of a large number
 of elementary particles), so he cannot possibly comprehend the content
 of a wave function that describes himself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, it would be incorrect to suppose that to analyze the
 procedure of measurements, one must always include explicitly the observer.
 In general, between the observer and the quantum object there is a so-called
 classical measuring device—an inanimate system with many degrees of freedom
 (~
\begin_inset Formula $10^{23}\gg10^{10}$
\end_inset

), which under the action of the measured quantum object irreversibly changes
 its own state in a manner that the observer can directly comprehend.
 Examples of such classical measuring devices are the photoemulsion of a
 photographic plate, the supersaturated steam in a Wilson cloud chamber,
 and the active medium in a quantum amplifier.
 There is even an example in which the device was the human eye: Pavel Cerenkov'
s discovery of Cerenkov radiation in which he detected individual photons
 directly with his eyes.
 Thermodynamics tells us that all these complicated, classical measuring
 devices are irreversible, and the detailed motions of their constituent
 particles are unpredictable.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BraginskyQM"

\end_inset

 section 3.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Useful Identities/theorems, etc ...
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:QMequs"

\end_inset

Quantum Mechanics useful identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamentals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\hat{X},\hat{P}\right]=i\hbar\hat{I},\label{eq:commutationXP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\hat{P},\hat{X}\right]=-i\hbar\hat{I}.\label{eq:commutationPX}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Heisenberg equations of motion are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}A=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H,A\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Operator Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Useful trace relations
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\ket A\bra B\hat{O} & = & \braket{A|B}{}\\
Tr\left(\ket A\bra B\hat{O}\right) & = & \braket{B|\hat{O}|A}{}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(\ket{A}\bra{B}\right) & = & \sum_{n}\braket{n|A}\braket{B|n}\\
 & = & \sum_{n}\braket{B|n}\braket{n|A}\\
 & = & \bra{B}\left(\sum_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}\right)\ket{A}\\
 & = & \braket{B|A}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(\ket{A}\bra{B}\hat{O}\right) & = & \sum_{n}\braket{n|A}\braket{B|\hat{O}|n}\\
 & = & \sum_{n}\braket{B|\hat{O}|n}\braket{n|A}\\
 & = & \bra{B}\hat{O}\left(\sum_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}\right)\ket{A}\\
 & = & \braket{B|\hat{O}|A}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
and that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Tr\left(ABC\right) & = & Tr\left(BCA\right)=Tr\left(CAB\right)\label{eq:cyclic permutation trace}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Eq.
 2.49 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bellacQM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
