\begin_layout Chapter
Approximations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Narrowband-approximation"

\end_inset

Narrowband approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This involves making the approximation that the quantity we are interested
 in studying is narrowly centered around a certain frequency: 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This approximation has been used in the following instances:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Replacing some function of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\omega_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

; This has been used in the following ways:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 in the expansion of the quantized electric field (see Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Qemrelations"

\end_inset

) is replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, which is the characteristic frequency of the electric field (e.g.
 the central frequency of a laser).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "integral approximation 1"

\end_inset

: The integrand 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

 is replaced with a Taylor series centered around the center frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(In the context of an integral), replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 with infinity; This has been used in the following ways:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "narrowbandNote1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Integral approximations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing an exact function with its taylor series (this can be used in
 the context of a narrowband approximation: replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\omega_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

; see sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Narrowband-approximation"

\end_inset

) or other examples: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "integral approximation 1"

\end_inset

 where the integrand is replaced with its Taylor series.
\end_layout

